    'body' => 'On Mon, 1 Jan 1996 12:58:59 -0500 you wrote:

>> I\'m getting ready to start a TNE based PBEM game set in the
>> middle of *a* Long Night (as opposed to *the Long Night <g>).
-

>> I\'m also running a Traveller-based Star Trek PBEM game.

>I would be very interested in the details of how you run a
>Traveller PBEM (Play by E-Mail?) game.  I have many of the original
>books from the game but scant opportunity to play.  Could you help?

There are tons of Play By E-Mail games running.  Some are on the
internet, some are on networks (like Fidonet, Tagnet or VNet),
and some are run on local BBS\'s.  If you are in an area where
there aren\'t too many opportunities to play live or you\'re on a
strange work schedule like me they can be great.

I\'m involved in several pbem games, and I can say three things
about them:

1. They *eat* your time! <g>;
2. They are lot\'s of fun;
3. They demand tons of patience.

To find more info on playing games by email drop by
http://www.pbem.com/pbem-page.html sometime.  That\'s PBEM.Com\'s
front page on the web.  They have lots of info on email games.
They will advertise your game, even set you up with a mailing
list if you ask.  They only charge a fee for games that charge
fees, IOW free game/no fee, paid game/you pay a fee.  I think
that\'s extremely fair!

If you have access to a VNet or Fido BBS, you can check the echos
there for information.  Fido has 3 very active rpg echos STARTREK
and STARTREK_RPG for Startrek based games, and SF&ANIMI_RPG for
all other science fiction rpgs.

The Trav-based ST game I\'m running is on the net..private email.
It\'s set about 40 years before the original series, just after
the Feds run into the Klingons.  The players are the Officers
aboard a scout ship sent to gather intelligence in an unexplored
sector that *might* be Klingon infested.  The ship\'s just about
to leave Starbase 6 and sail into the unknown.  It\'s been at that
point for over a month...here\'s where patience comes in
<g>...waiting for all the players to send in their moves and
such.  We\'ll do 2 - 3 turns a month once we get going.  I\'ve been
in email games that do 2-3 a week, but that will burn your
players (and GM) out if you keep it up for too long.

I\'m GMing a Twilight 2000 game on VNet. That one is averaging 2
to 3 turns a month.  That\'s about right for a fido-style network,
I think.

The Traveller game I\'m getting ready to run will be on fidonet in
the SF&ANIME_RPG echo...if I get permission from the moderator
that is.  <g> The players will be merchants/explorers/spies
working the frontiers (and beyond) of a pocket empire.  There
will be several other multi-system powers in the area to compete
with, as well as independent systems, pirates, and huge
unexplored areas.  A good bit of the characters\' business will be
commissions from their government to do undercover work.

Now, how do you do it?

1.  Find a game and play.

Check the newsgroups, pbem.com, this echo, fido/vnet/tagnet,
aol/cserve.  Find a game that looks interesting and ask the GM
(or moderator) if you can play.  If you *like* playing by mail,
then you might like GMing by mail.

2.  Prepare a game.

It seems to work best to keep everything as simple as possible.
Don\'t expect everyone to have a copy of the rules, so simplify
them and prepare posts to send out on how things work.  I hide
the rules as much as possible from the players.  I roll the dice
,usually, (when I want the players to participate in the rolls I
tell them to give me several numbers picked at random between x
and y, then I modify their "rolls" with rolls of my own),
generally I let the players concentrate on role-playing (as
opposed to roll-playing <g>).  Beyond that, do the stuff you\'d do
for a face-to-face game.

3.  Find some players.

Get on the fido style echos and lurk.  Decide who you\'d like to
invite to play in your game, and invite them.  It helps if they
know something about *you* before you invite them, so you
probably should do more than lurk, try you hand at playing.  Put
messages into a mailing list (like this one), in an appropriate
newsgroup (rec.games.frp.misc), and/or on www pages.

3.  Create some characters.

I tend to send out simplified forms with choices for the players.
They make choices, rank order lists of things from most important
for their character to least important, what skills they are best
at/worst at, things like that.  Sometimes all I get is a
narrative description of their character.  Then I roll their
characters up, describe the character to them in a post, and we
negotiate from there.  <g> I seldom give the player their stats
only in raw numbers, many of them don\'t have any idea what a 8 in
STR means.  <g> What I do is describe them.."You have above
average strength, superior intelligence, and extraordinary
dexterity."... and so on.

4.  Run the game.

I post a description of what\'s going on to a player.  They write
back with what they want to *try* to do.  If several players are
together they get one post (and maybe private ones too <g>), they
can exchange posts discussing what to do and then reply with
their move, and/or tell me what they try to do individually.  I
read their posts, organize them based on initiative, do any
rolling I need to do, and send them responses.  Sort of like what
we do in a face to face game, right?  <g> It just goes *much*
slower!

BTW, I\'ve found that when you get to bang-bang situations (combat
for example) you have to give the players *reasonable* deadlines
and stick to them.  If a player doesn\'t get his/her turn in then
the GM will NPC their actions.  Tell the players you\'re going to
do it up front, and give them the benefit of all doubts when you
do, but do it.  It keeps the game moving and nobody feels totally
left out.  I also make them give me *timed* moves (what do you
try to do during the next 5 seconds, or 10 seconds, or few
minutes depending on the situation) for actions where time is a
real factor..again combat is a good example, but so is picking a
lock before the guard gets back or locking onto the correct exit
point before the jump field collapses.

In the first pbem game I ran, I had one player whose mail *always*
arrived a couple of days after everyone else.  I wasn\'t using
*reasonable* deadlines yet, and I\'d respond to the other players
moves before my late player got his move in..so his move was
always getting stomped on.  It upset him..and me too!  I know
it\'s frustrating for players with fast mail to have to wait for
the players with slow mail, but again that\'s where patience comes
in. <g>

5.  Post regular Update Messages.

I learned this trick from Aron Head.  Every week post a
standardized information post to all the players.  Include in it
things like:  a roster of players, characters and addresses;
what everybody\'s character has been up to; what you expect
to be happening in the game during the next week; any news
about deadlines, changes of addresses, new players, etc.  Doing
this keeps the players up to date and involved even when they
haven\'t been doing much individually, so they don\'t all drift
away.  This is also where I warn players that they are in danger
of begin dropped from the game.

6.  Don\'t expect it to run forever or be problem free.

People move, get married, graduate, lose access, and just plain
drop out. Expect it, roll with it, and be prepared to bring new
people in. If you take on a player that\'s bringing it down for everybody
else..or that *you* can\'t stand..drop them.  It\'s tough, but do
it.  And, if it stops being fun for you, bring the scenario to
an end, and end the game.  You can always work up something else
and, armed with your experience, try again.

7.  Finally..just have fun! <g>

Eris Reddoch
ereddoch@amaranth.com


