    'from' => 'Steven Bonneville bonnevil@itlabs.umn.ed',
    'body' => 'Aaron DaMommio <aarond@pencom.com> wrote:

>What is harder to explain is how the Imperium has lagged at TL15 for so long,
>after earlier climbs. I guess a basic Traveller premise is that technological
>change is not steady-and-upward, but that it can level off.
>
>I don\'t really have trouble believing in a universe that is stagnating. It\'s
>just that it seems like the Imperium is a culture that would be continuing to
>progress technologically, and I don\'t see why it has hovered so long at and
>near 15.

The Third Imperium was advancing fairly rapidly, up to MegaTraveller, and
the rate of progress was accelerating.  The Terran Confederation had
achieved tech-12 by the Ninth Interstellar War, but the problems of the
Rule of Man trying to prop up the collapsing Vilani society stopped any
further advancement in Imperial Space until after the Long Night.  The
Sylean Federation had tech-12 at the founding of the Imperium, and things
took off after that.  The Imperium was considered tech-13 by 300, and the
xboat system was nearly state-of-the-art when construction began.  It
had tech-14 by 700, and tech-15 by 1000.  Considering all the tech-16
worlds popping up in the Core, tech-16 by 1250 or so might have been
reasonable -- before the Second Civil War.

Hyphen <library@babylon5.dss.gov.au> wrote:

>2. When the Marches was published, GDW decided that TL 13 was "average Imperial
>tech level" - it was the TL 15 planets that were anomalies.

Actually, this is still statistically true for the majority of the Imperial
population, pre-Collapse.  Averaging tech level of worlds, weighted by the
world population, you get about tech 12-13.  Some sectors are more or less
advanced than others.  I suppose you could say that there\'s an "average"
Imperial tech-level and a higher number that is the maximum commonly in use.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonnevil@itlabs.umn.edu>

