    'topic' => 'tech levels',
    'body' => 'Hans,

I think it is a real mistake to assume that because components of a thing
exist at a certain tech level, products that require a combination of those
same things should be available at that same level.

e.g.

>>Communication: Writing, signal fire.
>
>Writing is another one of those crafts that only need a stick and dirt (Or
>stone and chisel or wood and knife or...)

Sticks, dirt are available at any tech level.  However, writing, requires
someone to have an interest in preserving knowledge past tomorrow and
coming up with a writing convention.  This argues for writing to be available
in an age where the inmediate concern is not simply surviving past today.
You could make an argument for pictographs to be accepted as writing,
a need to express oneself and using materials at hand (variously colored
dirts, chalks, soot and naturally occuring cavewalls).  Writing also seems
to argue the necessity  of a society that is larger than the single family unit
or the clan that one belongs to.  In other words, if what you are defining
as writing that of a set vocabulary, with specific symbols that represent those
concepts then you must have a society that shares those symbols as a
necessary condition for writing to occur.

This does not happen at TL 0.

The same with surgery.  The argument that surgery could occur as soon as
sentients can wield a knife is a simplistic one.  One can open a body up with
something as crude as a rock, a sharpened stick or something as advanced
as a chainsaw.  The point is that the person doing the cutting has to have
developed the idea that cutting into the sentient under the saw will produce
the effect of curing the patient.  For that to happen, a good deal of time and
advances have been made between the time they first cut into each other,
the original purpose being to kill...

>>Transporation: Horses with saddle and stirrups, ships.
>
>Stirrups needs metal-working - TL 1.

They also need some understanding of tanning, horse training and the abilty
to put the three together...

Tech levels are s synergistic event.  To say that the only thing that is needed
is the essential building blocks for the subcomponents is, IMHO, a flawed
argument.

We understand in a theoretical manner what superconductors can do for us,
we have the materials knowledge somewhere to put them together, we know
about transmission of power and the essentials of physics to make it happen,
but we have not because we have not hit on the right combination.  That might
take something else htat helps us bring the entire package together.

>Gunpowder itself is TL 0, of course, but cannon needs some good knowledge
>of metalworking.

And chemistry, or alchemism...



Thor Christensen

