    'id' => '<6JN6gD1w165w@krypton.rain.com>',
    'ts-index' => '1996-01-03.ac259',
    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> writes:

> Stefan Matthias Aust wrote some very interesting things about tech levels.
> However, for Traveller purposes he makes the same mistake that GDW made of
> linking TLs to specific time periods in the history of one single planet.
> That some things appeared at a particular point in Earth history is simply
> a matter of historical chance. Some things could have appeared much earlier
> or much later.

I\'ve thought for *decades* that a very useful project would be sitting
down and trying to produce a set of "books" detailing how to go from
"nothing" (ie you and the books) to any desired piece of contemporary
technology. A side benifit of such would be that you could classify
tech levels in terms of how many stages of "tools to build the tools to
build the tools..." you have to go thru.

> My favourite example is the medical technology of surgery. All you really
> need to make surgery work is a sharp knife _and the knowledge to keep the
> wound sterile_. On Earth germs weren\'t discovered until the microscope, a
> TL 4 device, was invented. Hence GDW and Matthias classifies surgery as a
> level 4 technology. But if you knew about germs - if someone from another
> planet had told you (or if some stone age genius had deduced the way germs
> _work_ even if he didn\'t have a clue why it worked that way) - all you
> really needed would be a knife and boiling water. Hence _I_ classify
> surgery as a level 1 technology.

And history bears you out. There is ample evidence of surgery of *some*
sorts being done with limited success even by neolithic peoples.
Trephanation, for example (cutting a hole in the skull to release
spirits).

> >TECH LEVELS
> >
> >TL0 - Stone Age (-3000 TT)
>
> Egypt was flourishing in 3000 BC.

Believe it or not, Egypt in the earlier dynasties is classified as a
Neolithic culture!

> >Weapon Tech: Stone melee weapons, throwing weapons, bows.
> >Medical Science: Not existant.
>
> Curative herbs is available at the lowest tech level.

But to an extremely variable extent.

> >Mathematics: Not existant.
>
> All you need for mathematics is a stick and some dirt. (Hides and charcoal
> is a sophisticated variant ;-)

But the *idea* of even arithmetic has to be *invented*. It was a major
discovery that you could "count" things by using a pebble to represent
each item. So if you come back later and there are fewer items than
there are pebbles in your pouch, you know that someone took one.

This seems obvious to *us*, but it is a major invention. Numbers come
much later, as do things like addition and subtraction.

> >TL1 - Age of Early Civilization (-3000- -400 TT)

> >Transportation: Horses, costal ships or boats.

> Horses can\'t be used at TL 0?

Domesticating animals is another major invention. :-)

> >Communication: Writing, signal fire.
>
> Writing is another one of those crafts that only need a stick and dirt (Or
> stone and chisel or wood and knife or...)

But the *idea* is a major step forward.

> >Mathematics: Basic geometry, astronomy
>
> See above.

Again, both are *major* advances.

> >TL2 - Era of the Roman Empire (-400-500 TT)
> >
> >Empire building is the key event to classify a civilization as TL2.
>
> So Egypt was TL 2?

Egypt didn\'t really *have* an "empire" until quite late. They were
quite busy with the two kingdoms.

> >Advances in military tech, art and architecture.
>
> >Coinage,
>
> Coinage needs metal-working - TL 1.

But the idea of *money* is another major concept.

> >written history,
>
> TL 0. And not even just in theory. Remember the Babylonian clay tablets.

Babylon is several steps above "stone age".

> >glass
>
> Glass needs fire and sand - TL 0.

I\'d make it at least TL 1, as it requires several "steps" up from
"naked savage". Even the *earlist* glass requires more than just fire
and sand. You need soda and lime too. Without those, you won\'t get the
sand to melt at any sort of reasonable temp. Limestone is easy. "soda"
is not found laying around. You either mine it in the few areas where
deposits occur, or you *make* it, starting with things like seaweed.

> >Transporation: Horses with saddle and stirrups, ships.
>
> Stirrups needs metal-working - TL 1.

First you need the idea of domesticating animals, then you need the
idea of a way to stay on better.

If you are trying to "uplift" natives, you *will* have to teach them
the ideas in that order.

> >Communication: Paper.
>
> As opposed to papyrus? Vellum? What does it take to make paper in quantity?
> I\'ll have to look that up.

Paper is a pain, and one of the *requirements* is wire screens. That
means you need high grade metal (to make decent wires) and the ability
to draw wire somewhat reliably. Papyrus isn\'t too bad. Vellum requires
domesticated animals, and *good* tanning processes.

> >Inventions are porcelain,
>
> Now there\'s something I don\'t know too much about. I thought porcelain was
> just a fancy type of pottery.

Nope. Porcelain is *qualitatively* different from pottery. And it
requires *much* higher temperatures as well as considerably better
quality raw materials.

> >optical laws, archs (architecture), compass, spectacles, mirrors, clocks.

> Archs were used by the Romans, optical laws, spectacles and mirrors only
> need glass to work (Well, mirrors only need smooth metal), clocks are
> highly complex devices that need fine metalworking. Is fine metalworking
> a higher TL than ordinary metalworking? I\'m inclined to say so, but I can\'t
> really back it up.

The *true* arch came to the Romans fairly late as I recall. Glass
suitable for *any* sort of optical use is several steps up from the
"mix sand, soda, and lime then heat well" type of glass. Metalworking
has *lots* of stages.

> Gunpowder itself is TL 0, of course, but cannon needs some good knowledge
> of metalworking.

Sorry, gunpowder requires some "chemical" processing. At the very least
it requires mixing containers that are *not* stone, and shouldn\'t be
pottery. (I could send you a file on how to make saltpeter, It requires
*boiling* large amounts of liquid for *extended* periods)

While it is true that there *are* a lot of things you could get a TL-0
savage to do for you, to get them to do them for *themselves* requires
a few steps. While Stefan may have been rather pessimistic, you are
*way* too optimistic.

Reading up on the history of science and technology can be *very*
eye-opening.

Leonard Erickson           leonard@
(aka Shadow)    shadow@ (preferred)
