I think your rebuttal is viable but misguided.  Statements like,
[paraphrasing] "it only takes a stick and dirt to write, TL 0,";  "stirrups
require metallurgy, TL1";  or "it only takes a copy of Gray\'s anatomy to be
given to someone...".  All of these type of statements violate a basic rule of
technological advancement, stepwise increase.  A common language and symbol
system must be agreed upon before a stick and dirt will suffice.  Metallurgy
(beyond copper which is too soft for stirrups), Animal husbandry/training (ie
"horse" riding), and an advanced concept of animal control (more than hopping
on an animal to get from A to B, ie saddle, bridle, etc) all of these items are
prerequisites to the stirrup concept.  One exception to this might be a culture
(such as the tribal Mongol hordes) might devlop these things sooner.  The
suggestion of any introduction of advanced tech level, Gray\'s Anatomy is at
least TL 5, is an automatic bias.  Any person in any previous time period who
has access to advanced TL would be considered that TL in that area.  In other
words, a TL0 society with one individual (or culture) possesing TL5 medicine.

It would seem that the TL system should be applied by type of science, but this
has two major flaws.  One is the interdependency of most sciences.  The other
being practicality of use within a game system.  Like any other FRPG, Traveller
requires players to suspend reality in some measure for the sake of game play
and enjoyment.  I frequently have to remind players of this fact (as I myself
am often reminded).  Traveller is designed to have a variegated universe to
keep every place from being the same.

