> Actually, it\'s hard to understand how interstellar trade makes much sense.
> Much of the CT material has things like wine and exotic meats being traded
> around (I\'m specifically thinking of The Traveller Adventure) and that doesn\'t
> make much sense to me. However, in play I don\'t think I\'d much want to call
> that into question. If anyone wants to rattle off a justification for this,
> I\'d be interested to read it. I think a universe in which few goods but lots
> of info are moved around makes more sense as an actual extrapolation of our
> present, but when it comes to a game milieu, I\'d hate to give up Free Traders
> and the adventuring opportunities they provide.
>
> --Aaron
>
There\'s excellent historical precedent.  All over the ancient and medieval
world, traders tromped huge distances, undergoing great danger and effort,
to bring luxury goods from the elite of one area to another.  Don\'t know why,
exactly, but it seems a fundamental fact of human nature that when you get
rich, you simply *must* have that lovely vase/rug/wine/spice/whatever from
halfway across the world.  And when the exotic goods you can get are actually
from another _planet_ - so much the better!

I really would like to get more source material on trade, too.  An expanded
and more detailed list would be cool.  One idea:

pets - craze for particularly lovable animals from planet X could go to
       extremes - (possibly endangering the native population?)

Anybody want to start putting together an idea database for trade?
