    'from' => 'Michael.Barry@FINANCE.ausgovfinance.tele',
    'body' => '     I have been lurking around the Tech Levels discussion with considerable
     interest. A real-life (!) example of low-tech manufacturing can be seen in
     northern Pakistan, near the Afghanistan border. In the town of Dhurra, the
     main industry is producing handmade copies of firearms, using pretty
     rudimentary techniques eg machining rifle barrels from steel reinforcing
     rods and making other bits from metal scrap, wood and so on.

     Primitive weapons, I hear you say? Apparently, many of these copies are not
     only more reliable and accurate than the originals (AK-74s, automatic
     pistols, semiauto rifles, etc) but they also cost about a quarter as much.
     The only difference in appearance is that the copies have no serial
     numbers, manufacturers\' stamps and the like - although I\'m sure they could
     add these at a reasonable price!

     Your average Afghan or Kashmiri rebel can now get their hands on a great
     deal of sophisticated weaponry with little effort or technology at all -
     what is needed is weapons to be copied: something that the Third Imperium
     has no shortage of.

     Add to this the quantities of ex-Soviet, Czech and East German accessories
     floating about today (eg night vision gear, telescopic sights, laser sights
     - a nice little man in Smolensk tried to sell me all this stuff in early
     1994) and you have all the toys for a very interesting war.

     Could this be the situation in parts of the Third Imperium? Is this
     necessarily the case only with weapons? If people want something badly
     enough, they\'ll find a way to get it.
