    'index' => 'ac271',
    'body' => 'In xboat 489, Aaron DaMommio <aarond@pswtech.com> said:

>Actually, it\'s hard to understand how interstellar trade makes much sense.
>Much of the CT material has things like wine and exotic meats being traded
>around (I\'m specifically thinking of The Traveller Adventure) and that doesn\'t
>make much sense to me... If anyone wants to rattle off a justification...

Ok, here goes. Very briefly, I think too often it is assumed that all worlds
have the facilities and climate to grow just about anything - animal or
vegetable. Clearly this is not the case. An awful lot of \'planets\' are
actually asteroids, sun-burned balls of rock or frozen balls of rock in
vacuum. Although hydroponics, etc. could make up for this to a degree, it
would be the mass foodstuffs that are produced, with no space for, say, fine
wine grapes or free range chickens! Using valuable heat, light, oxygen and
food for growing meat cattle, etc. is VERY expensive - remember that farmers
on Earth get most of that lot for free! Even if the grapes were squeezed in,
you\'d always have someone saying that the wine lacked \'terroir\' (I think
that\'s spelt right? - i.e. the actual ground, natural sun, etc. give each
growing region it\'s own particular taste).

Okay, so I think there\'s a clear justification for bulk imports of many
foodstuffs. On particularly barren planets even basics such as grain might
be needed.

Population. Another big point to consider. If you have only 10 or 100 people
on a world (some Traveller worlds are fairly sparsely populated) then they
won\'t be producing food if there is some other factor taking up their lives
e.g. the starport is rated A it probably means most of them work there, or
they have TL15, in which case most are perhaps research staff or a
corporation site producing a specific high-tech component. This leaves
little time to worry about producing food and certainly does not allow the
production of all the basic materials required to sustain any society above
(approx) TL3. All those minerals that need mining, ores to be smelted,
petrochemicals for plastics, semiconductors... and then all that lot has to
be made into the telephones, televisions, computers, cars, etc. that make
life as we know it. Just imagine the complexities required to sustain TL10,
13 or 15! Some planets might even have a scarcity of particular minerals and
ores, making the first step impossible.

All these factors lead to any world of less than about pop level 6-7 being
(typically) highly dependent on other worlds for a huge variety of raw
materials and processed goods.

Now, Traveller falls down in 2 respects here:

Firstly it never really mentions the sort of bulk (megatons) carriers
required to make it economic to transport all the low price/low profit goods
critical to a planet\'s subsistence.

Secondly, when you expand systems using Scouts, WBH or the like, you may
suddenly find a range of other planets in system, some of which are perhaps
more suitable for growing food, or which might have the ores the main planet
doesn\'t have, etc. etc. Given a fully populated system, you can reduce the
inter-system traffic and get more of the raw materials in-system, i.e. you
get quite a bit of in-system bulk carrier traffic as well - suddenly the
bulk carriers become a lot more profitable, or you can use sling-shots or
mass-drivers to propel goods through the system!

I think this philosophy might help to justify all the trade goods given in
the CT and MT rules. One might ask why very small traders (Far, Free or Sub.
Merchants) are given cargoes of a few tons of worked metal. Okay, don\'t
regard this as just any old sheet metal - this is the 98652-A-TY bracket
required for high-stress low-pressure welding seals: 5 tons is a lot of
brackets and the destination world only needs a few thousand... 5 tons of
raw ore? Well, that\'s more difficult to justify, but perhaps it\'s because
there\'s a samurai sword maker on the destination world who insists on
refining his own metals? 5 tons of electronics? Easy - Mk 235 \'Talkie\'
Toasters - no one makes these on the destination world because of the
interstellar patent coverage purchased by the EatLots Toaster company... or
perhaps the 5 tons is computer parts for your pop 5 destination world. That
world might be marked TL13 for all I care, but no world with only a few tens
of thousands of people on it (even given robot support) will be able to
support a complete computer-construction industry from sand to working
boxes... PLUS all the other food and basic stuff-of-life production. At TL14
or 15 maybe robotics really do allow much more automation, but at lower TLs
you will always require sentient supervision which ties up people...

Also:
>>Another way to improve a TL description of a world would be to list different
>>levels for different areas of technology-- Medical TL 10, Military TL 13...
And Dave Golden said:
>        Ever see the World Builders Handbook? That was one of the
>innovations I really applauded.

Most definitely. Worth getting your hands on a copy of it, or its CT
predecessor Grand Census - or was that Grand Survey? I\'ll check...

Hope this is useful to someone...

Andy

P.S. Almost forgot. After all the \'logical\' arguments above, there will
still always be the nutters who are willing to pay interstellar shipment of
Beaujolais Nouveau or somesuch!!!

