    'topic' => ' TL and all that Jazz',
    'body' => '

On Thu, 4 Jan 1996, lots of people wrote:

>
> Sticks, dirt are available at any tech level.  However, writing, requires
> someone to have an interest in preserving knowledge past tomorrow and
> coming up with a writing convention.  This argues for writing to be available
> in an age where the inmediate concern is not simply surviving past today.

Quite

> This does not happen at TL 0.
>
> The same with surgery.  The argument that surgery could occur as soon as
> sentients can wield a knife is a simplistic one.  One can open a body up with
> something as crude as a rock, a sharpened stick or something as advanced
> as a chainsaw.  The point is that the person doing the cutting has to have
> developed the idea that cutting into the sentient under the saw will produce
> the effect of curing the patient.  For that to happen, a good deal of time and
> advances have been made between the time they first cut into each other,
> the original purpose being to kill...

It takes more than a sharp knife and hot water to perform useful
surgery. You need to know the role of the various organs, understand the
circulation of the blood, and have a clear idea concerning the effects of
the process.

It\'s all very well to talk about implementation TL vs discovery TL, but
the fact remains that in the REAL WORLD (Tm), we have approx TL 8-9 in
the West, and TL3-5 in the Developing World. Sure, they know all about
germs and infection - we\'ve told them all about it. It doesn\'t stop
malaria being the biggest killer in Africa and the Far East (close to 1m
deaths per year in Africa alone).

> Tech levels are s synergistic event.  To say that the only thing that is 
needed
> is the essential building blocks for the subcomponents is, IMHO, a flawed
> argument.

Exactly

> We understand in a theoretical manner what superconductors can do for us,
> we have the materials knowledge somewhere to put them together, we know
> about transmission of power and the essentials of physics to make it happen,
> but we have not because we have not hit on the right combination.  That might
> take something else htat helps us bring the entire package together.

Good example

> Another way to improve a TL description of a world would be to list different
> levels for different areas of technology-- Medical TL 10, Military TL 13, and
> Transportation TL 11, for example. Or you could write anywhere from a
> paragraph to a page describing the technologies available to a culture. If you
> use the TL concept, it\'s got to be recognized as a shortcut.

This has been done - see the RICE papers

> Knowledge would be the cheapest thing to transport.
> Actually, it\'s hard to understand how interstellar trade makes much sense.
> Much of the CT material has things like wine and exotic meats being traded
> around (I\'m specifically thinking of The Traveller Adventure) and that doesn\'t
> make much sense to me. However, in play I don\'t think I\'d much want to call
> that into question. If anyone wants to rattle off a justification for this,
> I\'d be interested to read it. I think a universe in which few goods but lots
> of info are moved around makes more sense as an actual extrapolation of our
> present, but when it comes to a game milieu, I\'d hate to give up Free Traders
> and the adventuring opportunities they provide.

Knowledge is a VERY difficult thing to copyright, as publishers are now
finding with the popularisation of the Internet. Ideas are the most freely
transmittable goods of all. IMHO, you can tell somebody how to make good
claret until you are blue in the face, but you\'ll never get the real
thing (Hello California!). Those Zillan Eisweins are here to stay.

> Believe it or not, Egypt in the earlier dynasties is classified as a
> Neolithic culture!

And why not - they hadn\'t even invented the wheel!

> > All you need for mathematics is a stick and some dirt. (Hides and charcoal
> > is a sophisticated variant ;-)
>
> But the *idea* of even arithmetic has to be *invented*. It was a major
> discovery that you could "count" things by using a pebble to represent
> each item. So if you come back later and there are fewer items than
> there are pebbles in your pouch, you know that someone took one.

Exactly - its bollox to say that all you need to use mathematics is a
stick and some dirt. Give someone a calculator and watch them try calculus.

> > >TL1 - Age of Early Civilization (-3000- -400 TT)
>
> > >Transportation: Horses, costal ships or boats.
>
> > Horses can\'t be used at TL 0?
>
> Domesticating animals is another major invention. :-)

Didn\'t BEGIN to happen until approx 8000 BC. A lot sooner than many think.

> > >Empire building is the key event to classify a civilization as TL2.

Why do you have to bulid an empire to be technically advanced?

> Babylon is several steps above "stone age".

Many steps (Early Stone Age began circa 2 million years ago with H.erectus)

Lots of other good points deleted for space :)

Jules
