    'from' => 'Simon.Harding@vuw.ac.nz',
    'body' => 'I have often considered it a major playability failing of Imperium Traveller
that there existed worlds that had interstellar contact (in the sense that
they had a starport of a reasonable rating) yet had very low tech levels. I
found it difficult to beleive that the technology involved in the starport
could be kept hidden from the surrounding world. The question always
followed that if they were able to hide the technology, why would they do
so? what possible purpose would it serve, for either the starport operators
or the travellers?
Some conspiracy theorists might argue that such a condition exists on Earth
today, with hidden landings of ET vehicles at top top secret facilities in
New Mexico or some such for the purpose of gradual transfer of technology.
Maybe Einstein did complete his unified field equations and they released
the secret of interstellar travel to a few able to realise their practical
potential but have been suppressed because of the destructive horrors they
also promised.
However, starports in Traveller aren\'t made out to be like secure facilities
hidden in the frozen polar wastes or anything like that. Traveller starports
are normally and most usually (correct me if I am wrong) more like Moss
Isley of Star War or as Whangaparoa was to early New Zealand.
In my Traveller universe TL is more an indication of indigenous productive
ability rather than availability. For example TL 10 doesn\'t mean there is
nobody walking around or operating on that world with TL15 equipment ofr
facilities, it just means that the world has to import any products over
TL10. ie there is no indigenous PGMP and no locally designed and
manufactured Battledress. TL then is a good approximation of availability.
No doubt this is way many of you also referee your games. I still have
problems with justifying it sometimes. One would expect the gap in TL
between the world and the imperial norm to close very quickly once contact
had been made, especially for resource rich worlds.

Simon Harding
Administrative Assistant
Graduate Students Office









