    'body' => 'Hi there

Someone has already mentioned my trade pages, but I\'ll advertise them again:

URL http://www.jb.man.ac.uk/~spe/Rules/Trade/Trade.html

These are a hypertexted version of the rules I use for my Traveller
game.  I\'ve just realised that the all important tables are missing,
because hypertexting them was a pain.  These rules are based on the
Merchant Prince/MT trade rules, plus expansion rules from a Challenge
supplement.  I use the MT rules to determine the relative price of goods
between a gven source and a given destination.  As someone pointed out,
this doesn\'t work v well as a carrying trade goods from one world to
another gives you a similar price regardless of what they are.  The only
variation in price comes from the table at the end of selling; buying
price is absolutely fixed.  In addition, cargoes are given exciting
titles such as C-E Cr 3400 NiAg 540 kl.

I\'ve introduced tables (which I\'ve missed out of the hypertext pages
--sorry)  which allow me to roll up cargo types in a range of about 40
different types (eg. Meat, grain, livestock, electronics).  Someone
pointed out that it is ludicrous to reduce all possible commodities to a
small number of categories; however, it is the only way to get variety
and still provide tables to aid the imagination -- if you want "pets" as
suggested in an earlier xboat, then just say your next livestock cargo
consists of such pets.  That is the variety in types dealt with.
However, variety in type also results in a variety in price: Under
textiles, silk commands a higher price than sackcloth.  Thus, I have a
Quality modifier, based on the cargo type (again, these are in the
missing tables), which is multiplied by the base cost, and so represents
the range of different values which the different varieties of a given
cargo type can command.

The second point I\'ve solved is the fact that prices vary according to
the market.  Each cargo has a market value, represented by the Market
modifier.  This is also multiplied by the base cost to give an asking
price.  When the cargo is sold, the local market can be assessed to find
an asking price.  The price of a cargo is then:

Base cost/price x Quality modifier x Market modifier

I have my players roll uncertain tasks to determine the Quality and the
Market, and together these give a range of possible values for the cargo.
These rules introduce variety in the products available, and allow
uncertainty to creep into the trade process.

I\'ll try and post the missing tables, or perhaps include them in the web
pages as ps files.

____________________________________________________________________________
"Traveller Done Wrong
         - Let\'s get the Fiction back into Science Fiction Roleplaying"

