    'month' => '01',
    'index' => 'ac315',
    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> writes:

> even if that planet is Earth. In the Traveller Universe the Ancients spread
> humans around on about a 100 worlds, and on about half of these the humans
> survived. That gives us 50 histories right there and if even one of them
> duplicated Earth\'s tech developements exactly I\'d be very surprised.

Remember, here on earth we have numerous examples of *independently
evolved* cultures, civilizations and technologies. At TL 0 there are
*hundreds*. At TL1 there are still a dozen or so. After that we start
getting too much cross-fertilizing.

But for TL 0 and TL1 (and even some of TL2) we actually *do* have
enough of a sample to make some statements regarding what tech gets
developed when.

> Then
> there\'s litterally hundreds of alien races each with their own histories (I
> once calculated that there\'s a minor indigenous race per subsector on the
> average (though I confess that I forget just what I based that estimate
> on)).

Now *there*, we have some interesting possibilities. There have been
recent threads on rec.arts.sf.science regarding how tech would develop
for such things as water breathers.

> It didn\'t happen at TL 0 on Earth (At least not if you don\'t accept Babylonia
> and Egypt as TL 0 societies - which is OK by me). But postulate a world with
> some more fertile areas where, say 4 people could gather enough food to keep
> 5 people alive (4:1 was the proportion of peasants to city-dwellers in the
> Middle Ages). Right away you have a leisure class at TL 0. Remember the
> "orchards" of Darrien? In that environment the Darrians could easily have
> invented writing at a very early stage.

Sorry, you are sufferring from a common misconception. TL0
hunter/gatherers have *more* leisure time than even *we* do. It only
takes a few hours a day to provide the necessities of life. The rest of
the time is free to do what you want.

The introduction of of agriculture *reduces* free time, and you don\'t
start getting it back until this century.

Writing develops *because* of agriculture. There\'s a need to keep
records, and that leads to both math and to writing. We\'ve only got a
dozen examples to go by.... And they *all* follow the same pattern.

Agriculture allows more people. Which makes you *dependent* on
agriculture. This means you need to keep good track of the seasons so
as to know when to plant. That leads to math and astronomy.

You also need to store food (the whole *point* of developing
agriculture was that even though you become a virtual slave to the
fields, you also don\'t have to worry about how to make it through the
winter). So that leads to more math, and to writing so that you can
keep track of *who* owns which containers, and what\'s in them.

Next, you find that droughts and uuntimelty rains are a problem. This
means you invent irrigation. This requires group effort, and surveying
and construction skills. At first minor, but quickly increasing. The
Egyptians got lucky. The floods not only removed the need for more than
elementary irrigation, it also fertilized the ground, so they didn\'t
wear it out. Note that most of the birthplaces of civilization are now
deserts and dustbowls... there\'s a reason.

Anyway, the Egyptains got pushed into better math because the floods
meant they *had* to develop surveying to keep track of who own which
chunk of land. But even that made little difference in their development.

Getting back to the general case, soon you need *lots* of workers to
maintain the irrigation systems, and build dams. You also need to build
storehouses. Bricks and pottery *will* be invented now if they haven\'t
already been.

There are several examples of cultures that got this far and then fell
apart after things like a major dam breaking at the wrong time
(someplace in Mexico) or the rains shifted (the Anasazi in the
Southwest).

About this time you start needing folks specialized in running things.
So you get kings and taxes. And you also get temples to the gods as the
astronomers have turned into priests. This is where you also get big
cities and multi-city cultures.

Angkor Wat in SE Asia is an example of a culture that got to this stage
(kingdom, verging on empire) and then fell apart. I\'d have to dig up
the references, but I recall reading that they fell because either they
"wore out" the land, or their irrigation system caused the jungle to
take over.

Note that we are now down to the dozen or so examples I mentioned.
China, India, Babylon, Egypt, the Incas, the Maya, etc. We\'re up to the
Bronze age (mostly). The *cultures* are distinct, but the *technology*
is remarkably similar.

But once you get past the point of "warring kingdoms", too many wild
cards pop-up. Even so, it\'s still worth noting that it\'s likely that
there are still patterns, but we don\'t have enough examples to draw on.
(We quickly get down to "the West", India, and China).

> >>>Transporation: Horses with saddle and stirrups, ships.
> >>
> >>Stirrups needs metal-working - TL 1.

I missed this earlier. Stirrups do *not* need metalworking. Because
they don\'t need to be metal, and in fact, I\'m moderately certain that
the first ones *weren\'t*.

> >Believe it or not, Egypt in the earlier dynasties is classified as a
> >Neolithic culture!
>
> If so then writing evidently IS TL0.

Depends on what you mean by "writing". Besides, Even *paleolithic*
cultures are a lot more advanced than most folks think. The typical
picture of a "caveman" is pure BS.

> >This seems obvious to *us*, but it is a major invention. Numbers come
> >much later, as do things like addition and subtraction.
>
> But in the Traveller Universe the idea dosen\'t have to be invented. They did
> that already on Terra... and on Vland... and on Zhdant... and on Darrian...

Do you have any idea how *hard* it is to get across the idea of
something like this? Once you get them to grasp the idea, they may take
it and run with it. Or they may look at it and say, "Gee, that\'s
interesting, but not terribly useful".

Again, check out history. Ideas like the decimal system took a lot of
convincing to get people to use them.

> >Domesticating animals is another major invention. :-)
>
> But they can be used at TL 0. I know that for a fact, because the Plains
> Indians did it.

They are an example of a people "stealing" a useful idea from as more
advanced culture. Which shows that tech transfer *does* happen. But
only the bits of tech that the low-tech folks can understand and that
they *want*.

Of course, the Americas are a bit of an interesting case because the
larger animals were killed off by humans *before* the idea of
domesticating animals got that far.

So it\'s possible to argue about whether or not they were "really" TL0
*after* they stole the horses. :-)

> Yes, but there\'s no reason why someone couldn\'t introduce the idea of writing
> into a TL 0 society without further ado. The tools are all there for the
> making: Sticks and clay tablets, ink and papyrus, hard stone and softer
> stone, flint and wood - all are available at TL 0. You don\'t need steel pens
> and paper to write. Oh, and there\'s the Inka system of knots in string.

But to go back to those Plains Indians... They *didn\'t* steal writing.
Why? Because they had no *need* for it!

The Inca system is thought to not really be "writing". It\'s a sort of
memory aid thingy. More than numbers, but not quite up to being
writing.  We\'ll never *really* be sure, because the Spanish did such a
good job of killing off the folks who understood them.

> >Metallurgy (beyond copper which is too soft for stirrups),
>
> Copper and iron are the same TL in Traveller (which may be wrong, but it is).

If I was designing a system from scratch, it\'d have a lot more steps at
the *lower* TLs. But I rather suspect that the Empire just used them as
a quick way of determing what sort of stuff you should be allowed to
import. Read "King David\'s Spaceship" by Pournelle for a good example
of what you can get away with in such cases. :-)

> would be TL 15. My point is that the knowledge is available. So TL is _not_
> (except for the top "cutting edge" TL) a matter of discoveries, it\'s a
> matter of wether or not those discoveries are being used on this or that
> particular world.

And that depends on various factors. Take a look at the way computers
spread (and are still spreading). We had some folks who took to them
right off, just because they were "neat". That doesn\'t mean we were at
"the computer TL" then. It just means that it was possible (with
difficulty to get them). They were a *novelty*.

Next, we had some folks discover that they could use the computer to do
things more easily. But they still were hard to get. If we were getting
them from traders, they be an expensive import.

Next, we\'ve got them being used a lot (pretty much the current
situation). But lots of folks still don\'t see any need to know anything
about them, and others refuse to learn. At this point, a Traveller
culture might start building its own, rather than importing them. The
computer is now a useful tool.

The next stage will be when "everyone" knows about them, and they are
about as remarkable as a toaster or a radio. They\'ll be a commonplace.

Finally, we\'ll get to the point where they are completely taken for
granted. The difference between this step and the one before is that
at the previous step there\'ll still be a few "reactionaries" who think
computers are a bad idea. At this step they\'ll be *so* integrated into
society that such an argument would be the sort of thing that draws you
up short and make you wonder about the sanity of the guy.

I\'d say that if we have to specify a point at which a TL has taken
hold, it\'s either the "useful tool" or "commonplace" stage.

> >When using this example, we have to assume, that developing technology isn\'t
> >only a random invention process
>
> Why? There are ample examples of things that are just the result of random
> invention processes.

But even *those* require a certain level of pre-existing base
technology. You can\'t "randomly" invent something until all the
parts/materials needed exist.

> >but some technology is based on other technology and that there\'s a causal
> >chain of inventions.
>
> Of course there is. That\'s the whole essense of the concept of TLs, IMO. You
> can\'t have TL 5 without some TL 4 foundations, etc. I agree. But the
> inventions are already done. We don\'t have to wait for someone to invent
> the microscope so that we can discover germs, because in the year 5600 AD
> the microscope has been invented scores of times on scores of worlds and
> we already know about germs and know how to deal with them.

Actually, you *don\'t* need a microscope for germ theory. You just need
it to help *confirm* it. It was propsed *before* the microscope.

> >The turing maschine (a theoretical computer) could have been invented with
> >Greek mathematics. However, nobody did it. Probably, the Greeks could have
> >built primitive calculation maschines if somebody told them how.
>
> But if you are a Referee preparing an adventure on Chaosheo (E87A788-1 in
> 1117) you couldn\'t care less about what the ancient Greeks did or didn\'t
> do. What\'s interesting is wether the Chaosheans can have a turing machine
> or not. Can they? Why not? If the ancient Greeks _could_ have invented it
> then who\'s to say the Chaoseans didn\'t?

Us. The Greeks could *build* a turing machine if we told them how. But
they couldn\'t *use* it. To *use* one, you need a lot of math and logic
that they didn\'t have. Since they didn\'t have the *theory*, they
wouldn\'t have any *use* for it.

> >Yes, a good point. I thought about this and decided to classify the TL based
> >on the time, when the technology was broadly used. on earth, steam power was
> >discovered about 50 AD, but nobody realized for what to use it. Time wasn\'t
> >ripe.
>
> But was that because they didn\'t realize what they could have done with it
> or because they _couldn\'t_ build steam engins of a useful size with their
> metallurgy. If the first, then steam powewr IS possible on a TL 1 world;
> if the second the it isn\'t. I think the difference is rather crucial.

I think it\'s a combination. The metals might not have been up to it.
But the *machining* definitely wasn\'t!

> >Tell this our ancestors and ask them why no one who used a watermill
> >invented a windmill :-) Perhaps because slave power was cheaper?
>
> Propably for the same reason why it took centuries from the time lenses
> were being ground for glasses before that German chap thought of putting
> two of them in front of each other and invented the telescope: Nobody
> happened to think of it.

Again, I suggest re-checking your history. It wasn\'t all that long
between when decent lenses started being produced and when the
telescope was invented. There\'s no "centuries" involved. *Maybe* a
decade or two.

