    'body' => '>Could you give me a quote for that astonishing information?

I\'ve seen this as well. I *think* it was in the set of atlases Joseph
Campbell was publishing when he died. And it\'s not just theory: it has been
observed in New Guinea within your lifetime. (I\'ll check if the debate
continues long enough, but my books aren\'t unpacked yet from most recent move.)

> If you did have
>a tribe living in an area where everybody could gather enough to live on in
>a couple of hours, pretty soon the population would increase to the point
>where this was no longer true.

Infant mortality in these societies is so high that life expectancy is only
20-30 years. (See
_The_Human_Species:_An_Introduction_to_Biological_Anthropology_, 2nd ed., by
John Relethford, p. 463. Surrounding pages have more info about disease in
h-g and ag societies.)

>Then some or all of the tribe would have to
>go farther afield to collect their vittles and it would take them a few
>extra hours just to move out to collect and to return to the tribe.

I think they generally move as they forage. And they operate in
astonishingly small bands.

>>The introduction of of agriculture *reduces* free time,
>
>That seems totally contra-intuitive. Why would anyone change from their
>pleasant pastoral hunter/gather society where they only have to work a
>few hours a day to the back-breaking day-long toil of agriculture?

You give us too much credit. Why do modern people join cults or go to grad
school? We\'re a stupid species.

Seriously, early ag societies were *not* a nice place to live. See
_Plagues_and_Peoples (can\'t recall author).

                                        Bobby Bryant,
                                        Confessed Grad Student

