    'ts-index' => '1996-01-12.ac341',
    'body' => '> >Sorry, you are sufferring from a common misconception. TL0 hunter/gatherers
> >have *more* leisure time than even *we* do. It only takes a few hours a day
> >to provide the necessities of life. The rest of the time is free to do what
> >you want.
>
> Could you give me a quote for that astonishing information? If you did have
> a tribe living in an area where everybody could gather enough to live on in
> a couple of hours, pretty soon the population would increase to the point
> where this was no longer true. Then some or all of the tribe would have to
> go farther afield to collect their vittles and it would take them a few
> extra hours just to move out to collect and to return to the tribe. Pretty
> soon there would be more people, and eventually they would have to spend
> most of each day gathering. Surely the reason for migration (and we know
> that there have been migrations all the way back the long years of human
> pre-history) is to provide food for people who would otherwise starve.

  The above information is true - gatherer/hunters have more leisure time
than people in agricultural societies.  Migration was driven by
population density, not food shortage - your assumption about people
gathering until population keeps growing leaves something out, namely the
ability to limit birth rates.  Most cultures do so - freely expanding
cultures with high birth rates are the exception, not the rule.

> >The introduction of of agriculture *reduces* free time,
>
> That seems totally contra-intuitive. Why would anyone change from their
> pleasant pastoral hunter/gather society where they only have to work a
> few hours a day to the back-breaking day-long toil of agriculture?

  Good question.  There are a number of theories.  The most popular
points to the rise of agricultural in the arid river valleys of the Nile
and the Tigrus-Euphrates.  Seasonal flooding makes irrigation and water
control central to raising yeilds, so is adopted.  Other cultures in
other climates do not adopt widespread agriculture - American Indians in
the American Northwest, for example, knew about intensive agriculture but
did not adopt it.

  My favorite theory about the origin of agriculture is that people
cultivated grain not for food but to make beer.  Agriculture had its
origins in provideing a consistant sourcee of intoxicants, and only later
was a way top produce food.

  Agriculture has two advantages - a more consistant, storable food
supply (especially with grains like rice or wheat), and the ability to
support roughly 100 times more people per square mile of land.  Problem
is that it takes far more work, and you can\'t go back once you\'ve
started, at least not without massive die-off (chat with the ancient
Mayas about that one).

> >and you don\'t start getting it back until this century.
>
> Now that is manifestly untrue. Throughout recorded history the percentage of
> society that was needed for food production has steadily fallen as technology
> improved (and vice versa).

  Sorry - until the mechanization of agriculture that begins in the 18th
century, most folks were farmers - productivity increased little.  And I
would hardly argue that workers in the 19th century in factories had lots
of leisure.

> >Writing develops *because* of agriculture. There\'s a need to keep records,
> >and that leads to both math and to writing. We\'ve only got a dozen examples
> >to go by.... And they *all* follow the same pattern.
>
> Wrong tense, even if the rest is right. Writing _developed_. Here on Earth.
> Possibly also on the other "home" planets. But not no the 95% of all planets
> that were settled by spacefarers.



> > Agriculture allows more people.
>
> Wait a minute. If one man can gather/hunt enough to survive in two hours,
> then he can gather/hunt enough for 5 people to survive in 10 hours. Thus
> 20% of the society can support the rest. In medieval economy it took 4
> peasants (well, people living outside of cities) to support 1 non-peasant
> (or city-dweller). Of course, he needs a lot more land to do it, but back
> then he did have a lot more land. Your claim just dosen\'t make sense. I
> must be missing some facts. Please provide them.

  You make the false assumption that the gatherer hunter wants to support
all those other people - he or she will limit population because leisure
has high marginal value.

  Again, agricultural societies support far higher densities, roughly
x100.  Is this good for the people involved?  For the most part, no.
Read Lewis Mumford on this (Technics and Civilization is a good place to
start) - he blames most of the problems in modern society on the
development of agriculture, and makes a very convincing case.


----
Mark H Clark
