    'body' => '
Comments from Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> marked with ">",
comments by Leonard Erickson with ">>"

I mostly agree with Hans\' thesis----TL progression will likely be
different in worlds that don\'t have to do the inventing themselves.
But I think Leonard\'s grasp of the history of development on Earth is
much more accurate than Hans.

>>Sorry, you are sufferring from a common misconception. TL0 hunter/gatherers
>>have *more* leisure time than even *we* do. It only takes a few hours a day
>>to provide the necessities of life. The rest of the time is free to do what
>>you want.
>
>Could you give me a quote for that astonishing information? If you did have
>a tribe living in an area where everybody could gather enough to live on in
>a couple of hours, pretty soon the population would increase to the point
>where this was no longer true. Then some or all of the tribe would have to
>go farther afield to collect their vittles and it would take them a few
>extra hours just to move out to collect and to return to the tribe. Pretty
>soon there would be more people, and eventually they would have to spend
>most of each day gathering. Surely the reason for migration (and we know
>that there have been migrations all the way back the long years of human
>pre-history) is to provide food for people who would otherwise starve.

I\'m not Leonard, but I\'ll try to answer anyways.

Hans obviously overlooked the part where Leonard mentioned that the big
advantage of agriculture was to store up food for the winter... so you
would survive it.

For a hunter/gather, during the spring, summer, and fall food is
plentiful and cheap and very little time is required to gather enough
to eat.

In the winter, very little food is available and people starve.

>>The introduction of of agriculture *reduces* free time,

Reduces free time drastically----but increases the stability of the food
supply with equal impressiveness.

>That seems totally contra-intuitive. Why would anyone change from their
>pleasant pastoral hunter/gather society where they only have to work a
>few hours a day to the back-breaking day-long toil of agriculture?

Leonard didn\'t say "pleasant".  He said "lots of free time."  Starving
isn\'t pleasant.

This also answers Hans\' question, "why wouldn\'t the population
explode?" question----the population is limited by the food available
during the winter.  Free time in the summer can\'t provide food in the
winter UNTIL you invent agriculture.

Once agriculture was invented, Hans picture is completely
right----population expands in a matter of a handful of decades until
every last minute is needed to make enough food to support the
population.  But you need agriculture to be able to use summer time to
provide winter food.

>Now that is manifestly untrue. Throughout recorded history the percentage of
>society that was needed for food production has steadily fallen as technology
>improved (and vice versa).

*Recorded* history.  Hans means, though he ignores the fact, that this
is after the invention of agriculture.  Think about it.  Leonard and
Hans agree here.

History started being recorded to make agriculture work better;
pre-agricultural hunter/gathers don\'t keep written records.

Leonard says it better than I:

>>Writing develops *because* of agriculture. There\'s a need to keep records,
>>and that leads to both math and to writing. We\'ve only got a dozen examples
>>to go by.... And they *all* follow the same pattern.

>> Agriculture allows more people.
>
>Wait a minute. If one man can gather/hunt enough to survive in two hours,
>then he can gather/hunt enough for 5 people to survive in 10 hours.

True----but why would he?  What\'s in it for him?  Why should he work all
day, when two hours suffices?  For the money?  Hasn\'t been invented
yet.  For the luxuries of life?  What luxuries there are, he makes for
himself, in two hours a day.

The invention of the economy, even a barter economy, requires a little
bit of sophistication.  At hunter-gather level, two hours a day
suffices to buy everything!  Why work more?

- Paul Colley
