    'topic' => ' Hunting vs Agriculture',
    'index' => 'ac347',
    'month' => '01',
    'body' => 'Actually, hunting _does_ produce a greater caloric reward than agirculture
does!  (Hey, I was surprised too.)  References include "An introduction to
psychohistory" by Michael Flynn (Analog April & May, 1988) and "Forragers and
Farmers: Population Interaction and Agricultural Expansion in Prehistoric
Europe" by Susan Alling Gregg (University of Chicago Press, 1988).

The _economic_ reason for moving to agriculture is that a given area can
support more people, even though they all have to work harder.  So, your
society of hunter-gatherers (with some spare time) grows until they exceed
the capacity of the land.  At that point their only choice to to take up
agriculture (or starve, or move...).

Yes, this is a simplistic explanation.  I\'m afraid I don\'t have time to
repeat all the material in my sources.  Gregg in particular looks at the
interactions between the two types of society.  Flynn\'s article is a popular
summary of analytical geography, and well worth reading.  I\'ll try to post
his bibliography this weekend.


Other useful sources include:

The Ancient Economy, M.I. Finnet
Artifacts: An introduction to early materials and technology, Henry Hodges
Technology in the Ancient World, Henru Hodges
Mechanics of pre-industrial technology, Cotterell and Kaminga

For a good overview of mathematical models of societies, see "How to Build a
Future" by John Barnes (originally published in Analog - March 1990 I think -
and reprinted in "How to Write Fantasy and Science Fiction").
