    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen writes:
> >The introduction of of agriculture *reduces* free time,
>
> That seems totally contra-intuitive. Why would anyone change from their
> pleasant pastoral hunter/gather society where they only have to work a
> few hours a day to the back-breaking day-long toil of agriculture?

Because agriculture produces a more consistent and predictable return than
does hunting/gathering, and allows you to stay in one place and develop
infrastructure instead of constantly migrating to keep food supplies
available.  It\'s a sure thing rather than a roll of the dice.  Can you
imagine how appealing a field full of grain, ready for the taking, is
to a hunter-gatherer?  Would you work to create that?

> >and you don\'t start getting it back until this century.
>
> Now that is manifestly untrue. Throughout recorded history the percentage
> of society that was needed for food production has steadily fallen as
> technology improved (and vice versa).

He\'s speaking of free time, not the percentage of total labor needed for
food-production.  It\'s true that technology has reduced the number of
farmers necessary to support a population: but many of the other people
have then become needed as the blacksmiths, animal-handlers, etc. to
enable that increased productivity.  The increased efficiency comes at
the price of requiring extensive non-farming work to support it.

