Despite the drive-weapon uses mentioned in the first ed. of HG,
I\'m pretty sure the subsequent "pedigree" of thruster plates is as follows:

Originally, CT didn\'t specify what M-drives were, but they were clearly
reactionless drives. They worked as long as the power plant was
running, and had no fuel requirements of their own.

Later came the K\'kree book:
_Aliens Book 2: K\'Kree_ illustrated Centaur conservativism partly by
the fact that they didn\'t engage in space flight until they detected
a carnivourous race on their moon/sister planet. To quote:

    "Unlike most spacefaring races, the K\'kree never went
     through a phase of primitive rocketry; their first
     interplanetary craft were fully developed grav-drive
     ships basically identical to those still in use today."


When DGP was designing MegaTraveller, they merged the starship
design sequence into the general vehicle design sequence from
the original _Striker_. To distinguish between the sort of grav-drive
used by a starship from that used by an air/raft, they used
anti-grav modules (that dropped off in efficiency away from
an existing gravity well) for grav-vehicles and thruster modules
(which maintained constant thrust regardless of outside environment)
for M-drives. Starships, of course, could use anti-grav modules,
but would be hampered in their maneuvering unless they were
close to a world.

The "plates" of thruster plates came into being to explain why
ships with reactionless thrusters always had glowing external
engines: they _weren\'t_ exhaust chambers, they were heat
radiators (yeah! that\'s it! radiators! hem, haw, errummahh).
