    'month' => '01',
    'index' => 'ac355',
    'body' => 'Hello Marc.

I\'ve read your question Kerry Harrison posted to the XBOAT mailing list in
which you asked for the readers opinion about the future Traveller products.
Here you are.

I would like to see new rules. I think, this a good opportunity.  I don\'t
care incompatibilities between the rules systems. I also don\'t care some
changes to technology and background if that fixes some of the most awful
quirks of Traveller. I think, it\'s more important to attract new customers
than the fulfill every wish of the Traveller-diehards.

Generalize the rules that they could be used with nearly any background. Add
alternative technology to be able to model Startrek or Babylon5-like
settings, but stay with the Imperium (about 1100) as default background that
is used throughout the rules as example. I think, this could increase
interest in Traveller as generic SF system.

Change Traveller\'s technology. Increase the importance of computers. Allow
AIs at for example TL 13. Don\'t introduce all space traveling technology at
TL9. I would suggest to introduce fusion power at TL9 but Jump Drives and
artificial gravitation at TL10 (Jump X at TL9+X). I don\'t like the static
one week jump duration. I like the idea that travel time is independent of
distance but I\'d use a system that let small ships (100t displacement) jump
in (for example) 69 hours and larger ships in more hours because the time
needed to fade away the jump field is related to volume. This would make
small ships faster and jump travel (IMHO) more interesting.

Don\'t use and overall TL but subdivide TL in transportation, power,
communication, medical, warfare, and so one. The TL in basic world design
might be an average value but more details world description should details
areas of lower or higher tech.


Book 1: Characters and Basic Rules

This book shall contain a brief introduction to role playing and the
Traveller universe as used as example background. Start with character
generation rules. I would like a fast a simple system as used in classic
Traveller. Use both an archetype and a die-rolling system. In my opinion,
about 60 skills is the upper limit, TNE has too much skills. Change the four
year terms to two year terms. Don\'t overemphasize combat and combat related
skills. For characteristic, use "a character with Strength 6 (12) is about
twice (three times) as strong as one with Strength 1" as rule of thumb, not
six or twelve times as strong. Don\'t use a proportional scheme. Don\'t tie
the number of skill to education. I use a scheme of no, basic, medium and
high education to allow learning special skills without malus. Medium
education allows most technical skills, high education is needed for
medicine and other science skills. No education only allows the most
primitive skills as melee combat, swimming and so one. All characters start
with basic education.

Character example: Dr. Christoph Crasemann, Age 27, Archeologist, 746869,
four terms university, one term occupation (archeologist), High Education,
No PSI, Bribery-1, Computer-3, Scouting-1, Driving (Ground Vehicle)-1,
History (Ancients, Darrians)-3, Communication-0, Slug Weapon-0, Space
Suit-1, Languages (Darrians)-2, Science (Archeology)-4.

It\'s my observation, that players will add more description and "life" to a
character with less "numbers." So keep character data to an absolute
minimum. This also allows to use the same rules for characters and non
player characters. (Don\'t use the two classes system of TNE.) Back to the
book. Next chapters would be skill system, combat, experience, environmental
rules (from falling damage, suffocation in vacuum to poison effects) and
equipment.

If you want to use a 2d6 system for the rules (which I would prefer), you
might look at the Forgotten Futures rules. FF is a shareware game, a bit
similar to Space 1889, by Marcus L. Rowland. (You could find the rules for
example at http://www.tierzucht.uni-kiel.de/~sma/forgottenfutures/.) Marcus\'
system is quite similar to the classic Traveller system but IMHO more
playable (hope you don\'t mind this :-)

Combat should be fast and deadly. Quite different to TNE! With FF rules,
most slug weapons are deadly. One good shoot and you\'re dead. That\'s more I
like it. I don\'t no your opinion about this, but I don\'t want Traveller as
military simulation but as role playing game with emphasize on exploration,
mystery (sense of wonder), communication and investigation. The rules
shouldn\'t offer combat as most successfully option for solving problems. The
equipment list should be generic. I don\'t need a dozen slightly different
guns, just state that most guns\' damage range between X and Y and that (for
example) von Neumann Waffentechnik megacorp offers the broadest collection
of deadly weapons.

An appendix should cover a subsector and detail one world together with a
short adventure.


Book 2: World Design

This book shall cover all aspects of world design. Starting this the classic
rules to roll up systems and planets to the more detailed rules of the World
Tamer\'s Guide. Additional I\'d wish better rules for different societies,
minor alien races and creatures. Please supply random tables because it\'s
easier to role something up and become inspired by the result (that you than
probably change anyhow) than to image and construct from scratch. Add animal
combat. Add rules for wormholes or pocket universes.

Please consider depending population on physical world data in the basic
world design and make Law Level more than a weapon control rating. For
non-frontier region, I would suggest to apply a malus to Law Level because I
(and hopefully also other people) believe in civilized private people don\'t
need weapons.

An appendix should details some ideas for colonization or exploration of a
new world.


Book 3: Starship Design and Operation

This book shall contain a simple and fast design system for star ships,
space ships and(!) space stations. I\'m not primary interesting in costs or
combat ratings but in size, form, deckplans, maintenance costs and crew
requirements. This book should detail all aspects of ship operations, space
travel and board routine. It shall also include zero-G operations like
repairs or space walks. Add a tactical star ship combat system which is
usable during role playing that means that give importance to character
actions.

I would like to be able to design ships without the help of a computer.
Detail level as for example in Space 1889 would probably be sufficient.
Choose hull size and form. Choose jump drive. Calculate jump fuel space.
Choose converter, power plant and maneuver drives. Calculate maneuver and
engine fuel. Add computers. Determine cargo space and living area. Calculate
crew. Add life support, cabins, bridge. Choose weapon system, ship boats and
additional systems.

Related to star ships are space stations and space ports. Add some rules to
detail and/or construct them. I always missed this in Traveller. Add it.
(Far Away#1 contains a useful article about this.)

As with the other books, add an appendix with some adventure ideas (lost in
space because of misjump, strange signals from within an asteroids belt, the
used ship parts auction, and so one)


Book 4: Imperial Sourcebook - Spinwards Marches

Draw from all the published material and do a fresh look to the (IMHO) most
interesting part of the Traveller background. Don\'t be afraid to change some
world characteristics, the (odd) 100t xboat-system or other parts of the
former games. Bring back some sense of wonder to the setting. TNE was
lacking this. The TNE settings weren\'t different from today settings.

This book shall contain two or three longer adventures.


Book 5-9: Alien Books for Aslan, Zhodani, Vargr, Droyne, Solomani.

Rules and additions for the most important Traveller alien races together
with their history, culture, believe, and so one. Add an adventure. I think,
it would be difficult to outdo the DGP alien books. Add typical equipment
and vehicles.


Book 10: Vehicle Construction

As Fire, Fusion and Steel (or even better GURPS Vehicles) provide some
simple rules to design all kinds of vehicles. I doesn\'t bother weapon or
especially ammunition design. Especially not about 60 pages as in FF&S. Even
if not total related to the title, add more equipment as communication
devices, protection equipment, medical drugs and devices, and so one.

An appendix, you\'ll probably guess, should give you some praxis with newly
design vehicles. An adventure.


Book 11: Strategic Wargame

Use an even simpler system to rate ships (and other combat vehicles) for
strategical combat. This product hasn\'t be direct related to roleplay but to
help image the Traveller warfare. It might be fun to play interstellar wars
or even relive prominent Imperial wars.

The appendix contains some scenarios as for example some fights of the Aslan
border war or the 5th frontier war. Of course, this book should include the
ships of all major alien races.


Book 12: Reformation Coalition

Start to support different backgrounds. Great parts of Path of Tears are
very well written. To accept this setting you\'ve to accept the virus
concept, although. The sandman-adventure of the Vampire Sourcebook has very
interesting opportunities. However, I always feel that most of the RC
setting was done that way to give nice opportunities for all kinds of combat.

Even more books could handle other settings, more equipment, worlds, and so
one. Together with this books, a series of adventures should be published.
(I would prefer something like the old classic Traveller adventure booklet
instead of Smash-and-Grab-like mission or most of the recent Challenge
adventures.)

Well, I hope this will help you in keeping the idea of Traveller alive,
bye
--
Stefan Matthias Aust  //  But it\'s gonna be really happening to ya

