    'index' => 'ac358',
    'topic' => 'Early TL comments',
    'body' => '>>Sorry, you are sufferring from a common misconception. TL0 hunter/gatherers
>>have *more* leisure time than even *we* do. It only takes a few hours a day
>>to provide the necessities of life. The rest of the time is free to do what
>>you want.

>Could you give me a quote for that astonishing information?
You would need to use a lot of bandwith for a full listing.  That has been
shown to be true for various North American cultures (pre-Columbus), Several
different studies of Amazonian, African, and Melanesian tribes (New Guinea,
Philippines) that I know of.

>If you did have
>a tribe living in an area where everybody could gather enough to live on in
>a couple of hours, pretty soon the population would increase to the point
>where this was no longer true.

Well, no.  There are a number of factors that tend to keep their population
down,
including a higher than standard death rate, and often a knowledge that too
many folks eat too much.  So they hold their population down by a number of
social strictures.

> Then some or all of the tribe would have to
>go farther afield to collect their vittles and it would take them a few
>extra hours just to move out to collect and to return to the tribe.

Often, when they hit this stage, a tribe breaks up.  Or, if limited in range by
surrounding tribes, it cuts back on its numbers (see above) or tries to take
more turf from a surrounding tribe.

>>The introduction of of agriculture *reduces* free time,

>That seems totally contra-intuitive. Why would anyone change from their
>pleasant pastoral hunter/gather society where they only have to work a
>few hours a day to the back-breaking day-long toil of agriculture?

Consistency of food source, of course!  Hunting/gathering goes in cycles of
feast and famine - and sometimes for completely unrelated reasons fails
altogether.  Agriculture provided a consistent means of providing food,
especially in temperate climates where winter rather limited the available
food sources.  It comes at a price - you cannot move the growing crops, and
once harvested, you cannot easily move the collected crops.  Not all societies
wanted this limitation.

>>and you don\'t start getting it back until this century.

>Now that is manifestly untrue. Throughout recorded history the percentage of
>society that was needed for food production has steadily fallen as technology
>improved (and vice versa).

Sadly, its not quite true.  While the number of people manufacturing food has
shrunk, the bulk of the surplus (non-food producing) population has gone to
produce other goods and services to exchange for food grown by someone
else: factory workers (and there were cloth factories going back to the middle
ages and probably earlier), sailors, muleteers, soldiers, merchants, craftsmen -
none of whom had huge amounts of leisure time (at least here in the west and
over most of the orient).

Sociologically yours,
Ted7
