    'id' => '<Pine.BSD.3.91.960115130421.20003A-100000@ganesh.lm.com>',
    'date' => 'Mon, 15 Jan 1996 13:15:05  0500 (EST)',
    'body' => 'All of the assumptions made on how long it takes for a hunter-gatherer to
hunt/gather daily food supplies assumes the conditions and food
availability of terra.  On a desert world would agriculture*ever*
develop?  Perhaps, but not in the manner it is done here.  Also, a lush
jungle world or other type of ecosystem could provide food for lots of
people without ever needing the \'stability\' of agriculture.

Oh, I don\'t have sources on hand here, but the assumption that early
agricultural societies were nice places to be are false.  More work, less
protein, at least in the early days. Archeological records show that the
non-farmers in the highlands and mountains around the mesopotamian region
were were most likely bigger, stronger, and more agressive than their
farming cousins.  Early agricultural societies saw diesase run rampant
(something like the Plague probably wouldn\'t happen in a hunter/gathering
society, population is less dense) do to crowding and lack of sanitation.

Slavery of all sorts was probably not very common until people realized
that they needed lots of arms to till the soil.

The above being said, a race that never needs or wants to move past
hunting/gathering will probably not develop starfaring technology
either.  It is hard to say, with all of our points of view being
huamcentric by definition.

It is nice to see practical discussion on this list.  I wasn\'t sure what
to expect, you know how e-lists can be.  So far xboat and its sister list
have been worth the effort.  I have been playing Traveller for about 18
years now, and it\'s nice to find others who love this most excellent game.

Tom Ellis
