    'subj' => 'Re: agriculture & development',
    'month' => '01',
    'index' => 'ac370',
    'topic' => ' agriculture & development',
    'body' => 'I think all the head-scratching about why an individual or society would
convert from a hunter-gatherer system to an agriculturally-based system when
the H/G has so much more leisure time is all missing the point, a bit:

Certainly, if the H/G is in a sparsely populated area, food is relatively
easy to come by.  However, as populatino increases, the area required to get
this food increases, not even taking into account game/forage depletion -
another serious factor.

Even this is inconsequential when you look at it from a simply human nature
point of view -
1) an agricultural system provides much more stable food supply, sure not
perfect, but NOT subject to migrations, die-offs, etc.  Herding, my personal
fave for a transition betreen h/g to agri life, kind of gives you the best
of both worlds - as long as you can protect your food from other
h/g\'s...which is a nice segue to:
2) security.  the biggest threat to humans were other humans.  security in
numbers.  more security in big numbers.  even more security in big numbers
behind big walls.
3) comfort - i\'m surprised nobody mentioned this yet.  it\'s a pain in the
ass to pack up a camp every day.  even if your bedroll is a shitty little
thing, every day you DON\'T move, you can \'comfort up\' your surroundings.
every new site always has a new collection of rocks, knots, roots, and burrs
that have to be dealt with or put up with.
4) procreation - children -esp very young - do not move well.
5) finally, h/g is opportunistic.  at least, more so than agriculture.  sure
the h/g has more leisure, but never knows exactly where the next meal is
coming from.  now, if you know that, barring flood or drought, that whole
field of wheat will be there tomorrow, you can PLAN.  and PLANNING is what
societies are based on.

I know - the above contains some sweeping generalizations, but I think they
are justified.  Ah well.

For me, #3, #2, and #4 are the most important.
Steve Lieb
