    'ts-index' => '1996-01-19.ac391',
    'date' => 'Fri, 19 Jan 1996 16:57:20 CST',
    'body' => '  A very interesting theory.  The reason I don\'t buy it is because I
don\'t buy the premise.  Quantitative superiority does not beat
technological superiority all the time - the Gulf War is proof enough of
that.  Even the WWII example you use is not correct - the Allies didn\'t
win because they had more tanks, they won because they had better
airplanes (in large part due to higher octane aviation fuel that allowed
higher power to weight ratios) that gave air superiority and battlefield
control.

  A far simpler explanation for the Terran victory is the Plague of
Duskir.  Canonical Traveller sources credit the plague with contributing
to victory - my feeling is that it was the primary factor.  When
Europeans encountered the New World, some scholars estimate that 90% or
more of the Native American population died of disease.  Many of these
diseases were trivial (measles, mumps, etc.), but in a population with no
aquired immunity they were deadly.  With the separation interstellar
rather than local, the Vilani would be toast.

----
Mark H Clark
mhclark@iastate.edu
