>
>Remember that they\'ll have learned the hard way that too many people equals
>starvation.

Well, family planning may be one of those advanced ideas (if it is advanced).

>So they\'ll not go *too* far in that direction.

?

>But it can be a possibility. It certainly means that they\'ll have the time
>ands inclination to hunt for things the Imperials want to buy or to
>produce "narive crafts" for sale. Assuming the Imerials come up with
>something they want as payment.

Ice cream? ;-)

>>Apparently you think that most of the low-tech worlds in the Traveller
>>universe are native worlds. I disagree. Of the 10.000 worlds of the
>>Imperium, 50 _at most_ have "native" human populations (in fact, many of
>>the 46 minor human races known were seeded on worlds outside the Imperium),
>>and many of those are high-tech. It\'s harder to tell about the minor non-
>>humans, because we don\'t know enough about them, so I suppose that\'s just
>>something we shall have to disagree about. But IMO most of the low-tech
>>worlds in the Traveller Universe are regressed societies. So I think that
>>retained technology is highly relevant.
>
>I\'ve *never* been comfortable with that sort of assumption.

Too bad, but it seems to be the assumption that the Traveller universe is
based on.

>It just doesn\'t make sense.

It has made sense to a whole lot of fairly succesful SF authors.

>*Especially* on hostile worlds. Natives make a lot more sense, and fit in
>better with the sort of SF that inspired Traveller.

You and I must\'ve been reading SF from two different parallel universes. The
SF litterature I\'ve read is chock full of regressed societies. As for hostile
worlds, that depends on the degree of hostility. But often the cause of the
regression IS the hostility of the planet.

>>Many "natives" are likely to be descendants of settlers who brought riding
>>animals to the planet because, unlike tractors and air-rafts, they can be
>>produced by a colonial economy and they manufacture their own replacements.
>
>In which case they\'d *already* have the riding animals. So they
>wouldn\'t need to pick up the idea from the Imperials *anyway*.

No, they would have retained the idea. What\'s your point? They would still
be a low-tech society who had not had to invent all the ideas they use for
themselves.

>Sure, *some* will. But it\'s going to require a relatively "friendly"
>planet, *and* a good reason for them to have had enough people to
>survive, but not enough to maintain tech.

A passenger liner full of people from a high-tech society misjumps to a
system with a relatively friendly planet. How many of them knows how to
cope with the basics of life? Sure, they\'ve got people who can program
a computer and maintain a power plant, but how many of them know anything
about primitive technology? By the time the spaceship wears out their
children will have learned to cope at a low tech level, but how many
retains any practical knowledge of medium-level tech? (How many had any
knowledge about medium-level tech to begin with?) None. That dosen\'t
sound like a fluke, it sounds like the standard scenario.

>>In a universe that has a drive which occasionally flings a starship up to
>>36 parsecs off course and turns into slag? I would say that fallen
>>civilizations would be quite common. Not to mention the effects of The
>>long Night...
>
>It\'d have to be a *huge* ship to have a population that could survive
>long enough to fall and then work back up. *Minimum* of 100 or so of
>breeding age. Populations lower than that tend to die off from genetic
>accidents and just plain "bad luck".

How large a passenger ship do you need to carry several hundred passengers?
Not very. And any planet with a sizable interstellar trade would have plenty
of cargo ships with crew of that size. (In my estimate _every single_ cargo
ship that we\'ve ever seen in any Traveller module is part of a 1% "luxury"
trade fleet. Bulk cargo is IMO carried on 100,000+ T ships and constitutes
99% of the merchant fleet.)

And, of course, if you keep flinging 12-man freetraders into the wild blue
yonder, once in a while one of them _will_ beat the odds and avoid genetic
accidents and just plain bad luck. What you seen to overlook is that if
something is 99% likely to fail then it is 1% likely to succeed. _And we
control the dice_. We decide what breaks a society that we\'re designing got.

I\'ve seen it argued that it\'s a series of low-propability flukes that caused
humanity to exist today, but I\'ve never seen a suggestion based on that to
the effect that we don\'t exist.

>The "long night" situation isn\'t *that* much different. Some types of
>colony (mining sites) aren\'t likely to survive long if contact is lost.
>Picture a deep sea oil rig trying to survive if the supply copters quit
>coming.

Mining sites are just a variation of the misjumped passenger liner. Although
they would be much rarer, I agree, because most outfits would extract their
people before they closed down. Unless the final disruption was violent
(like a war or ar Reaver attack on the staging world). But again, we can
decide that that was just what happened.

>Places *planned* as colonies would be better of, depending on how far along
>they were.

Absolutely. But there we have other ways to muck things up. Human failure is
always a good way. A power struggle, a mutiny, a small war over scarce
ressources, a disease... The possibilities are legion.

>Anybody who designs anything other than a mining setup or a research
>station that *isn\'t* iuntended to be self-sufficient is too much of an
>idiot to have been in charge (though it will happen occasionally).

Self-sufficient how long? Enough to survive the failure of one or two supply
ships, sure, but who reckons with the possibility that your outfit _and_ home
culture gets scragged together? And if you\'re paying high wages to your
mineing people then you don\'t pay for an agricultural support group too.

In fact, I can\'t see how a high-tech outpost or a misjumped ship can avoid
back-sliding. All the way down to hunter-gatherer is a bit far, but there\'s
no way they can produce the things needed to keep their high-tech equipment
going once they are cut off from the parent society.

>Such places would lose tech for some things, but for the most part it\'d
>not affect them all that much. Maybe we need to come up with a "how to
>build a colony" set of "rules", and list what happens at each stage if
>they get cut off.

An interesting idea.

>ps. I\'d suggest that we use "native" or "contacted" for indigenous low
>tech societies, and "fallen" for the backslid type.

A good idea. I\'d suggest "evolved" for those that has had no contact as
all ("historical" societies on presently high-tech worlds with indigenous
populations and interdicted worlds), "contacted" for indigenous populations
in contact with the Imperium, and "fallen" for backslid societies (of either
kind).

Oh, btw. about wether primitive people would want to adopt advanced ideas or
not: Remember the Five Nations? They may have been slightly more advanced
than the Plains indians (I believe that they were agriculturalists, but I
don\'t recall for certain), but not much, and they tried to adapt to the
"White Man\'s Way". Did it very successfully, too, including writing and
newspapers and such... If the white man had been willing to let them, they
would very propably have made it.



      Hans Rancke
University of Copenhagen
