>> 2) security.  the biggest threat to humans were other humans.  security in
>> numbers.  more security in big numbers.  even more security in big numbers
>> behind big walls.
>
>Erm...actually, before the advent of \'civilization\', the biggest threat
>to humans would have been other predators and not necessarily other
>humans Human vs Human conflict generally occurs in situations where one
>group maintains herds which can be pirated, or where one group has access
>to resources (of one sort or another) that another group needs or wants.
>Hunting and gathering societies tend to have far less conflict with other
>human groups than herders, or societies which practise agriculture.

I would strongly disagree with this statement. [totally without educational
basis, i might add :)]

What predators actually PREY on humans?  Only the largest.  Sure, wild dogs
have taken children, etc, but i\'m talking about subsistence, not
oppportunity.  Once humans develop speech, and weapons (esp an effective
missile weapon) the activities of natural predators become almost
disregardeable.
I think the anecdotal evidence of hunter-gatherer groups *lack* of conflict
tends to result more from the geography and population levels of remaining
hunter gatherer groups.  I mean, all that are left really only exist on
marginal or remote areas- everyone else having advanced OUT of the H/G
stage.  I would think that looking at human groups that have relatively
recently advanced from this stage shows a significant history of warfare,
raiding, and combat - (and i don\'t mean to offend anyone here, i am just
trying to prove a point!) look at the tribal cultures in sub-saharan african
or the north american plains.  They fought ALL the time - if it wasn\'t
organized warfare, it was raiding.
Not to commit the naturalistic fallacy, but i think it\'s clear that WHENEVER
a group of humans has found ground fertile enough to cultivate (or some
similar aspect like fishing) they have 1) built a village 2) built a wall 3)
prospered except where the H/G around them were too overwhelming.

In sum, I really think that where life/death decisions like these are
concerned, people act for loss-minimization NOT gain-maximization.  At
least, people with families.  I don\'t think that point can be overstated -
there is a significant difference betweren the way people think when they
are responsible for them selves, and when they are responsible for family -
tribe.
Steve Lieb
(liebx004@maroon.tc.umn.edu)
(Who continues to suffer from .sig bloat - and therefore has clipped the
whole thing. Wait . . .)

