aware of this than we seem to be)

>>So they\'ll not go *too* far in that direction.
>
>?

See above. If they figure the group is getting too big, they\'ll startt
eliminating extras by whatever the customary means is.

>>It just doesn\'t make sense.
>
>It has made sense to a whole lot of fairly succesful SF authors.
>
>>*Especially* on hostile worlds. Natives make a lot more sense, and fit in
>>better with the sort of SF that inspired Traveller.
>
>You and I must\'ve been reading SF from two different parallel universes. The
>SF litterature I\'ve read is chock full of regressed societies. As for hostile
>worlds, that depends on the degree of hostility. But often the cause of the
>regression IS the hostility of the planet.

Other than the "post atomic war" type stuff, most of the US SF which
seems to be the basis for Traveller has that sort of story as an
*exception*. Look at Andre Norton, Poul Anderson, etc.

I hope you aren\'t basing your views on Perry Rhodan? :-)

>>>Many "natives" are likely to be descendants of settlers who brought riding
>>>animals to the planet because, unlike tractors and air-rafts, they can be
>>>produced by a colonial economy and they manufacture their own replacements.
>>
>>In which case they\'d *already* have the riding animals. So they
>>wouldn\'t need to pick up the idea from the Imperials *anyway*.
>
>No, they would have retained the idea. What\'s your point? They would still
>be a low-tech society who had not had to invent all the ideas they use for
>themselves.

You *were* talking about the natives *getting* ideas from the Imperials
or other visitors. And, as I pointed out, they *won\'t* get riding
animals that way (unlike the American indians).

Nor are they going to *retain* the idea for long if they don\'t have any
animals suitable for the purpose.

>>Sure, *some* will. But it\'s going to require a relatively "friendly"
>>planet, *and* a good reason for them to have had enough people to
>>survive, but not enough to maintain tech.
>
>A passenger liner full of people from a high-tech society misjumps to a
>system with a relatively friendly planet. How many of them knows how to
>cope with the basics of life? Sure, they\'ve got people who can program
>a computer and maintain a power plant, but how many of them know anything
>about primitive technology? By the time the spaceship wears out their
>children will have learned to cope at a low tech level, but how many
>retains any practical knowledge of medium-level tech? (How many had any
>knowledge about medium-level tech to begin with?) None. That dosen\'t
>sound like a fluke, it sounds like the standard scenario.

Quite a few will. More people than you think have hobbies that give
them knowledge of at least *some* obsolete tech. Some have quite a bit.
For example, I myself know things like how to make gunpowder, sulfuric
and nitric acids, and a lot of other chemical stuff starting pretty
much from nothing but raw materials. I note only know the *current*
methods, which require hard to produce catalysts and the like, but I
also know the *historical* methods, which are much easier, even if they
are less efficient.

I also know something about farming, raising animals, primitive
weaponry, metal refining from ore, hand forging, casting, etc, etc.

If the ship\'s library is intact, they *will* have more knowledge than I
do. What I listed above is the stuff I can do *without* reference
materials.

Given misjumps and the like, plus the "imperial technical packages",
I\'m willing to bet that part of the survival gear on a properly
equipped ship is a microfiche reader (or equivalent) that requires
nothing but a decent light source to use. And a "shoebox" full of all
the tech info you could possibly need to survive on a reasonably
earthlike planet.

Remember, the original edition of the Encyclopeadia Brittanica had
*all* the technical knowledge of the time in it! And it wasn\'t any
bigger than what I\'m proposing.

>>It\'d have to be a *huge* ship to have a population that could survive
>>long enough to fall and then work back up. *Minimum* of 100 or so of
>>breeding age. Populations lower than that tend to die off from genetic
>>accidents and just plain "bad luck".
>
>How large a passenger ship do you need to carry several hundred passengers?
>Not very. And any planet with a sizable interstellar trade would have plenty
>of cargo ships with crew of that size. (In my estimate _every single_ cargo
>ship that we\'ve ever seen in any Traveller module is part of a 1% "luxury"
>trade fleet. Bulk cargo is IMO carried on 100,000+ T ships and constitutes
>99% of the merchant fleet.)

As I\'ve said before and will say again, that sort of trade volume is
pure nonsense. It costs less to make the stuff locally than to ship it
over interstellar distances. *Especially* once you have decent fusion
power. With that tech level, I can extract chemically pure elements
from ordinary rock. And it\'ll cost less than mining does. Dump your
inorganic trash into a fusion torch and plasma seperator and you have
100% recycling. Add some rock and you\'ll get the traces of whatever
gets lost. Plus, lots and lots of silicon and oxygen. Seawater is even
better.

The only places where being self-sufficient doesn\'t make sense are
things like research stations, survey teams, and the occasional place
where there\'s something like gemstones, or *really* rare elements to
mine. Anyplace where you are harvesting some sort of rare organic, you
might as well have a garden plot.

Once the population hits a million or so self-sufficient is the only
thing that makes sense (work out what it costs for food *plus shipping
costs* and several *months* of reserves, then compare it with what it
costs to have a few hundred folks raising and processing food).

And it makes sense to do it at levels in the low thousands. It\'s cheap
insurance, and cuts way down on shipping costs.

>And, of course, if you keep flinging 12-man freetraders into the wild blue
>yonder, once in a while one of them _will_ beat the odds and avoid genetic
>accidents and just plain bad luck. What you seen to overlook is that if
>something is 99% likely to fail then it is 1% likely to succeed. _And we
>control the dice_. We decide what breaks a society that we\'re designing got.

Yes, we control the dice. So we are justified in having *a* low
probability event occur. Even a string of them, if it gives us an
"interesting" locale. But doing so over and over again for hundreds of
planets isn\'t even "cheating". It\'s just plain lazy. And stupid, to boot.

So a *few* planets populated by the descendants of castaways can be
justified. But not the widespread numbers we see.

>I\'ve seen it argued that it\'s a series of low-propability flukes that caused
>humanity to exist today, but I\'ve never seen a suggestion based on that to
>the effect that we don\'t exist.

That\'s because the probability of an event that has already occured is
100%. Saying that an event is unlikely *to* occur is quite different
from saying that it is unlikely to *have* occurred.

>>The "long night" situation isn\'t *that* much different. Some types of
>>colony (mining sites) aren\'t likely to survive long if contact is lost.
>>Picture a deep sea oil rig trying to survive if the supply copters quit
>>coming.
>
>Mining sites are just a variation of the misjumped passenger liner. Although
>they would be much rarer, I agree, because most outfits would extract their
>people before they closed down. Unless the final disruption was violent
>(like a war or ar Reaver attack on the staging world). But again, we can
>decide that that was just what happened.

But only once or twice. After that, we\'re back to the "it makes no
sense" problem.

>>Places *planned* as colonies would be better of, depending on how far along
>>they were.
>
>Absolutely. But there we have other ways to muck things up. Human failure is
>always a good way. A power struggle, a mutiny, a small war over scarce
>ressources, a disease... The possibilities are legion.

But they *don\'t* allow for a *legion* of such planets!

>>Anybody who designs anything other than a mining setup or a research
>>station that *isn\'t* iuntended to be self-sufficient is too much of an
>>idiot to have been in charge (though it will happen occasionally).
>
>Self-sufficient how long? Enough to survive the failure of one or two supply
>ships, sure, but who reckons with the possibility that your outfit _and_ home
>culture gets scragged together? And if you\'re paying high wages to your
>mineing people then you don\'t pay for an agricultural support group too.

Want to bet? It\'s a lot cheaper than shipping in food. Anyway, we
specifically *weren\'t* talking about miners. Self-sufficiency for air,
water, and food (in that order) are the number one things that will be
considered in setting up *anything*. The logistics get too unweildy
otherwise. Miners and small research groups do ok on shipped in food.
Maybe even on shipped in water (but the accountants will quickly point
out that recycling gear plus *lots* of spares costs less than a months
supply of water!). *Nobody* will want anything to do with a setup that
doesn\'t have *air* recycling, or a breathable atmosphere. :-)

You can feed miners MREs or C-rations for a while. Especially if
there\'s an emergency. But they are gonna want *real* food. And while
meat is a problem (though not as bad as you might think), fruit and
vegetables are not only fairly easy to produce, they actually *help*
recycle water and air, if you need to do that.

There are even lots of animals that work well as food animals in
limited space. Rabbits, Chickens, guinea pigs (a staple food-stuff even
now in Peru! Want a recipe? :-)

>In fact, I can\'t see how a high-tech outpost or a misjumped ship can avoid
>back-sliding. All the way down to hunter-gatherer is a bit far, but there\'s
>no way they can produce the things needed to keep their high-tech equipment
>going once they are cut off from the parent society.

True. But that *doesn\'t* mean that they can\'t produce lower tech stuff.
And don\'t be so sure about the inability to rebuild things. Give me an
environment where I can breathe the air, drink the water without too
much treatment, and eat some of the native life, and give me the ship\'s
library. It may take me several *years*, but given the resources of
even a *small* ship I\'ll be able to do one *hell* of a lot.

It pays to study *real* ships. You will find that even the smallest
freighter has a full fledged machine shop, so they can repair things at
sea, or when in out of the way ports. Only breaking things that require
a foundry will put the ship out of commission. And they also generate
more *electrical* power than a small city! Heck, that\'s how New York
City got the power to restart the local power plants after the Great
Blackout (modern powerplants require some power to run the instruments
and things like fuels pumps. You can\'t start them without it). They got
a power feed from ships in the harbor. And in Hawaaii, after an
especially bad typhoon in the 60s, the navy sent a nuclear sub to one
of the outlying islands to fill in for the local powerplant until it
could be repaired (it was there for several weeks, and was replaced by
some airlifted diesel generator units.. The island wound up with a
better power system than it had started with!)

A *Traveller* ship can produce more power than most powerplants. And it
too, will be able to fix all the parts small enough to get to the
"shop" and lots of others that can\'t be. That\'s why "Engineering" needs
so much space. :-)

>>Such places would lose tech for some things, but for the most part it\'d
>>not affect them all that much. Maybe we need to come up with a "how to
>>build a colony" set of "rules", and list what happens at each stage if
>>they get cut off.
>
>An interesting idea.

Truly. Might even make a decent supplement.

>Oh, btw. about wether primitive people would want to adopt advanced ideas or
>not: Remember the Five Nations? They may have been slightly more advanced
>than the Plains indians (I believe that they were agriculturalists, but I
>don\'t recall for certain), but not much, and they tried to adapt to the
>"White Man\'s Way". Did it very successfully, too, including writing and
>newspapers and such... If the white man had been willing to let them, they
>would very propably have made it.

They *did* have the incentive of wanting to *not* be seen as
"primitive" and "inferior". Unfortunately, they hadn\'t counted on
racism...

There are several SF stories about cultures wanting to raise their
"tech levels" so as to get a better status when integrated into the
"empire" or "federation" that had contacted them.

BTW, some of the stuff I mention in passing above would make great
adventure hooks. Or just minor but fun things to fill in gaps. Like the
players landing at a Class D(?) port just after some sort of disaster
and having to rig an adapter so they can supply power to the natives.
(Just think, the natives will likely pay them *something* and they
might just wind up with a nice goody like a lifetime waiver of port
fees or something)

Or a ship has misjump, but isn\'t too damaged. Except they need some
"unobtanium" <grin> to do the repairs. And one of the passengers is an
amatuer geologist, or has studied engineering history and knows that
they *used* to use <fill in the blank> for that...

