>Someone mentioned that the canonical reason for Terran victory in the Nth
>Interstellar War was some sort of plague that hit the Vilani. Sorry, but
>I\'ve never come across this one ... but will freely admit that I do not have
>a 100% complete set of Traveller/MTrav/TNE gear ... so, *where* is it
>mentioned? I have a friend who *has* as complete a set of Traveller gear
>as it is possible to have, and *he* has never heard of it.

>
>Regardless, from what we know of the history of diseases on Terra, it seems
>unlikely in the extreme that some sort of nasty Terran-originated disease
>would have been such a killer that it would have enabled the Terrans to beat
>the Ziru Sirka simply because of it.

My understanding of the issue is that it is presupposed that the Vilani
Empire was already on the verge of collapse.  The problem is that the
collapse of an Emire that size doesn\'t occur overnight.  Given
the huge differences in scale between the Terrans and Vilani Empire,
is hard to see (even with a tech edge) that the Terrans could have
given the Vilani Empire a big enough shove to make a significant
difference in the course of events.

To me, the idea of the a plague is that it causes a widespread disruption
in a system that is just barely functioning.  If you add this to
the a a number of other external threats, and maybe a rebellion or
two in various parts of the empire, and you can see the central
government just being unable to exert control.

Of course even then, you still don\'t have a Terran "victory".  They
just don\'t have enough people do overcome the even the scattered
remnants of the empire.  My presumption has always been, as things
came to a head, a number of Vilani generals saw the collapse coming
and decided that it could be staved off by coopting the some of the
forces pushing collapse.  This idea is that a portion of the Vilani
military, along with some reformist rebel groups, negotiated a
surrender in which the Terrans assumed control and ruled through
the existing power structure.  Then both the Terran and other
rebellious forces, and the forces the Vilani would have lost fighting
the aformentioned, could be used to stablize the situation.

>However, just consider a few facts that make the plague scenario unlikely.
>One, the biggest killer in modern times, disease wise, was the so-called
>Spanish Influenza which broke out at the end of WW1. It was, as I have been
>given to understand by several sources, far and away the most virulent
>plague of modern times ... yet it was really rather trivial in an overall
>sense. Sure, a hell of a lot of people died, perhaps as many as died in WW1,
>but that was peanuts.
>
>More virulent diseases *do* exist, pneumonic plague, for example. However,
>in that case, the disease is *so* virulent and *so* quick acting that it
>basically kills off its human victims so quickly that it cannot spread (at
>least at medieval rates of travel).

The problem is that you a looking for a disease that kills a majority
of the population.  The Black Plague killed 1/3 of the population.
Some thing kills even 10% will cause a huge disruption to a society
(esp. since space travel, the backbone of the empire, will be hardest
hit).

>Anyhow, given McNeill\'s evidence that almost all (if not *all*) diseases
>have been crossovers from animals, and that not all such crossovers are
>successful, then it seems to me that the Vilani would have encountered this
>sort of problem on the thousands of worlds that they had explored and
>settled prior to contact with Terra.

If you have a biosystem that is compatible enough for humans to live
then you are going to deal with bateria.  However, virus\'s are another
matter alltogether.  In an ecosystem where you don\'t even share a
universal ancestor, it is possible to see how the threat of viral
infections could be trivial or non-existant (esp. since we know
nothing about what other biosystem might be like).


