    'body' => '> From: Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
> Subject: Tech Implementation Chart
>
> Does anybody want to help me work out a chart of tech implementation levels?
> That is, a series of levels denoting the technological support someone with
> all the necessary knowledge would need in order to be able to introduce a
> new technology into a society that lacks it.

Sounds good.  Though its really fleshing out the comments in Book 2, that
the TL is a measure of the local capabilities, and affects whats readily
available for trade purposes.  Higher TL equipment may be arround, but
its imported - so expensive.

Some Comments...(anything snipped out has not comments)

> Technology Implementation Level Zero:
> =====================================
> CONTAINERS: Baskets, small clay pots, gourds, skin bottles.
Baskets need tools to cut and split the materials, you might not need to
split the right sort of reeds though.

> COMMUNICATIONS: Writing, smoke signals, beacons, semaphore, flags.
For smoke signals, semaphore and flags, you\'d need some sort of blanket
or cloth.  Would anamal skins be suitable for these tasks?

> FOOD: Hunting, gathering, kitchen gardening, salting, smoking, drying,
>       fermentation (?), winter wine.
I agree wth the (?) for fermentation, wouldn\'t you need some sort of
container, both to hold the fementing mash, but also for boiling the hops
etc..  Unless anyone knows of a recipie that doesn\'t need the boling process?



> Technology Implementation Level One:
> ====================================
> CONTAINERS: Large clay pots, glass bottles, leather bottles.
How would the tube (assuming blown glass) be made?  It could be made from
brass, though making tubes is quite a tricky thing.

> MILITARY: Chariots, war elephants, siege machines.
Chariots and siege machines probably need Iron age tools.  Although you
could make the wood working tools out of bronze, they don\'t hold their
edges well.
Its like the argument that the Egyptians who built the statues in
the Valley of Kings, had to be Iron age.  You can\'t carve Granite with
bronze tools!

> COMPUTING: Logarithmic tables.
You could have these at TLL0, all you need to make a set of Napiers
Bones, is some sticks and a knife.

> ENVIRONMENT: Carved caves, brick and stone buildings, sewers.
Again you\'d need Iron tools for most of the stone work.

A very good start.  Though IMHO the TL thing went down hill with MT.
I do like the Book 2 description, its easy to play with, and allows
variations.

There will be two forms of TL.  The planets that have "evolved" to that
TL, much like our world.  And those limited by some other factor.  If you
have C20 knowledge of materials science and engineering, along with
biology, chemistry, and physics.  You can make a better go of things with
a previous centuries resources.

An example (not a good one perhaps)
We know a lot about weaving.  You could perhaps create a loom capable of
quite good weaving, with TLL0 materials.  Because you know how wool has
to be spun, and how to weave.  It just need improvisation to make it work
with TLL0 materials!

Or bridge building.
With knowledge of engineering, and the apprpriate knots/lashings.  You
can make quite a good bridge, again with TLL0 materials.  Grass, reeds
can be made into ropes,  trees can be cut roughtly (just felled and
trimmed).

Alun
