    'topic' => 'secret histories; tech v. mass',
    'body' => 'Re Secret Histories by Robert Flammang <FLAMMANG@vms.cis.pitt.edu>

Thanks for a nice analysis.  I don\'t buy the all of the details
necessarily, but the overall premise -- that the Third Imperium is every
bit as corrupt as any other huge, old, government -- matches the tone of
my own Traveller universe very well, and I think that many of your points
are well taken -- especially the underlying reason for the
extraterritoriality of starports.

Re tech vs. mass

Let\'s not forget the recent experience of the United States in Vietnam and
the Soviet Union in Afghanistan.  The military forces of the US and USSR
indisputably had significant technological superiority during the entire
period of engagement, yet could not defeat the indigenous forces.  Factors
contributing to this result included, in no order, (1) superpowers\' lack
of domestic support for the war effort, (2) superpowers\' lack of clearly
articulated military and political goals, (3) indigenous forces\' ability
to retain local support and to "occupy the moral high ground" at home and
abroad, and (4) superpowers\' inability to use their technology -- designed
for superpower vs. superpower conflicts -- effectively.

As to mass, I don\'t think that either side necessarily outnumbered the
other in those wars (NVA/VC vs. USA/other SEATO/ARVN: those were probably
pretty close; does anyone have the numbers?  Likewise, the Red Army
devoted large forces to Afghanistan, but I don\'t have the numbers on each
side).

Maybe these have some application in the N Interstellar War situation.
The Ziru Sirka, already tottering and wracked by internal dissension,
lacked the political will to destroy each of its border enemies seriatim,
nor to purge its internal enemies.  The Terrans military and political
leadership was able to convince the populace that the end was at hand
unless everyone pulled together and _produced_ to defeat the evil Vilani.

(It must have been a nightmarish time:  UN Permanent Emergency Regulations
requiring everyone -- except the owning class and certain other elites, of
course -- to work at military production twelve hours per day; suspension
of all due process -- except for the owning class; food rationing, energy
rationing, medicine rationing, net.sex rationing -- except for, well you
know; drug testing to make sure that citizens were not taking prohibited
drugs and were taking required drugs; a lot of "everything not prohibited
is required", in general, except, of course, for the owning class.  This
could be a good era in which to set a Traveller adventure -- sort of a
very black Paranoia.  It\'s no wonder the Solomani are so fascistic in the
57th century.)

