    'body' => 'Leonard Erickson writes:
>I\'ve got most of Chandler\'s stuff. Though his stories are (IMHO) are a
>lot less like Traveller than (for example) E.C.Tub\'s "Dumarest of
>Terra" series (which *has* to be where they got fast drug and slow drug)
>And Chandler\'s Universe has a history that was specifically set up to
>*make* lost colonies likely. Traveller has nothing equivalent to the
>"gaussjammers".

Surely the jumpdrive is _exactly_ the equivalent of gauss-jammers in terms
of getting people lost who didn\'t want to be.

And Chandler is not the only SF author who uses lost colonies. Bradley\'s
Darkover, Bujold\'s Barrayar, and McCaffrey\'s Pern are/were all lost colonies.
Harry Harryson uses them in "Deathworld 2" and "Deathworld 3" (and arguably
in a way in "Deathworld 1"). Pournelle has them, both in the making and as
such. Piper has a blueprint for how it could happen in "Cosmic Computer"
and a number of them in "Spece Viking". Mack Reynolds has some, though those
are of the voluntarily restrained variety. Vance\'s viewpoint cultures are
mostly high-tech, but his worlds are riddled with old cultures that has
degenerated in one way or the other (And he has one very funny short-story
("The Magicians" ?) where the people maintain the old energy cannon by
polishing the exterior to a fine luster).

>>Anyway, the un-interdicted TL 0 worlds in the Traveller Universe are
>>exceptions too. There is one in the entire Deneb Domain. TL 1-3 worlds
>>are more numerous (about two dozen), but still few enough.
>
>Still, that\'s rather common, all things considered.

Well, that seems to be a point we\'ll simply have to agree to disagree on.

>>And I bet you could teach them to an indigenous population too, couldn\'t you?
>
>If I had a *good* reason. [Long piece on why you wouldn\'t].

Completely irrelevant. Not everybody have the same good sense you have. The
question was wether anyone who wanted to _could_ introduce such technologies.
Motivation is easy enough to provide. If something is a foolish thing to do,
all we need is a historical fool. There\'s no dearth of fools in human
history, and I\'ll bet there\'ll be no dearth in the future either.

>You really don\'t need *that* much machinery to have "few hundreds"
>feeding "a million".

What farming methods do you know that allows 1 person to feed 5000? That\'s
including all processing, mind.

>And it *will* be repairable locally. Take a look
>at the mid 19th century. Farm machinery had come into being, but was
>still mostly animal "powered".

Sure, but it\'s news to me that the agricultural sector was only 0.02 % of
the population in the 19th Century.

>>Hundreds? Of un-interdicted pre-industrial worlds (TL 0-3) there are about
>>23 (give or take a couple, I ran through the listings pretty fast) in the
>>Deneb Domain. That\'s a far cry from "hundreds". Of these some may very well
>>be contacted. But many of them have populations of less than a million.
>>Some of them in the thousands (a few even in the hundreds). That dosen\'t
>>say "indigenous" to me, does it to you?
>
>The 23 is a better number for the whole of "known space"!

Is not! ;-)

>Depending on tech level, hundreds and thousands *can* be indigenous.

I think you\'re letting your enthusiasm getting the better of your good
sense here. You can\'t really mean that you think that a population of
900 or even 9000 sentients can be indigenous.

>Remember, the population on Earth only hit a million in the last thousand
>or two years.

Make that 10 million shortly before recorded history.

>Back when we were primarily hunter/gatherers the population was quite
>likely in the tens of thousands.

You can\'t be serious.

>And there was a point *somewhere* in the last couple of million years when
>the population was in the dozens...

You talk about propabilities and then blithely suggests that even _one_
planet with a sentient species just happens to be at the point in time
(out of millions of years) where the number is in the hundreds? If you
are serious then say so and I\'ll just drop the argument. This is simply
too silly. I\'d grant you _one_ low-population indigenous species in all
of Charted Space, and even that is bucking the odds (but as I\'ve said,
low odds do come out occasionally).

>Also, you are ignoring a somewhat more likely possibility. For worlds
>with relatively low populations and a "low" tech level, it\'s possible
>that they are colonies created by "back to nature" types. Sort of like
>the communes so common in the late 60s and early 70s.

No, those are much more likely, and I don\'t ignore them. Of course, _you_
are ignoring the possibility of such colonies being cut off during The
Long Night and changing from artificially maintained low tech to the real
thing. This could have happened a lot, if you maintain that such colonies
are common today, since they would propably have been equally common
before The Long Night.

>>Oh, I think we can squeeze a few more than two out of that scenario. It\'s
>>a big universe and the Reaver mentality is universal.
>
>It\'s not *that* big, and the odds against a "mining camp" surviving are
>pretty slim. Especially given that reavers *do* have some brains. About
>six months to a year after knocking off the staging base, they\'d figure
>that the mine would be easy pickings...

Sharks and minnows. The Reaver fleet that can take on the defenses of a
mainworld wouldn\'t be interested in an odd outpost. Besides, raids on
outposts, colonies and even mainworlds are just the thing to push
societies into decline.

>>Is that something that you\'ve calculated or is it just an assumption on
>>your part? If the first, could you let me see the calculations? I think
>>I once calculated the transportation overhead for bulk cargo at 1 Cr per
>>kilo, but I won\'t swear to it. I\'ll see if I can dig out my figures.
>
>Don\'t forget that you have much the *same* cost for *producing* the
>food "on site" as at wherever the shipper gets it.

That is debatable, to say the least. There is something called economics of
scale, for one thing. But we don\'t have to argue about it. Just take a look
at the world today. Denmark produce more than enough food to feed all its
citizens. Nevertheless they both export and import food. The solution to
this seemingly paradoxical fact is left as an excersise to the reader.

>Add in the extra layers of "middlemen" (shipping brokers, wholesalers, etc)
>involved in the longer trip. Figure a 10% "charge" for each layer.

So you haven\'t done any calculations. Right. Well, let\'s run with your 10%
for a bit. That means that if one planet can produce something 10% cheaper
than another, transport between them makes sense. That\'s well within the
variance (?) you can find between rival food producers on Earth today.

>Oh yeah. The *real* killer on some of this. How many foods *can\'t* handle
>sitting around for a week? or Two weeks?

Damn few. I challenge you to name three bulk food products that can\'t take
that. I suppose that you will be able to come up with some gourmet items
that can\'t, but I\'m confident that I can name 10 that can for each that
can\'t.

>So if you want *fresh* food, it *has* to be produced locally. Damn little
>produce will handle two weeks of shipping all that well. Meat will have
>to be frozen. Etc.

I\'ll remember that when I have my fruit salad dessert tonight. Lessee:
Bananas, apricots, pears, apples, oranges... Not a single local fruit
among them (apples and pears aren\'t in season right now).

>And I\'m sure Europe has the same sort of advertising campaigns we keep
>seeing "Buy Oregon fryers, they\'re fresher", and all the other
>exhortations to buy from local suppliers.

Yeah, but if we did, we wouldn\'t need embargoes.

>>What is "small"? If it\'s more than a couple of hundred then you have a
>>nucleus of a population large enough to satisfy you (by your own earlier
>>posting). If it\'s more than a couple of dozens we\'ve got enough to
>>satisfy me.
>
>A couple of hundred *aren\'t* going to survive if the place isn\'t
>self-sufficient to at least *some* extent. How long would the bases on
>Antartica survive if contact was cut off?

I think things are getting muddled up a bit. We\'re discussing two
different things here. One is how much need there is for interstellar
bulk cargo transport, the other is the likelihood of lost colonies.
You seem to be arguing one way on one subject and the other way on
the other.

>But assuming a few hundred people, I see no reason for the
>"sustainable" tech level to be much below 19th century. And a lot
>*higher* in spots.
>
>The idea is that you use the ship to help make the things you need to
>make what you don\'t have.

You keep making the assumption that everybody will behave rationally and
that everything will go right. I maintain that such is a really poor bet.

But let\'s make a thought experiment. You have a misjumped passenger ship.
The jump drive is slagged (and I mean _slagged_). The ship settles down
on an Earth-prime planet. You have 200 passengers and crew. You have a
minimum survival packet (as required by Rule of Man regulations). (Not
more than minimum, because noone really thought that they would ever
need it, and keeping it fresh costs money. Just be thankful that your
purser hasen\'t sold off most of it (That\'s going to be our next thought
experiment, right? ;-).)

First question: What are your ressources? How much food do you carry? What
other ressources? (Don\'t forget the five tons of mail ;-).

Once the captain has marshalled his ressources and accepted that his yet
unborn children are going to live their life on this planet, what does he
do to ensure them the highest possible standard of living?


