    'date' => 'Wed, 24 Jan 1996 13:38:08  0500 (EST)',
    'body' => 'Hi All.
A lot of people have been saying that 3D navigation is difficult.
It was so in 2300AD, but only because of the fractional light-year
distances and the fact that you had to know the exact distance to
calculate how fast you could stutter-warp to a destination.  With
Traveller, the problem is made easier because everything is in whole
units:  the maps are in whole parsecs, and so are the jump ranges.  Here
is my system for 3D navigation.  It utilizes hex maps 10 x 10 x 5
parsecs, which look much like old Trav maps, except there is a number
from 1 to 5 in the center of each world symbol representing its
Z-coordinate.
The depth of a subsector map is kept thin to minimize the number
of "overlapping systems" (i.e., one\'s that are "on top" of one another).
The galaxy is obviously deeper than 5 parsecs, but you simply have
different maps representing "layers" of space.  A sector is 4 layers deep
and is 2 x 2 in the x-y plane.  Yes, it is a _much_ larger volume than in
2D Traveller.  A campaign could take place in two subsectors (10 x 10 x
10 parsec volume).

Okay enough background blithering, here\'s how you navigate:

1. Look at the map and count the number of hexes between departure and
destination (just like in 2D Traveller).

2. Take the absolute difference between the departure and destination
Z-coordinates (i.e., the little numbers in the world symbols).

3. Cross reference on the following table:

DISTANCE IN XY PLANE
0123456
----
V S0|0123456
E E1|123456-
R P2|233456-
T A3|344556-
I R4|45556--
C A5|5666----
A T6|6----
L I
  O
  N

The body of the table shows the jump distance (in parsecs) to the
destination.  In this case, it is the euclidian distance rounded up.  If
you want, you could make it the euclidian distance rounded to the nearest
whole number, giving the excuse that jump drives can be "pushed" for an
extra half parsec.  Either way, this is a quick and approximate means of
doing 3D space navigation.

And that\'s all there is to it!  Admitted, this says nothing to the
political and economic problems converting to 3D would cause, but like I
said previously, it might be worth the effort for marketing reasons.
Lots of SF fans will be turned off by the grossly unrealistic concept of
2D space.

Charles.

