    'from' => 'mstiavel@astro.sns.it',
    'body' => 'I bought 2300AD but never played it. At the time I had a successful MT
campaign and 2300AD did not look to me interesting enough to be worth a
try. The rules looked reasonable although they seemed a bit too much combat
oriented (when I want a wargame I play a wargame). Personally, I do not
like combat intensive role-playing, neither when I am a player nor when I
am the referee (as it often happens).

More importantly, 2300AD was missing the big picture and grand scope
of Classic Traveller. Still, if I had to choose today between a TNE and a
2300AD campaign today I would try 2300AD (and for the same reason..).

One thing I found annoying in 2300AD was the lack of even the most basic
design rules for vehicles and starships in the basic boxed set I bought.
I was very much in favour of the CT philosophy of providing basic design
rules in the standard set and enhanced design rules in a suitable
expansion (especially when the two are compatible..). I also recall that
not much was available on world generation. Both were serious limitations
from my point of view, since I like very much designing
vehicles/starships/etc and also generating worlds.

The fact that starships are a rare commodity in 2300AD is also a limitation.
One runs the risk of reducing a science fiction role-playing to just
an ordinary combat/detective/whatnot  with just better weapons and tools.

              Cheers,
                        Massimo
