    'index' => 'ac449',
    'month' => '01',
    'body' => 'Thu, 25 Jan 1996 01:00:19 +1100 (EST),  Phillip McGregor
>Someone noted that the Tasmanian Aboriginies were wiped out by a mixture of
>being hunted down and disease, the latter mainly while in what he called
>"concentration camps". Well, so what? The people in question were even more
>primitive than the mainland aboriginies, and, IIRC, it was at one stage (and
>may still be, I don\'t know offhand) regarded that they were wiped out on the
>mainland *by* said mainland aboriginies.

As has already been pointed out, you don\'t need to "wipe" anyone out.
A 10% fatality rate is is more than enough to push a wobbly society
over the edge (especialy a technological one).

>They were a *stone age* people. We know that the Vilani were "backward"
>*compared to the Terrans* in their medical technology.

Even today, the sudden onset of unknown disease can cause problems.  Add
to this the fact that the Vilani were not only less developed in biology
(the implication I had is that they were were we were about the late
1800\'s) but specifically, they entire lacked the basis for forming any
working theory of evolution and genetics.  Finally, the lack of FTL
communication means that word of the plague will have trouble spreading
any faster than the plague itself.

So the idea that a society, encountering a virulent disease from a
source they hadn\'t needed to worry about before (virus\'s), for which
the population has almost no resistance to, for which there is little
or no warning, and for which they have no systematic understanding of,
would be in trouble is reasonable.


