    'index' => 'ac458',
    'month' => '01',
    'body' => 'I have always seen the fuedal structure as the "space between the stars"
being fuedalized, and the worlds answering to Sector dukes, Subsector
dukes, and local barons and viscounts. Marquis I place over small clusters.
The local naval units answer not to the people, but the nobles; COACC
answers to the local Gov\'t, Navy doesn\'t.

Here is how I run it (all IMNSHO):

Arch Duke: No real power til 1100 or so, then taxation and employment
reforms, as well as trade law reforms implemented by the archdukes. mostly
the emperor\'s stand-ins for negotiations with extra-imperial cultures.
Normally a retirement for an overly troublesome/meddlesome Sector Duke.

Sector Duke: Controls the Sector Naval, marine, Scout, and intelligence, as
well as sector wide trade and safety regulations.

Subsector Duke/Marquis: controls 1 reserve fleet, and collects taxation.
Same kind of trade governance as the Sector level, but more ability to
adapt it to local demands.

Cluster Marquis/count/Viscount: Administers combined actions of local
navies and
 SS navies. May have a localized "cluster fleet" if the duke allows, mostly
for code enforcement. No really big ships, but plenty of couriers and
patrol craft.

System Baron/Viscount/Count: Controls local navy, and taxes local world for
it\'s support. can be crippled by lack of local gov\'t cooperation, but can
blockade the world in that case. In systems with large non-mainworld
populations, will be a viscount or count. Also controls starport, and
regulates in-system travel. Normally leaves the world alone. Most local
world gov\'t heads are treated as Baronettes; they have to answer to the
baron in intersellar matters, and should take his advice on local matters,
but are autonomous of him, provided they pay their taxes, and provide the
required allotment of draftees or volunteers for the Imperial Forces.

I see the taxation as follows:
Secotr taxes subsector rulers, per capita residents. Charges liscence fees
on starships.
SubSector: Taxes either world nobles or cluster nobles, but not worlds
under a cluster ruler. Such taxes per capita resident.
Cluster: Taxes it\'s member world\'s nobles, per capita resident.
Local: taxes it\'s world on a per capita tax, raised by whatever means the
local gov\'t chooses; also places draft minimums into effect, and gets
percentage of profit from starports and spaceports in system, as well as
portion of local ship registry fees.

ANy noble can authorize "imperial corporate entities"; such entities may
conduct buisiness at any world subject to the chartering individual\'s
taxation, whether direct or indirect. Mega Corps are merely liscenced by
the Emperor or an Archduke.

Some sample costs from my GM\'ing habits:

Liscencing a commercial (passenger or cargo vessel): cr2/ton per year.
requires an inspection by naval or scout authorities, normally done during
annual maintenance. cr1/ton that for non-commercial vessels.

System Corp Liscence: cr1000 per year. Pay to the system noble. Negotiate
with local gov\'t for on-world status, though.
Cluster Corp Liscence: cr10000/year Pay cluster nobleman.
SubSector Corp Lisc: cr25000/year
Sector Lisc: cr100,000/year
Domain Lisc: cr 500,000/year
LIC: MCr1 per year. Pay Sector duke in home sector.

All liscences must be accompanied with a minimum 5% share of the company,
in lieu of income taxation. Ship liscencing allows buisiness to be done
without such a charter, although a line must have one.

Spaceman\'s ticket: = Apprentice cr 100/year
                   = Rating Test cr100 pass or fail, per endorsement sought.
                   = Skilled Liscence cr 200/year, any number of endorsements.
                   = Master\'s ticket (required for all commercial vessels in
                     excess of 499 tons) cr 500/year, endorsements for Nav,
                     Pilot, Engineer, Leader, Admin, Legal, and Computer
                     required to attain.

        Endorsements in my MT games: All require level 1 and a routine,
skill, edu, 1/2 hour, safe task. No retries allowed without paying again.
Standard Endorsements: Pilot, Nav, Steward, medical, Gunnery (each
separate), Gravitics, Vacc Suit, 0-G Ops, Admin, Legal, Broker, Ship\'s
Boat, Electronics, Mechanical, Computer, languages(each separate). Ship\'s
Troops rating requires vacc suit 1+, one close combat skill at 1+, and one
ranged combat at 1+, and successful tests in all three; passed tests do not
require retests.

Reading a person\'s ticket makes it one level easier to determine their
skill levels accurately during an interview. It also allows estimation (one
level harder than base) without meeting the individual. Such a ticket is
actually an ID card, with all the usual imperial ID bells and whistles.

Most crews look for ticket holders with the correct endorsements first,
then apprentice tickets and others without the sought endorsement but with
a ticket, and then for non-ticketed persons, whom they can get a ticket for
by the skipper signing for one.


-Wil

