    'subj' => 're: Whither 2300?',
    'topic' => 're: Whither 2300?',
    'index' => 'ac461',
    'month' => '01',
    'body' => 'I\'ve played in, refereed, and loved Traveller since 1982, and I also read
and used the initial edition of the \'2300 rules from 1986, when it appeared
in Britain for the first time.  Now Eric Ackermann wrote in xboat digest
511 about a possible future for this RPG given the breakup of GDW, and I\'m
not sure whether this is the right environment for the discussion of this
"other" SF game system but I\'d quite like my (briefish) "deux centimes"
worth, and would love to see it reborn and developed in perhaps more caring
hands...

The second edition rules became available from GDW in 1988 and were IMO a
positive development of one of the fastest, most flexible rule systems I\'ve
ever had the pleasure to use.  Possibly 2300AD found itself swamped during
MT\'s early years, maybe this is just the perspective from this side of the
Atlantic, but 2300 never seemed (certainly in terms of its published
adventures) to capture the full potential of its (almost) believable
"future history" and its hard science background.

Coming from a Traveller campaign I was immediately impressed by the Near
Star Map and associated information.  A 3D universe, at last!  Using the
"physics" of stutterwarp drives, this is how the near stellar neighbourhood
_had_ to be explored.  All games need a fundamental background to provide a
framework (whether it\'s Traveller\'s Imperium/Known Space, Space:1889\'s
Victorian Solar System, or whatever) and the NSM provided just that.  It
would have been good to extend the data well beyond "current Human
exploration" though, (+50 ly?) even if only for Referee\'s additional/secret
information.

I found that ex-Traveller players generally hated the lack of both
artificial gravity and anti-gravity, but it led to vacuum-bound starships
with spin habitats that were definitely "Not Traveller": this of course
forced the concept of "Dispense With All Preconceived SF-RPG Ideas".  This
_could_ be real.  This is how it _might_ really be.  Starship design was
(for me, always has been) fun.  Starship combat in "Star Cruiser" could
feel incredibly realistic.  Stay hidden.  Deploy drones and missiles.  Keep
quiet.  When players become paranoid about potentially successful alien
weapon sensor scans...well, I think that\'s a victory in game design terms.

Again, and recently mentioned in the digest, one of 2300\'s great strengths
were its aliens.  They were all excellent but the Kafers, whilst the most
humanoid, were truly and abominably alien.  Their reasoning was totally
flawless given their background and nature, but utterly foreign to Human
ways of perception.  There could only be the one result.  (And thank
goodness for DunArmCo and their assault shotguns, I often found myself
thinking, as the very corners were rolled off my D10\'s in panic).  (Hey, if
any _real_ aliens monitor the xboat\', it _was_ just a game, you know?)

What didn\'t I like?  Well, I expect that like most readers and contributors
to this mailing list, I enjoy altering, amending and adapting "official"
adventures to fit my players\' situations and my own referee-required goals,
but in terms of the published 2300 adventures, there\'s hardly a one that I
used at any level beyond that of background information.  Does this mean
that novice gamers starting on 2300 used the published adventures and began
to hate the very idea of gaming?  Or perhaps that parsec-weary campaigners
hated 2300\'s lack of any decent, continuing adventures/campaignlets that MT
was then in the process of developing?  I don\'t know the answer to this,
and would really like to know what other 2300 referees think, but it
certainly feels like it contributed to the long-term failure of this
otherwise excellent system.  There was also that bizarre and vast dichotomy
between the cyberpunk and decadent Core-World mindset and those trying to
make a (lower-tech, honest) go of it in the Colonies.  It was neither
"Bladerunner" nor "Optimistic 50\'s Heinlein" enough, and the adventures did
not seem to be capable of suggesting either a generic socio-Human feeling
that could create a link between these two World-views or provide the basis
for (rule-based) "home-brewed" options.  Where was it trying to go?  Did
you just use it as a dead-ended, "Aliens"-esque rules set?  I had to,
finally, and did.  Sure, the one-off adventures I wrote were fun for me and
(I think) the players, but I\'m a campaigner at heart, and 2300 as published
didn\'t seem to be the Universe for that kind of playing.

I regret that 2300 failed in the RPG marketplace.  It had some great
strengths and provided many people with a lot of entertainment.  I don\'t
think I can blame GDW for the demise of the game; maybe it\'s our fault
through lack of player support, but I\'d _really_ like to think of a
positive future for what was often a great system.

*** I\'ve just typed my above feelings to find the
<ad2300-request@mars.galstar.com> mailing list address posted on the last
digest.  Time to monitor that, I think, and I\'ll return to lurking here.
Thank you... ***



Andy Goddard
Audio Visual Media Services
University of Strathclyde
Glasgow


