    'date' => 'Thu, 25 Jan 1996 16:02:22 +0000',
    'body' => 'Some recent discussion:

>>We have an immense range from continent to continent (and even withing
>>continents).  Look at Africa.   And we have much faster trade and
>>communications between parts of the world than the Imperium has
>>between systems.
>Yes, it always seemed to me that GDW made these wide variations in TL
>to mimic the situation in our world today. But the wide variations we
>see... today are primarily due to accidents of history...
>But in CT, by 1104 (the year Adv. #1 takes place) accidents of history
>should be, well, history. The Marches have been settled for a thousand
>years, and have shared a common history for that long.

Just to add my 2 cents...
Given the thousands of inhabited systems in the Traveller universe,
potentially each with multiple planets - inhabited or uninhabitable, some
much larger than Earth, etc., I don\'t find it at all unusual that there is a
HUGE variety of technologies spread across them in much the same way that
there will be a HUGE spread of population, history, religion, government,
economy, etc. An entire subsector could be left unexplored for hundreds of
years just because of some adverse encounter by the first explorers, or
because the explorers\' major religion suddenly turned inward and exploration
was frowned upon. Just look at the fight going on today to keep space
exploration funded! Every individual planet will have all the complications
of different atmospheres, flora, fauna, ecosystems, bacteria, etc. against
which any colony must battle to establish itself. Any colony that doesn\'t
reach a given size won\'t be able to support the infrastructures required for
high technology manufacturing, etc. unless they import - and to do that they
have to have something to trade. If you can\'t produce the high tech goods
initially then you have to produce lower tech goods and/or refine raw
materials from the system in which you\'ve settled. Perhaps in a hundred
years time you can grow the population sufficiently to support the next one
or two technology levels. That\'s assuming your populace hasn\'t succumbed to
the new religion which requires only every fifth woman to be allowed to give
birth...

Remember that there are always limitations to ANY system. As a simple
example, apart from jump drive, you can\'t break the speed of light. So radio
communications between two points will never get faster. Perhaps you can
increase the bandwidth to fit in more info, but eventually the whole radio
spectrum fills up (especially given the amount of data transfer that seems
inherent in most futuristic societies).... there\'s always a limit.

So, I can easily see where the diversity of techs, etc. across the Imperium
occurs. However, there are certainly a large number of
difficult-to-rationalise UWPs for many planets. If people can explain tiny
worlds having thick atmospheres, or habital worlds in systems where the
planet should be an iceball or a fiery inferno, then I\'m, sure a few tech
differences can be explained away.

Enough warbling. More work to do. :-(

Andy

