    'from' => 'Nick Munn nsm14@cus.cam.ac.uk',
    'body' => 'On Fri, 26 Jan 1996 xboat@MPGN.COM wrote:

> From: A.S.Lilly@bnr.co.uk (Andy Lilly)
> Subject: Low Tech in the Imperium

[Cheap work-force at low TLs, unwillingness to confer military tech.]

> Anyone care to work out similar or alternative strategies for the other
> races: Zhodani, etc.?

Zhodani: More interested in pyschic development than TL development at a
governmental level. No way the Consulate are going to arm people who
don\'t sincerely believe in the Consulate and what it stands for -- and
they\'re going to know! Commercial concerns will also stagnate tech
equalisation, as in the Imperium. Plus a lot of effort is going into the
Core Expeditions, not social development.

Solomani: Sol Sec probably want control of military elements themselves.
As we know, Terrans are rather pushy compared to Vilani, so there\'ll be
more of a Technology Rat Race, but the Party will dampen this a bit.

Vilani: The Ziru Sirk\'aa is too conservative (and too high tech) to
develop much new technology. I would expect a large degree of homogeneity
on Vilani-culture worlds; of course, later-settled worlds, or worlds with
"minor race" inhabitants, or "reserved" worlds (for later exploitation)
could all have lower TLs.

Vargr: Devil take the hindmost! Fiercely competitive, not given to
cooperation, Vargr tech levels are known to vary wildly from world to
world.

Aslan: Technologies can often be a jealously-guarded Clan secret; thus,
worlds which aren\'t entirely loyal to a single Clan may see less
development than those which are. Read "Shogun" if you want an idea of
what I mean...

Hivers, Kkree and Droyne I don\'t know about.

Darrians suffered from the Maaghiz; tech level imbalance there is a
relatively recent historical accident. The Spinward Marches have in any
case been developing for the last millenium, so it\'s fair to argue that
the Darrian "background" isn\'t stable.

Nick

