    'date' => 'Mon, 29 Jan 1996 02:37:51 +0100 (NFT)',
    'body' => 'In his last two posts Phil McGregor manages to very effectively express what
I also firmly believe. Something may look hard science fiction for a couple
of years but it will not last long. A game should last more than that and
therefore should have flexible rules leaving a lot to imagination.

Traveller is completely unrealistic from several points of view:
social (govern by idle and protagonist nobles? you must be joking),
military (dukes order sector admirals? sure..), economic (low salaries,
no robotics), astronomical (abitable planets around Deneb),
physical (jump drive, antigrav, thrusters, yeahh), etc.

STill I consider it the best role-playing game of all times (I am
thinking to Classical Traveller).

Why? I do not care about hard science. I care about a roughly consistent
picture, I care about a bright future, I care about roleplaying, I care
about mystery. When you tell me that Grandfather was a power hungry
error-prone dictator I can accept it. When a grand-duke kills the
emperor I can perhaps accept it. But when you talk about a virus
I stop wasting my money.

Not only I would like to see a post-rebellion timeline without the
virus, I would also like a timeline without rebellion...

                                             Cheers,

                                                   Massimo

P.S. as far as I can see real hard science fiction has more to do with
convicing politicians and public that some real smart idea is worth trying.
Bad thing is that scientists themselves disagree on what is a real smart
idea..
----
