I have to admit that I never played the TNE rules, but that\'s because I
hated the look of them just glancing at them in the store.  MT was a
revision of CT, and (I thought) an improvement.  TNE, however, was an
entirely different game--both in terms of the setting and the system.  Once
you abandoned D6\'s and changed all the skills and attributes around, it just
wasn\'t TRAVELLER anymore, as far as I was concerned.

As for the "dont\' use it if you don\'t like it" argument for FF&S, you don\'t
always have that option.  If, using your example, characters are paying
passengers on a starship, deck plans could be important (depending on what
you\'re planning to do to them...), and  so it *does* matter how much tonnage
is taken up by engineering, gunnery, etc.

While I\'m here, I have to say that I fully agree with Phil McGregor on the
issue of keeping one\'s science fiction internally consistent rather than
having it agree with the latest scientific fads.  I would point out, though,
that the same argument could be made for keeping the tech level designations
the way they are.  It\'s a lot simpler than revising the old system (which
works) and also remember how vague the whole basic world generation is anyway.

