  {
    'body' => 'Here\'s a brief summary of the jump torpedo debate as I see it:

1) After a long hiatus, Phil McGregor strikes out of nowhere saying that
we\'re all ninnys for not allowing them and proposes a plausible though
challengeable system for how they might work.

2) I replied that this presented a problem for the Traveller background
in that it would render the X-boat network obsolete and would allow "jump
gates" that larger star ships could use.

3) Phil retorted with "of course it does, that\'s part of my background!"
(paraphrased).

4) Alun came up with a number of reasons why jump torps could not replace
X-boats. Namely:  Limited storage, security, cost, and politics.

5) Someone (sorry I forget the name) replied with a number of challenges
to Alun\'s proposals.

6) A number of others have cited some minor references hinting at the
existence of jump torps.

Sorry to anyone I left out, but these are the salient messages in
my opinion.  Now here are some of my responses to these.

To Phil:
You can have warp drives and phasers in _your_ background for all I care,
but the debate here is about the Traveller universe.  Granted that jump
torps are mentioned in Leviathan, but that was put out by DGP and GDW
seems to have jumped on their apparent error after publication, stating
that these torps were Ancients artifacts.  Having jump torps and jump
gates in the Traveller universe is going to change it fundamentally.  As
others have mentioned, one of the fundamental aspects of the Traveller
universe is slow communication speeds.  GDW has specifically mentioned
this as one of the bases for their background:  The communication
system is analogous to the 18th century (paraphrased from "The Traveller
Book").
Your explanation for why the Imperium doesn\'t officially use jump
gates seems a little thin to me.  You basically said that the Vilani are
stodgy and don\'t like to change systems very often.  What about other
nations?  The Darrians, Sword Worlders, and Zhodani (to name a few) all
use jump ships instead of jump gates.  Why?  And why has their never been
mention of jump gates anywhere?


To Alun:

Here are your reasons for why jump torps could not replace X-boats, and
my objections to them.

Limited Storeage Capacity:  I don\'t think this is true.  We can hold
several terrabytes of info in something a few cubic meters in volume
now.  By TL 10 or 12, storage capacities should be virtually unlimited by
our standards.

Lack of Security:  Someone pointed out that you could easily have a jump
torp come in system and tight beam its message at a ground station.  This
is a TL-8 procedure.  It could then erase its messages to prevent enemy
interception.

High Cost:  This one is hard to figure.  Some people have argued that the
jump torps should be disposable because the cost of recovery would be too
high.  I disagree.  You just have to put a small dirt-cheap chemical
rocket or ion drive on it, and it can eventually guide itself into orbit
around whatever system body you like.  Depending on where it comes in,
recovery time might be days, weeks or months, but in a continuously
running communication system, this wouldn\'t be a problem.
The real question is a matter of reliability to cost ratio.  If a
jump torp only arrives at its destination 90% of the time, then why not
send two?  Chance of message not getting through would be 1%.  If the
odds of success are lower, just send more.  The only limiting factor here
is cost. If jump torps cost enough, and are unreliable enough, then this
scheme isn\'t economical.  But I can\'t see the torps costing much, as they
would be mass produced in droves, and would have no need for life
support.  Also, you save on salaries for a lot of people.

Politics:  You stated that anyone trying to challenge the Imperial X-boat
service would dealt with promptly, implying that they would be put out of
business by political maneuvering and so on.  This _might_ be an
explanation for the continuing existence of X-boats in the Imperium
(though I\'ve seen several posts arguing convincingly that it would not),
but it does not explain  why many other governments  use exactly the same
system.  Do the Zhodani and Solomani also have monopolistic
communications companies that crush any attempts at inovation?

All this to say that if jump torps were allowed by eliminating
the 100 ton rule (i.e., if they were allowed by the physics of the
Traveller universe), then they would be used extensively and would change
the Traveller universe in many fundamental ways, not the least of which
is the marginalization of the X-boat network.  X-boats could still be
used to carry cargo and such, but it would most likely be much faster
and more economical to have small unmanned vessels carrying the messages
if this was possible.

Charles.

