    'body' => 'More Comments on how j-torps do or don\'t change the CT background.

>Date: Wed, 31 Jan 1996 15:15:26 -0800
>From: Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers)

>>        Even without j-torps, the navy has always had this capability.
>>Problem is, the information you gather is two weeks old before the main
>>fleet arrives. That\'s true with both j-torps and scout ships.

>But, above and beyond the two week problem (which is not what I was
>refering too), you also have the problem that you risk loosing ships
>due to enemy action when they enter a system.  This is a fundamental
>military problem that jump torps do away with.  (And, BTW, the
>info arrives _two_ weeks after you sent it, but it is _one_ week
>old.  I guess all your thinking is indeed failable).

Of course my thinking is fallible, as is yours.

The moment before the fleet arrives in its target system, the information about
the system that it read off of the j-torp last week, is now TWO weeks
old. Think about it.

>>I\'m not aware that GDW ever presented j-torps as being faster than
>>X-boats.

>Why can\'t they be.  Unless you want to impose some arbitrary
>restriction on them.

Well, actually I DO want to impose a j-4 restriction on them, but that\'s
beside the point. If you allow civilians j-5 and j-6 drives, then they
can build ships that can outrace the X-boats. If outracing an X-boat
route makes a problem for your campaign, then you need to come up with
an explanation for why it never (or rarely) happens. Once you have an
explanation that works for j-6 liners, I would imagine it might work for
j-6 torpedoes too.

>>        I\'ve never had to make any change at all in the background.

>Maybe you haven\'t thought it through as well as you claim.  Even
>something as fundamental as the spread of the news of Stephon\'s
>assination has to be changed (in addition to marginalizing the
>X-boat system).

I think I\'ve thought through the background pretty well.

News of Strephon\'s death travelled to the Spinward Marches through j-6
Imperiallines couriers. I don\'t see how j-torps (at TL15) could be any
faster than that.

>>(Well, I had to make one. Before I bought Leviathan, I had told my
>>players that jump vehicles couldn\'t be under 100 tons.

>Everytime your players use jump torps to do something they
>couldn\'t do before, you have and example of how you have changed
>things at the player level.

You\'re absolutely right of course. The introduction of j-torps
did affect the player-character\'s lives. But it didn\'t really change the culture
and history of the Imperium.

>>J-torps affect the
>>X-boat network about as much as automated drones affect Federal Express
>>today.

>I\'m not sure what you mean.  Are you saying that if I could buy a machine
>that delivers my package faster than Federal Express, without my
>ever having to go to a Fed Exp office (or wait for pickup), to
>any destination regardless how remote from federal express offices
>it is, that it wouldn\'t affect Federal Express?  Boloney.

Sorry my statement was so vague. Let me try again.

It wouldn\'t affect FedEx\'s earnings very much. (It would, of course
affect one\'s own relationship with FedEx a lot.) Such a drone system is
possible with today\'s technology. The drone could be smaller than a
FedEx jet, and it would be unmanned, so you wouldn\'t have to pay any
pilot\'s salary. But you and I both know that it would be ridiculously
expensive to build such a beastie. If you were rich enough to buy one of
the navy\'s experimental robot airplanes, you could obviously have your
own neat, high-tech replacement of many of FedEx\'s services. This might
affect your own life (and adventures!) quite alot. But the rest of us
drudges will go on using a more mundane courier. (\'cause it\'s cheaper!)
The overall business climate and culture of the USA would be unchanged,
I think.

You may think differently, of course, but that doesn\'t mean my notion is
baloney. Nor does it mean that I haven\'t thought through the
consequenses of CT\'s j-torps thoroughly.

Well I\'ve "droned" on enough about this...

>Date: 01 Feb 96 11:19:27 +0100
>From: robert.brennan@isocor.ie

Regarding the feasibility of X-boats in the first place:

>Sorry to say, but in HG it\'s very possible to build J-4 ships with
>maneuver at about 120-150tons.  Probably at TL15 these could be J-5.
>You see, one thing that always surprised me about any traveller design
>sequences was that all the example ships built by GDW sucked!  I think
>that this was because their  ships were built by people who "knew" how
>they should turn out.  If you let a bunch of players at the design
>sequences with a spreadsheet, then you\'d get some quirkey designs
