    'month' => '02',
    'body' => 'Fri, 2 Feb 96 08:58:37 MST, stedee@auto-trol.com (Steve Deemer)
>David P. Summers writes:
>>I\'m not sure what you mean.  Are you saying that if I could buy a machine
>>that delivers my package faster than Federal Express, without my
>>ever having to go to a Fed Exp office (or wait for pickup), to
>>any destination regardless how remote from federal express offices
>>it is, that it wouldn\'t affect Federal Express?  Boloney.

>Well, if it cost a million dollars per package, each time you used it,
>you\'d probably begin to think that Federal Express wasn\'t such a bad
>deal after all. And if Federal Express owned rights to the technology
>and got a royality every time you used the machine, they probably wouldn\'t
>mind either way what you did.

This goes under the heading of imposing arbitrary restrictions
to make it work.  (in this case making j-torps arbitrarily expensive).
Aside from the problem that these restrictions always have their own
side effects (how do you enforce these restictions, are their smugglers,
if so why don\'t you see them?  it still doesn\'t explain the fact
that jump torps don\'t eleminate the need to have hugely expensive
networks of jump-6 couriers [since they are secret anyway you aren\'t
going to worry about a few  regs], or why you don\'t see them outside
the Imperium, etc.  Then you need to put in even more arbitrary
rulings on how things work, but then these all have their own
consequences), the main problem is that imposing arbitrary conditions
so that a technology doesn\'t have any effect but one carefully selected
one tends make the background seem the mush more arbitrary and that
much more hokey.

Introducing new technologies that seem cute without thing through
all the implications has ruin many a good background.

>If the machine had the possibility of going off in the wrong direction
>and posing a hazard to the general public, there are various legal and
>regulatory agencies who\'d probably care very much when and where you
>used your machine.

And how do jump torps do any of this anymore than an X-boat?

>Even though we\'re all using e-mail, the Post Office is still doing some
>business.  They haven\'t been completely marginalized by this example of
>new and better technology.

Well, in fact they already have been partially marginallized.  The
only thing they are used for is (aside from packages) is slow, cheap
delivery and delivery where you need the original.  Anything else
is either e-mailed or faxed.  This process is continuing.

>Reading the news, the PO is now attempting to
>set itself up as some kind of controller for e-mail, applying some type
>of virtual "stamp" to every piece of e-mail for starters, with the
>implication that we would all be billed for this service. Think that might
>have an impact on how we use this technology?

I\'ve not heard of it.  Probably because it is just a dumb, pointless
idea that won\'t even come close to the light of day.  However, even
it were to happen, it wouldn\'t be what you are claiming.  The anology
wouldn\'t be banning j-torps to keep x-boats around (which is as doomed
to failure as trying to ban e-mail to keep the mail service going) but
more like the people that run the x-boat network setting up a
jump-torp network (either way x-boats still get replaced).

[Note, just so we don\'t forget, loss of the x-boat network is only
one problem that jump-torps introduce to the background (I\'ve
mentioned some before) and even you patch enough arbitrary restrictions
to keep x-boats going, you still have to deal with those.]

