    'ts-index' => '1996-02-02.ac525',
    'date' => 'Fri, 2 Feb 1996 17:41:49  0500 (EST)',
    'body' => 'Hi All. In the last Xboat, Tom Trelenberg asked:

>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>
My question concerns a conversion between starship damage and some of
the 10D+ damages that can be achieved from weapons in Book 4: Mercenary.
Starship damage is done in "hits" (i.e. each laser that hit gets to
role once on the "hit location" table of Book 2, missles get 1D6 "hits"
and High Gaurd has other tables).  Is there any official (or working
unofficial) method to determine how many pts of damage (e.g. 16D)
constitues a "hit" if the weapon is used to fire at a starship.
If anyone has any workable scheme on this I\'d like to hear it.
<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<

Generally speaking a personal weapon can never do significant damage to a
ship.  An average hull can take 1000 points of "personal weapons" damage
from lasers before a man-sized hole is made. Even an iris valve can take
100 (both of these figures are in "The Traveller Book" I think).  So even
a weapon doing 10D needs to fire three shots to get through a valve and
about 30 to get through a hull.  This assumes that someone is just walking
up to the side of the ship and trying to blast into the hull.  You could
rule that someone walking right up to a turret and firing an FGMP down the
barrel would disable the turret (but, of course, that\'s a _bad_ place for
your FGMP toting guy to be :-).

As far as I know, other than these 1000 hit point and 100 hit point
values, there are no conversion from personal weapons to starship damage
in CT.  Going the other way, I vaguely remember reading somewhere that a
laser can make a 50 meter radius beaten zone by rapid firing from orbit.
Any human in that area is toast, and I imagine most vehicles as well.

Hope this is useful to you.
Charles.

