    'subj' => 'Xboat vs. Jtorps',
    'from' => 'pierre-louis constantin Pierre-Louis.Con',
    'body' => 'Hi!

How does one subscribe to the Jtorps mailing list?

Just kidding!   Hm, you can remove your claws from my face
now.

MHO about J-torps:
1) For delivering mail:  It seems to me that unmanned jump torps for
delivering mail would be unreliable;  no engineer on board, no
guarantees of how things go once the jump is completed, no defense
mechanisms, etc.  Sending email through j-torps means taking the risk
of losing your mail.  Also j-torps cannot carry parcels, just data.
It seems to me that market pressures would push j-torps use to a few
niche markets; 1. Bulk mail  2. Military uses.
1. Bulk mail is rarely urgent, so the jump drives would be
something like J-2 rating on average.  This is consistent with the
rate of information progpagation across the imperium.
2. Military uses is what Dulinor used. :)

2) As a weapon:  The only problem I see with this is that if you use
a relatively realistic drive (i.e. no reactionless plates) your
missile will need a lot of fuel, and so be on a size comparable with
very small starships.  Not a stealthy weapon at all.  You also need
to feed your nav computer with accurate intelligence so as to hit the
right target. Intelligence gathering is relatively expensive, and now
your have to risk million-credit missiles on it.    Not a very good
gamble.
There are 2 ways out of these problems; One is to use micro-jump
missiles, which reduces your need for intelligence, fuel, and since
you only need a jump-1 drive your missiles can be quite small.  IN
fact this could be a very good strategic weapon, if you coordinate
your fleet with your j-torp/j-missile arrivals.
The second idea would be to not send a simple j-missile, but an
actual warbot with strategic planning programs.  The size of a medium
starship, it can jump into a system, latch onto an ore-rich asteroid,
deploy its autofactor and starts building an arsenal in-system.  Of
course this is a long-term device but it would be almost undetectible
until it\'s too late for the ennemy.  I admit this is more far-fetched
but hey, it sounds fun to me. :)

Maybe I should warn you that my Traveller world uses modified
HepLar engines (very low fuel consumption in athmosphere - but if oyu
need to manuever in space, you better plan it beforehand!) and
instantaneous communications in very limited cases - and it still
feel very Traveller-esque.  So maybe you should take my ideas with a
grain of salt. :)

--
Pierre-Louis Constantin, ift. a. "He whose name was writ in E-mail."
Independentist: My Canada excludes the federal bureaucracy :)
