    'index' => 'ac537',
    'month' => '02',
    'body' => 'Some more fuel for the flames about j-torps.

>Date: Fri, 2 Feb 1996 13:56:36 -0800
>From: Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers)

David:
>>>I\'m not sure what you mean.  Are you saying that if I could buy a machine
>>>that delivers my package faster than Federal Express, without my
>>>ever having to go to a Fed Exp office (or wait for pickup), to
>>>any destination regardless how remote from federal express offices
>>>it is, that it wouldn\'t affect Federal Express?  Boloney.

Steve:
>>Well, if it cost a million dollars per package, each time you used it,
>>you\'d probably begin to think that Federal Express wasn\'t such a bad
>>deal after all. And if Federal Express owned rights to the technology
>>and got a royality every time you used the machine, they probably wouldn\'t
>>mind either way what you did.

David:
>This goes under the heading of imposing arbitrary restrictions
>to make it work.  (in this case making j-torps arbitrarily expensive).

Me:
Hmm... I guess I don\'t see how anybody (you included) can avoid making
arbitrary restrictions on j-torp technology. Steve and I arbitrarily
restrict them by assuming high production costs. You arbitrarily
restrict them by assuming they can\'t exist. (At least, I think that\'s
what you assume; this thread has been going on so long now that I may
not remember correctly! (^8"  ) Every game system requires restrictions.
And when the game is about something that does not exist (and can not
exist!) like "Jump Drive," these restrictions are going to be arbitrary.
There\'s no way around it!

The only non-arbitrary solution is to abolish all jump drives, in
torpedoes and in anything else. But I don\'t propose to adopt any
solution so reasonable as that. It just wouldn\'t be fun! 8^)

David:
...Stuff Deleted...
>.........  Then you need to put in even more arbitrary
>rulings on how things work, but then these all have their own
>consequences), the main problem is that imposing arbitrary conditions
>so that a technology doesn\'t have any effect but one carefully selected
>one tends make the background seem the mush more arbitrary and that
>much more hokey.

Hokeyness is a perennial problem in all science fiction, Traveller
included. Since arbitrary restrictions on magical technology cannot be
avoided, one has to cover up the hokeyness with well reasoned
environments and good old fashioned showmanship. I always thought that
CT did a particularly good job with this. It\'s why I like the game.

>Introducing new technologies that seem cute without thing through
>all the implications has ruin many a good background.

I couldn\'t agree more with the principle. But I need to point out that
j-torps are not "new." They\'ve been around for quite awhile now. Longer
than FFS by a decade.

...More stuff deleted...
>[Note, just so we don\'t forget, loss of the x-boat network is only
>one problem that jump-torps introduce to the background (I\'ve
>mentioned some before) and even you patch enough arbitrary restrictions
>to keep x-boats going, you still have to deal with those.]

Back to the old argument regarding military tactics. I believe
you said words to the effect of, "J-torps make it safer for a scout ship
to jump into an enemy-occupied system. A scout ship can launch a j-torp back
to the main fleet faster than it or a companion could jump back itself.
In the pre-j-torp universe, such scouts might be blasted before they got
a shot at returning."

I don\'t think the tactical situation will be any different with
or without j-torps. Here\'s why: The scout mother ship can launch a
subsidiary starship as fast as it could launch a torpedo. (See the Book
5 rules for launching ships.) The way I see it, the introduction of
j-torps changed nothing in the cannon. At least not in this instance.

-Rob
