    'body' => '>The moment before the fleet arrives in its target system, the information about
>the system that it read off of the j-torp last week, is now TWO weeks
>old. Think about it.

I did.  The message they recieve off of a j-torp is 1 week old.  You
2 week number depends on an arbitrary assumption about what they
are doing and what they are going to do next.  Quibles about how
old the information is when they finish depends on what they
do with the info and is just semantics.

>Well, actually I DO want to impose a j-4 restriction on them, but that\'s
>beside the point. If you allow civilians j-5 and j-6 drives, then they
>can build ships that can outrace the X-boats.

The Imperium didn\'t restrict X-boats.  They just chose to build
the network at jump-4 (and nobody else has the means or the desire
to build their own).  Restricting j-trops to jump-4 is like
resticting people from building jump-6 ships.  It\'s a significant
change in the background.  As I already mentioned, you have to
explain why they did it, how people in the Imperium feel and
react to the restiction, how they can enforce it, why you don\'t
see them outside the Imperium, etc. (and those explinations will
each have their own consequenced).

But even then, you aren\'t out of the woods.  Even at jump-4 j-torps
offer service to the majority of worlds that don\'t reside, meaning
that being on the X-boat network doesn\'t mean much.  Also, you have
the problem that if j-torps are availble how were some people able
to get news of Stephon\'s death faster by mainting hugely expensive
networks of jump-6 couriers.  Additionally, not matter what the
timing, a jump torp is a way of getting information about a system
without risking ships.  These are only the problems that have come
up so far.

>If outracing an X-boat
>route makes a problem for your campaign, then you need to come up with
>an explanation for why it never (or rarely) happens.

Outracing X-boats with expensive systems of jump-6 couriers is
a part of the Traveller background (it\'s how a select few have been
able to get a monopoly on timely information).  Introducing torps
that make the capability widely available fundamentally changes
that.  Reread the description of how word of Stephon\'s death
was spread and who benefited.

>I think I\'ve thought through the background pretty well.

So do I, and I\'m not impressed by claims that you are somehow
more up on the problem.  Particularly when I don\'t find the
arguements themselves that convincing.

>News of Strephon\'s death travelled to the Spinward Marches through j-6
>Imperiallines couriers. I don\'t see how j-torps (at TL15) could be any
>faster than that.

The problem there is that such news was only available to a select
few because of the huge expense of maintaining a fleet of jump-6
couriers.  Jump torps make this available to factions that didn\'t
have the news.

>        You\'re absolutely right of course. The introduction of j-torps
>did affect the player-character\'s lives. But it didn\'t really change the
>culture
>and history of the Imperium.

You have a technology that is so useful to PC\'s but has no affect on
the society as a whole?  Even without the problems mentioned above
this strains credulity.

>>I\'m not sure what you mean.  Are you saying that if I could buy a machine
>>that delivers my package faster than Federal Express, without my
>>ever having to go to a Fed Exp office (or wait for pickup), to
>>any destination regardless how remote from federal express offices
>>it is, that it wouldn\'t affect Federal Express?  Boloney.
>
>Sorry my statement was so vague. Let me try again.
>
>It wouldn\'t affect FedEx\'s earnings very much. (It would, of course
>affect one\'s own relationship with FedEx a lot.)

First of all, effecting how the Imperium relates to the X-boat
network is the fundamental problem.

>Such a drone system is
>possible with today\'s technology. The drone could be smaller than a
>FedEx jet, and it would be unmanned, so you wouldn\'t have to pay any
>pilot\'s salary.  But you and I both know that it would be ridiculously
>expensive to build such a beastie. If you were rich enough to buy one of
>the navy\'s experimental robot airplanes, you could obviously have your
>own neat, high-tech replacement of many of FedEx\'s services.

Apples and Oranges.  The problem is that you aren\'t sending your
Fed Ex drones through space where they can\'t run into anyone or
anything, but into airspace crowded with civilian traffic flying
over more innocent people.  Also, you preprogram a ship to jump
and off it goes (one of the reasons for postulating j-torps in
the first place), unlike flying an plane.

>You may think differently, of course, but that doesn\'t mean my notion is
>baloney. Nor does it mean that I haven\'t thought through the
>consequenses of CT\'s j-torps thoroughly.

