    'topic' => 'X-boats vs. J-torps: another angle',
    'body' => 'With regards the current thread of jump-torps, I would like to toss in my
$0.02 worth.

Using FFS, I constructed a TL-14 X-boat with 1,000 (yes, I said *one
thousand*) flight computers in addition to the five model Fb computers. 
Why?  Well, because:

	a) I needed something to replace the non-existant maneuver drive
(and fuel);

	b) I needed a way to simulate the "extensive array of databanks"
the damn things supposedly had (but never really did in the official
write-ups) since the earliest days of CT.  

Why use flight computers?  Because for X MCr, I could have Y TL-14 Mod Std
computers, or Y*1000 TL-14 Mod Flt computers.  If each flight computer
(which is 1/10 the size and mass of a standard computer) has just 1/20
(i.e., 5%) the data storage capacity of a standard computer, I\'ve still
crammed *fifty* times the capacity of a standard computer for the *same*
cost!  

What does this have to do with the discussion, you ask?  Well, since an
X-boat can carry such a *huge* amount of data (at least, in my campaign),
it now becomes economically feasible for the IISS to run the X-boat
Network.  

And as for the jump-torps, I\'ve built one using FFS that had *one* flight
computer in it.  That\'s one-tenth of one percent of the capacity of an
X-boat.  

Conclusion: X-boats *are* feasible, and so are jump-torps; but each in
their own special circumstances.  The analogy of the X-boat Network being
the USPS and the jump-torps being FedEx is a good one.

Hope this helps!

Franklin W. Cain

