>Actually, it\'s just math.

Not really.  The math is trivial.  The problem is that your definition
of "old" depends on how long it takes to get to a certain point in one
course of action arbitarily chosen from a whole set of possibilities.
In fact, I can think of one where the information from the torp is
not only not 2 weeks old, but it isn\'t even 1 week old (you send
it into the system and jump near the system to recieve the data).

>>The Imperium didn\'t restrict X-boats.  They just chose to build
>>the network at jump-4 (and nobody else has the means or the desire
>>to build their own).  Restricting j-trops to jump-4 is like
>
>I never said the Imperium restricted X-boats. I did say the presence or
>lack of restrictions is beside the point.

Well what you said was...
"Well, actually I DO want to impose a j-4 restriction on them"

If the Imperium isn\'t restricting them, what is?  Are you going
to arbitrarily say they can\'t go faster than j-4?

You did also try and claim the restriction was besides the point
because otherwise civilian ships need to be restricted to
avoid out racing X-boats.  Specifically, you said...
"but that\'s
beside the point. If you allow civilians j-5 and j-6 drives, then they
can build ships that can outrace the X-boats."

However, this only points up one of the problems with j-torps.  The
fact that only a few factions of the Imperium can afford the huge cost
of keeping up a network of j-6 couriers means that they can out-race
the X-boat network and get important info before anyone else.  The
high cost of j-6 ships is a partial restriction, and cheaper J-torps
make such a information available to factions that can\'t keep of a
network of couriers.

>Even at jump-4, starships offer service to the majority of worlds.
>A starship can deliver any message a j-torp can. The introduction
>of j-torps adds nothing to this situation.

To many worlds, visits of any ship, let alone a jump-6 ones, are
infrequent.  With jump torps a world can keep torp sitting around
to send off if they need.  It hardly pays to keep a jump-6 ship
and a crew just sitting around.

[Regarding jump-torps vs networks of jump-6 couriers...]
>How would the introduction of j-torps make the capability any more
>widely available than starships? J-torps can\'t do anything a starship
>can\'t do.

Fine if a jump-torp costs as much as jump-6 courier and requires
a crew as costly just keep around.  Regardless of the implausibility
of this (which has already been covered), let me ask...  Do you charge
the cost of a jump-6 courier ship to your PC\'s for every jump-torp
they have?  Do you require them to maintain an whole new crew just
to use one?  The cost of a jump-6 network is prohibitive to all but
a few, cheaper jump-torps makes such networld pointless.


>>You have a technology that is so useful to PC\'s but has no affect on
>>the society as a whole?  Even without the problems mentioned above
>>this strains credulity.
>
>This doesn\'t strain credulity at all. My players have a starship. They
>NEVER book passage on liners. And yet the loss of their business somehow
>does not put the big merchant princes into bankruptcy.  That\'s because
>most people do not own starships. Just like most people do not own
>j-torps. Players are not most people.

Most people don\'t own starships, but everytime someone sends a message
it goes by some who does.  And just like jump-torps affect your PC\'s,
they affect these people (and those who might be able to compete
with them if jump torps were around.)  By affecting how every message
is sent, they affect the whole Imperium.  You want a technology that
is important to your PC\'s to have no affect on the Imperium, technology
doesn\'t work that way.

>>Apples and Oranges.  The problem is that you aren\'t sending your
>>Fed Ex drones through space where they can\'t run into anyone or
>>anything, but into airspace crowded with civilian traffic flying
>>over more innocent people.  Also, you preprogram a ship to jump
>>and off it goes (one of the reasons for postulating j-torps in
>>the first place), unlike flying an plane.
>
>All of the problems you mentioned for drones can be gotten around.

It depends on what you mean by "gotten around".  The problems
of your drones are more fundamental than for jump torps (as
I pointed out).

>The
>one problem that can\'t be gotten around is one you don\'t mention.
>Expense. Widespread use of drones is economically unfeasible.

Because the cost of totally restructuring the air traffic system,
and resticting a very profitable passenger system, makes the
cost of such a system more than an order of magnitude than
the system now in use?  Are you claiming that j torps cost more
than a jump-6 ship?  (see comments above).

However, if you could "get around" the problems, then your drones
would, in fact, marginalize Fed. Ex.  However, this wouldn\'t
actually happen because Fed. Ex. is already being margninalized
by fax and e-mail (just like X-boats and mail boats would be
marginalized by jump torps).


