    'body' => 'David P. Summers a dit (6 fevrier 1996):
>went to the huge expense of mainting fleets of j-6 couriers
>and why j-torps didn\'t make such information much more widely
>available.

1. Torpedoes are not manned.  They are not armed.  There is a
better chance of seeing Dulinor wearing a bright red suit than having
a military organization basically put sensitive intelligence in a
unmanned, unescorted 4 megacredit bottle big as a speeder.  Yes, it
might
be almost impossible for an ennemy to detect it, but the chance
exists.
Also you need 2 (30 MCr) ships to launch and gather the torpedo.
A single 30+ MCr courrier (given J-6 rating) might be more
economical,
and safer too.

Unless a *network* of J-torps is established, there is the problem of
knowing when to expect a torpedo.  MilSpec Message torpedoes will NOT
announce their arrival in a system.  They\'ll just wait for an encoded
radio signal to reach them and use a laser comm to instruct the
collector
ship of its position.  Unless there is an established routine, (or
you have autonomous j-torps, which are not much smaller than
courriers
after all), it will be costlier to use a j-torp than a courrier.

 there is no proof that they did not ALSO use J-6 message torpedoes.
This doesn\'t affect the Traveller background one bit.

2. Why aren\'t J-torps more common?
        Let\'s assume that they ARE rather common - as j-4 and j-6
 torpedoes.
 The J-4 torps seem less expensive than XBoat.  However there is
still
 the problem of autonomy and retrieval.  A Xboat route does not
simply
 carry messages either.  And XBoats are a guarantee of certain
Imperial
 standards.  Planets on XBoat routes are generally better off than
 planets who aren\'t on the routes.  So it is quite possible that
 most systems will lobby for a XBoat route instead of a JTorp route.

 What about the planets not on the routes?  They probably won\'t use
 JTorps because of obvious mail robbery problems.
 The place most likely to use such a route would probably be for
 aslans sending email back to their home quandrant through the rift.
There
 is very little reason to send parcels back, the few systems useables
 for that can be easily protected and each clan can have its own
JTorp
 route back to the main aslan equivalent of XBoats.

 As for J-6 torps, do they affect the background so much?
 Well, one way to see how their existance did not affect the
background
 so much is to realize that 6JTorps are a single, point-to-point
shot.
 There are no J-6 networks because they\'re too expensive (especially
 considering the various taxes imposed on J-6 drives by the
goverments:)
 and also because there aren\'t that many places where TL15 spaceship
 tech can be maintained - especially closer to the frontier.
 MegaCorps will gladly pay that much money when there is an emergency
-
 from one point to another.  Not as a network.  And MegaCorps keep
their
 info to themselves.  So the way the information spread does not
 necessarily contredicts the way it has when there were news of
Strephon\'s
 death, for instance.

 In any case, that is how I fit J-torps in my campaign and I don\'t
think
 it messes up the background at all.

 I suppose someone will have to come up with correct figures to see
if
 my argument holds up. :)

PS: Considering how malleable Jump Tech has been in the past (ah, the
glorious days of jump tugs :) I believe people should tolerate
J-torps
as at least semi-canon.  After all Leviathan was published by GDW. :)
Oh - there are only 2 rules against it, really:  The minimum size of
a
ship, and also that ships require at least 2 crewmen.  If you stick
to
the rule too much, you get some silliness.  Ah well, maybe if we
strap
the pilot and the engineer to the outside of the torpedo? :)


