Wed, 7 Feb 1996, pierre-louis constantin <Pierre-Louis.Constantin@DMI.USherb.CA>

>1. Torpedoes are not manned.  They are not armed.  There is a
>better chance of seeing Dulinor wearing a bright red suit than having
>a military organization basically put sensitive intelligence in a
>unmanned, unescorted 4 megacredit bottle big as a speeder.

Xboats aren\'t armed either.  They have security the same way torps
would.  The ship that launches the trop protects it at one end (or the
info gets sent on a tight beam moments before launch).  At the
other end all it has to do is send the info on a tigh beam
and then erase it.

>Also you need 2 (30 MCr) ships to launch and gather the torpedo.
>A single 30+ MCr courrier (given J-6 rating) might be more
>economical, and safer too.

You don\'t need expensive ships.  The cheapest thing is to
just preposition them in a distant orbit (perhaps even out
in the oort cloud) and just send the info on a tight beam.
Even if this wasn\'t true, you don\'t need expensive ships.
Any old interplanetary shuttle will do.  This are a small
fraction of the cost of a J-6 ship.

>Unless a *network* of J-torps is established, there is the problem of
>knowing when to expect a torpedo.  MilSpec Message torpedoes will NOT
>announce their arrival in a system.  They\'ll just wait for an encoded
>radio signal to reach them and use a laser comm to instruct the
>collector
>ship of its position.  Unless there is an established routine, (or
>you have autonomous j-torps, which are not much smaller than
>courriers
>after all), it will be costlier to use a j-torp than a courrier.

You answered your own problem.  The torp just sends the info to
a predetermined point.

> The J-4 torps seem less expensive than XBoat.  However there is
>still
> the problem of autonomy and retrieval.

XBoats have the same problem on a bigger scale.  An Xboat is
more trouble to retrieve than a torpedo.  Why do you think
there there is a class of ships designed just to tend X-boats?

