  {
    'body' => 'Information stored in a warship\'s computer would be valuable intelligence
to an enemy.  This information would include at least the ship\'s log
(which would tell where the ship has been and what it saw there),
communication codes and protocols, and intelligence assessments made by
the ship\'s intelligence officer and by naval intelligence.  This
information could be accessed if the ship is boarded.

For this reason, warship computer security is strict.  Only certain
crew can access certain ship computer functions, and only at certain
times or with higher authorization.  The main security measure would
probably be retinal scanning, because it can be done through a vacc suit
(unlike DNA or fingerprints).  What about electroencephalograph
readings?  Societies making widespread use of psionics might have
computers with psionically activated switches.

Nevertheless, security can be hacked.  (A telekinetic PC once held a dead
crew member up to the retinal scanner and used his telekinesis to move
the corpse\'s eye left, right, up, down, as the computer ordered.)

For this reason, warship computers can be directed to purge their memory.
This purge can take the form of deletion of all information, including
how to run ship systems, or the computer can just delete all files
previously marked.  An analogy with the brain would be removing the whole
thing versus just a lobotomy.  Another purge format would delete ship\'s log
files in reverse chronological order, so that the most sensitive
information -- i.e., the most recent -- would be deleted first.  That
way, if the original owner retook the ship, it wouldn\'t have to rebuild
memory from scratch.

Your comments are welcome.

--Glenn
