    'month' => '02',
    'body' => 'Hi, I\'m back.

David, I\'m glad you found the time to keep the thread going, because
I\'ve still got a bone to pick with you. (Forgive us Tom, but it looks
to me like there are still enough people interested in this argument to
keep it public for a little while longer.)

>From: Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers)

>[OK, this is degenerating to trying to find flaws to pick at jump-torps.
>The problem is that, even if you follow this route, you have a background
>were every possible reason why jump-torps might exist has been used
>to the fullest but every possible use, other than for PC\'s, was dropped
>at the first difficulty without any attempt to overcome them.  While,
>as I say below, I still don\'t think it solves the problems, even if
>it did I find the approach strains the credulity of the background.]

I agree with you that the issue that j-torps raise is one of background
rather than technique. Technical issues have always been trivial to
handle in any science fiction milieu. Retcons are more problematic.

Surely, you and I have the same motivation, the desire to protect the CT
background, while at the same time developing our own campaigns in a
manner consistant with it. And this common motivation underlies the
assumptions we make when faced with "new" situations. Like j-torps.

But I have gotten the impression in some of your past posts that you think
my hokey and arbitrary assumptions are somehow hokier and arbitrarier
than your own hokey and arbitrary assumptions. I just don\'t buy it. Here
are our assumptions, as far as I can see, laid out next to each other.

1)*I* assume that small jump drives are DIFFICULT to build.
2)*You* assume that small jump drives are IMPOSSIBLE to build.

Both of these assumptions do the job of preserving the CT background.
Neither assumption is in any way better thought out, technically
reasonable, or more consistant with background than the other.

True, your assumption has the relative advantage of being easier to
impliment than mine. You need not come up with design rules for these
small, hard-to-build jump-craft.

My assumption has the relative advantage of being fully compatible with
"Leviathan." I can understand that not everybody considers this so
compelling an advantage. That\'s fine.

My assumption has the relative disadvantage of intoducing a danger. The
danger that players might spot and exploit some loophole which I
inadvertantly may have placed in the jump-craft design rules. But since
I\'m not a total idiot, and have thought things through pretty well, this
danger is a small one.

I\'m prepared to discuss the relative merits of our differing assumptions
to some extent. (That is, to the extent that they affect more or less
objective aspects of the game, and not just personal taste.)

But hokiness? Arbitraryness? Incredulaty? Surely my assumption scores no
higher in these catagories than yours does.

-Rob

