    'body' => 'Hello all,

        Okay, I have found an interesting (although somewhat unlikely

 to  please everyone) solution to the J-torp dilemma.

 Let\'s take a bit of a philosophical parenthesis here:

 Observations:
 If we were all unaware of the universe around us, the universe
 might as well not exist.

 There are 3 possibilities here;
 1 - The universe doesn\'t exist
 2 - The universe exists but is not observed
 3 - The universe exists and is observed

 The uncertainty principle states that you cannot observe a
 phenomenon without having an effect on it, however minute.  Now,
 let us assume for a moment that the \'stability\' of the universe
 depends on it being observed (i.e. wether the universe exists from
 one moment to the next depends on if a sentient creature can observe

 the causal characteristics of that universe from one moment to the
 next), because, once again, the universe doesn\'t exist unless
someone
 checks to see if it exists.

 Now how does that apply to Jump Torpedoes?

 Well, the simple (and useful) conclusion we can find is that
 Unmanned jumps are very risky!  Because one can imagine jump space
as
 being a separate universe and since there\'s no sentient creature
 aboard the unmanned vehicle, nobody is going to keep observing the
 pocket universe for its continued existence!  The jump pocket might
 collapse or might not.  The success of the whole jump might simply
 depend on wether someone is expecting mail on this torpedo or not.
It
 might actually get there without anyone thinking about it.

 Therefore networks of Jump torpedoes would be extremely impractical
and
 unlikely to succeed in getting mail through.  Most uses of jump
torps
 would simply end in failure, unless you have, say, people on staff
 who constantly worry about wether the jump torp actually gets there
or
 not.  And that would be unlikely because how can you keep your
thoughts
 on something all day long?  And also, Jump scientists haven\'t really
 figured out this theory. :)

 Anyway... I know it sounds pretty crazy but it\'s not that much more
 far-fetched that Psicoms! :)  It fixes most of the problems - no
 need to artificially make jump-torps drives unreliable or change the
 whole Traveller background.  There might be times when unmanned
 jumps have worked reliably, but this explanation doesn\'t preclude
 them from working fine; it just explains why all the
background-damaging
 applications would NOT work. :)

 What do you sophonts think?  Does jump drive play dice with the
Universe?
 <dons battle dress> :)


--
Pierre-Louis Constantin, ift. a. "He whose name was writ in E-mail."
Independentist: My Canada excludes the federal bureaucracy :)
(: "I hate fanatics with a passion; all extremists should be shot." :)
