    'body' => 'Sat, 10 Feb 1996, Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
>OK, I\'ll grant you that. It\'s about 20-50 times cheaper than using an
>unmanned ship. Still, an unmanned ship could be use if the admiral wanted
>it bad enough. The torp makes that tactic a lot more feasible. But it
>dosen\'t create a new option; just makes it cheaper

[I assume you meant to say "a _manned_ ship could be use if the admiral
wanted to"]
First of all, the loss of human life is more than just cheaper and better.
But even so, anytime you have an advance that eliminates the need for
a harder way of doing the same thing, you can still say that you can
do things the old way "if you really wanted to".  The question is,
why would you want to?  What you are doing is solving a fundamental
dilema in Traveller tatics.

>i was thinking
>of such information as ships in system, which you don\'t need to get that
>close to the planet to see. What kind of info are you thinking about?

That and more.  Just start thinking about all the kind of info a fleet
could use about a system it wants to enter.

>1) The X-boat Network. That uses equipment that we already know is not the
>   most effective available (this by political design). We\'ve been told
>   that it averages 2.4 parsecs per week (which seems awfully slow to me,
>   but that\'s what we\'ve been told.)

No.  The design was j-4.  The equipment used to make a j-4 network _was_
the most effective available.  With torps you can have the same network,
at j-4 for the same reasons the old one was, and save the Imperium big
bucks.

>2) The courier networks like Imperiallines. These use commercial starports
>   for refuelling and thus gets the message through in something less than
>   6 parsecs per week (The starport stops add a day or so per jump, and you
>   can\'t always find a proper starport precisely 6 parsecs away in the
>   direction you want to go. Call it 5 parsecs per week. Such a setup is
>   available at the cost of the couriers themselves. That\'s the one we\'re
>   told the Imperial Bureaucracy use.

Right.  And j-trops make such a network cheaper for a lot less than the
cost of the couriers (plus ships crew).

>3) A courier net with refuelling dumps spotted at 6-parsec intervals. These
>   would be faster than the Imperiallines-type setup since refuelling can
>   be done faster (you cut out the trip from and to the planetary 100-diameter
>   limit) and all the jumps can be J6 . Call it 6 parsecs a week. Such a
>   setup costs the price of the ships plus the cost of setting up the fuel
>   dumps PLUS the cost of _maintaining_ the fuel dumps if they are used
>   regularily. Try working out the logistics of maintaining a fuel dump
>   within jump-1 of a suitable base starport. It\'s not cheap. It gets
>   worse the farther out the dump is from the base. Such a setup is more
>   likely to be emergency use only.

On the other hand a jump-torp makes this feasible.  You don\'t have to
maintain a full base (which, BTW, can simply be in the outer reaches
of a solar system, there is no need to make it so far you need to
jump to get to it) with jump-torps.  Since they are so much cheaper
and don\'t require a crew, you just need to fuel one and leave it sitting
someplace.

>4) The J-torp network. This requires a manned J-6 ship for each node. If
>   fuel dumps are expensive to maintain, just wait till you have to have
>   live crew on station. It would be cheaper than a type 2 courier system,
>   but a lot less flexible. It would be a lot more expensive than a type 3
>   system, especially an \'emergency only\' one, yet such a system is all
>   any of the major players would need to explain the information-lag
>   effects described for the Rebellion.

On the other hand, a jump-torp makes just this kind of network not
only feasible, but within the reach of a large number of the factions
involved (since, with torps, it becomes essentially the same as #3).

>You can send messages one jump by J-torps for the cost of one ship at the
>sending end and a cheap in-system shuttle at the recieving end, but if you
>want to be able to return the messages or relay them, you need another
>ship at the other end.

You just need a in-system shuttle at each end.

>>Secondly (and more importantly), if you want to spread information widely
>>and at the fastest possible speed (like the major factions needed to), you
>>need a network.
>
>Agreed. But a type 2 network of couriers cost less than a J-torp network and
>only looses you a day per jump.

I don\'t see where you get this at all.  The cost of jump-6 ships is
huge.

>The type 2 courier network will replenish their life-support at the same
>starports where they refuel and I naturally assume that the fuel dumps will
>have fuel for the crew as well as the ship.

If you are going to replenish life support you either need to land
at a port or maintain a full fledge base at every system.  In either
case either the cost or time involved was more than you were implying
in the appropriate message.

>Well, that\'s just where you make your mistake. It may be cheaper for
>organisations like the Megacorps and the other Imperium-wide organisations,
>*IF* we assume that they want to cover the whole Imperium.

This is what the factions actually did.

>>would make available more widely.  Not to everone, but to a lot more people
>>than were actually able to have them in the Rebellion sourcebook.
>
>But the cut-rate courier system is available to a lot of outfits who
>apparently didn\'t have it. The Sword Worlds, for example.

You keep assuming the a fleet of jump-6 ships are "cut rate".  Why,
I don\'t know.

>So does the ones I\'m defending. But the energy is created by the ship and
>fed to the torp (since the torp dosen\'t have any fuel),

Actually ,they do have fuel.

>Worse how? Of course jump torpedoes allow you to do some things that you
>can\'t do without them (Otherwise why bother?), but your argument is that
>those capabilities will invalidate some of the Traveller background. Why
>would the fact that one ship can send messages (at 21 MCr a crack) to all
>worlds within 6 parsecs invalidate anything? I don\'t think they would be
>used much at that price.

OK, first of all, you are getting into something I just hate.  A
background that, instead of coming up with reasonable technologies
and having a background that fits, you have background where
one or more technologies "just happen to have" exactly the right
cost and performance so they have exactly the right effect.  It
just gets hard to ignore the fact that your character isn\'t a
realistic person in a realistic setting, but is just a set of
numbers in a contrived game.

Now it seems to me, (and I don\'t have my Traveller stuff handy
so I might be off) that you arbitrarily set the cost of jump-torps
at more than 1/2 the cost of a jump-6 ship.  Why?  you are making
them more expensive than a jump-torp with both a drive and
fuel.  And why even  bother?   Are your PC actually blowing 21 MCr
a crack?

Lastly, it doesn\'t matter what they cost, if the cost of sending
a jump-6 ship is even more.

>That depends on the scale involved. I did have limited ressources. I wanted
>those couriers I bought to be available in a crisis. Until then I thought
>they might as well do something.

So you "just happened to have them".  Then what about situation where
you don\'t?

>A single high-population world could afford more than 100,000 jump-6 couriers
>if they didn\'t spend their naval budget on anything else.

I\'m not sure where

>Certainly someone
>with the ressources of more than one world can afford a few hundred.

Not if you could have a hundred system defense boats that can
turn the tide of a battle.  You are basically making the mistake
of looking at the resources of a large organization and not
appreciating that demands on resources will escalate just as
fast as the resources do.  Look at the US government, AT&T, any
large organization, none of them spend money on the premise that
they have some much it doesn\'t matter.  Because there is always
something else to do with it.  In a realistic setting nobody
have money "to burn."

>Not unless you send them in close to the mainworld. A scout can collect
>all the relevant material just as well from a few hundred thousand kms
>away.

If the scout can detect enemy ships, they can detect him.

>>It was a debatable concatentation.  You were using the rules to address
>>issues that they clearly weren\'t intended to cover and blithly assuming
>>there would be no problems.  It\'s not an unreasonable _possiblity_
>>but it is just that, only a _possibilty_.
>
>OK, so show me the snag.

You don\'t understand.  You are making abitrary assumptions.  Can
they be proven to be false, no (after all, I said they were a
_possibility_).  But you also can\'t show me a single thing
that says it possible for ship to send an object without
a jumpdrive through jumpspace.  In fact, passages on what
happens when a jump field generator fails during a voyage
can be interpreted as saying it\'s impossible.  If you want
reinterpret the rules to say that what you want works, that\'s
fine.  But that doesn\'t mean that you have shown objectively
that it will work.

>But my torps do have a jump drive and they do generate a 100 T jump field.

Then why do you need a ship with a jump drive to send one?

>What do you mean "before"? I\'ve never run a game where that was true, nor
>do I recall any official adventures where that was an issue.

Gee, on every adventure where we have had to go in and collect information,
this has come up everytime we have had gotten and important information
but could still collect more.

>>and to just eliminate it by writing "jump-torp" on a sheet diminishes
>>the game).
>
>Well, that\'s a good reason for you to refrain from using jump torpedoes, but
>I don\'t see that it has anything to do with wether jump torpedoes will
>invalidate the Traveller background or not.

