    'id' => '<v01520d02ad45627218f5@[128.102.186.50]>',
    'ts-index' => '1996-02-12.ac593',
    'topic' => ' Two Arbitrary Assumptions about j-torps',
    'index' => 'ac593',
    'month' => '02',
    'body' => '>But I have gotten the impression in some of your past posts that you think
>my hokey and arbitrary assumptions are somehow hokier and arbitrarier
>than your own hokey and arbitrary assumptions. I just don\'t buy it. Here
>are our assumptions, as far as I can see, laid out next to each other.

Well, I will state that I believe you need to make some assumptions.
But this doesn\'t mean that once you make one assumption, making any
number of assumptions, regardless of what they are, is OK. Clearly
some assumptions are more of a problem than others.
>
>1)      *I* assume that small jump drives are DIFFICULT to build.
>2)      *You* assume that small jump drives are IMPOSSIBLE to build.

Well, in fact, if you look at traveller, even difficult jump-torps
have uses that one would have seen.  As I comment below, you have
the fundamental problem of changing technology after a background
is set.  Except for one slip-up (by someone who didn\'t write
the background), Traveller has been pretty consistent with
nothing below 100 tons.

Also, if you look at fields, critical properties, and economies of
scale, the idea that you need a certain size to be pratical is
consitent with our real life experience.  On the other hand,
you are proposing is a discontinuity in an otherwise steady
change of properties, our experience is that nature doesn\'t
work that way.

Finally, that a technology can\'t be done is less of reach than
to say it has to fit exatly a certain set of parameters.  This
is basically Occam Razor.  It doesn\'t say it can\'t be, it just
says it is unlikely (or, in games terms, implausible).

>Both of these assumptions do the job of preserving the CT background.
>Neither assumption is in any way better thought out, technically
>reasonable, or more consistant with background than the other.

I don\'t agree, but this is the sort of decision each GM needs to make.
However, it also needs to be remembered that, not allowing them
gets you away clean.  If you try and carefully introduce them
so they onely have one desired effect (and I don\'t think this
can be done) you will continually be in danger of an unexpected
consequence (and will either have to live with and inconsistency
or apply another complication to the background).

The fact is that the best time to make technologies available is
before write a background.  To do it afterward is fraught with
dangers.

>True, your assumption has the relative advantage of being easier to
>impliment than mine. You need not come up with design rules for these
>small, hard-to-build jump-craft.

I think easier is an understatement.  I would go with "not fraught
with diffuclties and unforseen dangers"  :-)

