    'index' => 'ac597',
    'month' => '02',
    'body' => 'William F. Hostman writes:
>Rob, your assumption is based upon an idea that makeing it difficult to do
>prevents major impacts upon the published history; such a device, even as
>an emergency lifeboat system, would have had major effects during the 4th
>and fifth frontier wars, as losing sides could send out the message that
>contained their attacker\'s force strengths, location, and such, as well as
>known weaknesses. Such data becomes invaluable, especially if the fleet
>sends 1 per ship to neighboring systems, where they can activate merchant
>shipping and such ( even a few hours warning is a major change), as well as
>step up monitoring for up to a week.

One of the major problems many people have with the Traveller background
(and that unfortunately often included GDW\'s people) is that it\'s difficult
to maintain a sense of proportion. Jump torpedoes would have no such effect
on the 4th and 5th Frontier wars, because your average Traveller task force
is big. I\'ll repeat that. It is big, Big, BIG! A Traveller interstellar
government could afford to build 100 T message torpedoes, if they were
useful, and battleships are big enough to carry them. This would be wasteful,
though, and what they would be more likely to have are scores of couriers.
Just how many is something one can discuss. But if such data really is
invaluable, then a Traveller task force who cannot get jump torpedoes
because they don\'t exist WILL have couriers instead.

So the impact jump torpedoes will have on this aspect of the Traveller
background is that a fleet can use 21 MCr torpedoes instead of 255 MCr
couriers. So if we say that the average task force has 20 couriers, jump
torpedoes will allow the task force to be about a quarter of a light
cruiser stronger. (Less, actually, since jump torpedoes must be regarded
as one-use only in this context, which means a task force would have to
carry more to do the same job. And they can\'t report back, either).

No, the place where jump torpedoes will have an impact is with the mid-
sized outfit. Not the small free trader, because even 6 MCr and 2 T is
an non-trivial part of a free trader\'s budget and cargo capacity, and not
the large outfits, because they can afford couriers and ships whose ship\'s
boats are themselves jump capable, but the subsector corporation and the
small one-planet government (the ones whose population are counted in
millions, not in billions). In short, such outfits as the corporation
in _Leviathan_.

To put tings a little in perspective: A planet of 10,000,000 inhabitants
in a dense area (50% chance of a star system per hex) will on the average
have 3 planets within 1 parsec, 6 more 2 parsecs away, 9 more 3 parsecs
away, 12 more 4 parsecs away, 15 more 5 parsecs away, and 18 more 6 parsecs
away. And it can have one courier for each of those 63 planets for about 3%
of its naval budget. And 63 jump-6 couriers costs less than one _light_
cruiser.


      Hans Rancke
University of Copenhagen
