    'body' => 'Re: Atlas of the Imperium: a collection of offset-square sector maps only.
No world data, XBoat routes, or library data.

Re Couriers vs J-Torps

In every case where couriers would have been sent off, the J-Torp AS
PUBLISHED would have replaced the courier for warning neighboring systems.

As to the "up to a week" of notice, a J-TORP AS PUBLISHED will leave
shortly after the battle has a definite flow (Some would have already been
sent) carrying current projections. This means that the couriers would have
been available to function as skirmish line units (anti-fighter, etc),
rather than being in jump. Also, the invading fleet needs time to refuel
before it can move on. In a war of Attrition (Which imperial warfare seems
to be), all combat effectives, of any size, inflicting any damage at all
have effect.

Also, J-Torps, no matter how expensive, if fitted as lifeboats, would allow
key officers to escape from a losing battle. And there were many such
battles from what I\'ve read. Outnumbered, out gunned, etc, early in the
war. Not a matter of winning, just a matter of making it cost as much as
possible.

In the Solomani rim war, the same is even more true.


-Wil

