    'body' => 'Some Comments on David\'s post:

>Date: Mon, 12 Feb 1996 13:48:11 -0800
>From: Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers)
>
[deletions]
>Also, if you look at fields, critical properties, and economies of
>scale, the idea that you need a certain size to be pratical is
>consitent with our real life experience.  On the other hand,

Economies of scale and technical limitations sometimes have hard and
fast minima. (Nuclear bombs & reactors for instance) But more usually
these minima have to do with cost-benifit economics. Making the device
smaller is hard and expensive. (TV sets, computers, HiFi stereos, etc.)
These constraints won\'t always stop someone with money and a reason to
spend it.

>consitent with our real life experience.  On the other hand,
>you are proposing is a discontinuity in an otherwise steady
>change of properties, our experience is that nature doesn\'t
>work that way.

My discontinuity is no more discontinuous than yours. And you just
mentioned critical properties and economies of scale which show that
nature does indeed sometimes work that way.

-Rob

