    'month' => '02',
    'index' => 'ac623',
    'body' => 'There seem to be some problems with keeping two different, albeit similar,
threads apart, so I\'m splitting this discussion up into two. In this
message I\'m defending the jump torpedo that I claim is possible under the
old rules without violating the 100 T lower limit for jump fields. I\'ve
dubbed it the \'Rancke jump torpedo\' to distinguish it from the \'Leviathan
jump torpedo\'. It consists of a collapsible framework with the jump grid,
jump capacitors similar to the ones put into a jump drive needed to
generate the jump field desired, and a recording unit. To use, the ship
expands the framework, generate a jump solution with it\'s computer,
generate the energy needed in its own jump drive and feed it to the
torpedo capacitors.

David P. Summers writes:
>[I assume you meant to say "a _manned_ ship could be use if the admiral
>wanted to"]

You assume wrong. If sending a jump torpedo to the 100 diameter limit to
collect info and relaying it is a feasible tactic then sending an unmanned
ship to do the same is equally feasible, just more expensive. If the
admiral wants it badly enough he can do it even without j-torps. Thus
J-torps does not _add_ a new option.

>But even so, anytime you have an advance that eliminates the need for
>a harder way of doing the same thing, you can still say that you can
>do things the old way "if you really wanted to".  The question is,
>why would you want to?  What you are doing is solving a fundamental
>dillema in Traveller tactics.

I didn\'t say J-torps wouldn\'t add new options. I said these new options
wouldn\'t make the huge difference you claim. If the knowledge to be derived
from such tactics is big enough to change the result of a lot of battles then
a scoutship  is a cheap price to pay. If a scoutship is too expensive to
loose on such a venture where a torpedo is not, then the benefit to be
derived from the tactic is not enough to invalidate the Traveller background.

>That and more.  Just start thinking about all the kind of info a fleet
>could use about a system it wants to enter.

No, we\'re talking about information available from an exposed position (like
the defenders 100 diameter limit) AND not available from a safer place in the
system. What would that be?

>>1) The X-boat Network. That uses equipment that we already know is not the
>>   most effective available (this by political design). We\'ve been told
>>   that it averages 2.4 parsecs per week (which seems awfully slow to me,
>>   but that\'s what we\'ve been told.)
>
>No. The design was j-4. The equipment used to make a j-4 network _was_ the
>most effective available.  With torps you can have the same network, at j-4
>for the same reasons the old one was, and save the Imperium big bucks.

Was jump 4 the best available when the system was set up? Perhaps it was. I
don\'t have a timeline with me. What I\'m sure of is that the decision not to
upgrade the system was a political one. As for the rest, see my economic
analysis below.

>Right.  And j-torps make such a network cheaper for a lot less than the
>cost of the couriers (plus ships crew).

Not if each node demands a jump-6 ship to maintain.

>You don\'t have to maintain a full base (which, BTW, can simply be in the
>outer reaches of a solar system, there is no need to make it so far you
>need to jump to get to it)

There is every need if you want a covert network. Ships in normal space can
be traced much more easily than ships jumping. But I didn\'t say a full base.
Just a ship.

>>You can send messages one jump by J-torps for the cost of one ship at the
>>sending end and a cheap in-system shuttle at the recieving end, but if you
>>want to be able to return the messages or relay them, you need another
>>ship at the other end.
>
> You just need a in-system shuttle at each end.

Not the Rancke Jump Torpedo (tm).

>If you are going to replenish life support you either need to land
>at a port or maintain a full fledge base at every system.

What in the galaxy for? Leave food and oxygen at the fuel dumps and any ship
can cope. Why would they need to have a full base available? R&R may be good
for morale, but it\'s not essential to survival.

>>Well, that\'s just where you make your mistake. It may be cheaper for
>>organisations like the Megacorps and the other Imperium-wide organisations,
>>*IF* we assume that they want to cover the whole Imperium.
>
>This is what the factions actually did.

I\'d like some quotes about that, actually. It\'s not an unreasonable thing for
them to do, but where does it say that they did?

>>But the cut-rate courier system is available to a lot of outfits who
>>apparently didn\'t have it. The Sword Worlds, for example.
>
>You keep assuming the a fleet of jump-6 ships are "cut rate".  Why,
>I don\'t know.

No, I defined one type of courier "net" as cut-rate: The one where the
owner only want to maintain an "emergency only" courier on Capital. That
would only need a few couriers to maintain (depending on the distance the
message has to travel) yet is enough to explain the movements we are told
about in "Rebellion".

>OK, first of all, you are getting into something I just hate. A background
>that, instead of coming up with reasonable technologies and having a
>background that fits, you have background where one or more technologies
>"just happen to have" exactly the right cost and performance so they have
>exactly the right effect.

Funny, that\'s just the kind of thing I enjoy. Trying to reconcile two
seemingly contradictory facts. In this case some facts of the Traveller
background is defined for us. So is some of the physical laws (ie. game
rules). They seem to contradict each other. Yet we "know" both are true.
How to reconcile them? Obviously by either introducing some new historical
facts or introduce some new physical law that just exactly explains it. In
either case something apparently contradictory is shown to be possible,
which enhances plausibility. Not as much as a having a perfectly meshed
set of rules and a background built from it from the start, but we\'re not
going to have that with Traveller anyway, by virtue of the way the game
evolved.

>Now it seems to me, (and I don\'t have my Traveller stuff handy so I might
>be off) that you arbitrarily set the cost of jump-torps at more than 1/2
>the cost of a jump-6 ship.

Not quite. There\'s a jump-6 courier in _Fighting Ships_ that costs MCr 255.
I won\'t mind betting that I could make a cheaper one, but I like using
canonical background material. So MCr 255 it is. I can\'t calculate the
exact price of a \'Rancke jump torpedo\', because I don\'t know how much you
save by deducting the special fusion reactor part of a jump drive. Thus
I arbitrarily decided that such a torpedo would displace and cost the
same as a jump drive of the equivalent jump number. That\'s not an
unreasonable guesstimate, is it? We can also put it at the price of a full
jump drive PLUS the framework, but that would make it _more_ expensive and
bulky (thus less advantageous).

>Why?  you are making them more expensive than
>a jump-torp with both a drive and fuel.

What\'s the cost of a jump-torp with both drive and fuel? I\'ve skimmed through
_Leviathan_ just now and I couldn\'t find any mention of size, price, or
performance stats for their J-torps.

>And why even  bother?   Are your PC actually blowing 21 MCr a crack?

Not their own money ;) No, I\'m just defending a concept. My players have never
used a RJT. But a jump-2 torpedo would \'only\' cost 9 MCr and is more likely
to be the kind borne by a ship that uses such contraptions. Besides, they
would be marked \'Property of [the company that financed the expedition]\' and
you might get it back for no more than the salvage fee. (10%?)

>So you "just happened to have them".  Then what about situation where
>you don\'t?

But a Traveller fleet will have them. They\'re useful and they don\'t cost much.

>>Certainly someone
>>with the ressources of more than one world can afford a few hundred.
>
>Not if you could have a hundred system defense boats that can turn the tide
>of a battle.

Ah, but that\'s just my point. You CAN\'T have a hundred system defense boats
_that can turn the tide of a battle_. The cost of those couriers are less
than ONE _light_ cruiser. Call it system defense boats equivalent to two
light cruisers if you want to be generous. On the scale Traveller fleets are
usually built that is of absolutely no account.

>In a realistic setting nobody have money "to burn."

True enough. But they\'ll still use a fair amount on intelligence. And a tiny
amount (relatively) is enough to buy the couriers.

>If the scout can detect enemy ships, they can detect him.

Actually, I could give you an argument about that, given the rules about
signature according to size, but there\'s no need. You see, there\'s quite a
difference between the top speed of a ship and the top speed of a photon.
A scout can jump in somewhere hours or days away from the guns of any
defenders and still be able to see what they need and get out again
while the getting is good.

>You don\'t understand.  You are making abitrary assumptions.

I make the assumption that the Traveller rules are consistent. I don\'t think
that\'s so terribly arbitrary (Not borne out by the facts, maybe, but not
arbitrary ;-).

>But you also can\'t show me a single thing that says it possible for ship to
>send an object without a jumpdrive through jumpspace.

Except the _Starship Operator\'s Manual_. A jump drive consist of three things:
A jump grid, capacitors and a special fusion reactor. The fusion reactor burns
the fuel real fast and store it in the capacitors. The capacitors are capable
of holding that energy for a short while before it has to be discharged. When
they discharge the grid forms the jump field. Logically it should make no
difference wether the capacitors was charged by an onboard fusion reactor or
one exterior to the field. Once the energy is in the capacitors, the fusion
reactor\'s part of the job is done.

>In fact, passages on what happens when a jump field generator fails during
>a voyage can be interpreted as saying it\'s impossible.

Let\'s have a quote or two.

>>But my torps do have a jump drive and they do generate a 100 T jump field.
>
>Then why do you need a ship with a jump drive to send one?

Because the energy is generated by the ship (that\'s why you don\'t need fuel
space on the torpedo).

I guess it\'s time for me to put my calculations where my mouth is. Let\'s see
just how a RJT network stacks up against some other types.

Basic assumptions: The cost of maintaining a ship is 10% of its cost yearly
(this is what TCS uses). This includes crew training, salaries, and pensions
as well as servicing, yearly refits, and replacement of worn out equipment.

The cost of a X-boat link is 1 jump tender and 1 X-boat (actually, it\'s
half of two tenders and two ships, since a tender will be part of two links).
It\'s more expensive for an end link (one that is the last link in a chain,
but cheaper for a fork link (one where a tender is part of three links), but
I will postulate that they cancel out.

The cost of a courier link designed to allow one message each way each week
is two courier ships.

The cost of a RJT link is one jump ship and one torpedo.

The cost of a spy network is increased by the need to keep the tender
supplied with fuel from elsewhere.

All costs are in MCr.

X-boat link:Courier-6 link:X-torp link:Spy torp link:

X Boat: 70.652 couriers:J4 torp: 15J6 torp: 21
Tender: 157.2255.55 @J4 ship: 200J6 ship: 255
Supply ship: 50

MCr 22.785/year55.11/year21.5/year32.6/year

Finally, let\'s look at what I call the \'cut-rate\' courier network. That\'s
the one where you only maintain a single courier in readiness at Capital,
with order not to rush home unless something really momentous occur. Say
what someone like the Duchess of Mora might have in order to maintain a
lobbyist at Capital.

Distance from Mora to Capital is (roughly) 145 parsecs. Allowing for
ackward positions of starports suitable for refuelling it might take
29 jumps to get from one to the other. Assume you want the ship to stay
12 weeks and then return. You\'d need 6 couriers to maintain a constant
presence on Capital. That will cost MCr 155.33/year to maintain, which
is affordable considering that Mora\'s naval budget is MCr 3,500,000/year
(after Imperial taxes).

OK. So the X-torp link is MCr 1.285 cheaper than a X-boat link, yet the
Imperium chose to implement a X-boat network. Why? One possibility is
that jump torps was not invented yet when the network was set up. Another
is that the X-boat manufacturers rolled bigger logs than the jump torp
manufacturers. Both are historical explanations that are more than
sufficient. Or possibly there is a hidden cost with the torps. If you
simply assume a 1/36th chance of a malfunction in jump torps you increase
