    'date' => 'Fri, 16 Feb 1996 13:01:03  0500 (EST)',
    'topic' => ' Task system comparison.',
    'index' => 'ac637',
    'month' => '02',
    'body' => 'Hi All.

Wil, I liked your comparison of the task systems (despite the objections
of some who would have this list ethnically cleansed of TNE
comparisons).  I\'ve never liked the high percentages that MT gives for
extreme success and extreme failure.  Here, for your perusal and critique
(and the perusal and critique of others, of course (as if I needed to
ask :-)), is the task system that I use.  It\'s a heavily modified
CT/MT system.

Targets are numbers instead of levels (I\'ve always considered the
distinction to be merely semantic, anyway).

Two dice are rolled with modifiers being [skill] and [ability/3].  I like
ability divided by three because this creates modifiers rangeing from 1
to 5, a very similar scale to skill levels.  Also, I like the way it
divides up the ability levels, giving 6-8 the same "average jo" modifier,
and making an ability of 15 really kick-ass.

Ab.  DM
0-2  +0
3-5  +1
6-8  +2
9-B  +3
C-E  +4
F+   +5


For extreme results I use my patented doubles rule:
If you roll a success, and the roll is doubles, you may try for
extreme success by rolling the task again.  If you succeed on this second
roll (doubles don\'t matter this time), then you have an extreme success.
If you roll a failure, and the roll is doubles, you must try to avoid
extreme failure by rolling the task again. If you fail on this second
roll (doubles again don\'t matter), then it\'s an extreme failure.


The reason I like this is that there is always at least a minute chance of
extreme failure and extreme success, no matter what your target is (not
true of TNE or MT).  Even if you only need a 3+ to succeed, you can still
fail (1/36 chance) and fail extremely (1/36 * 1/36).  If you need a 12+,
you can still succeed (again 1/36), and succeed extremely (1/36 * 1/36).
This allows for exciting events like a David vs. Goliath "lucky shot" even
when one is completely outclassed, or a complete goof-up by the hot-shot
pilot.

I have the probabilities for success/failure and extreme success/extreme
failure for all targets from 2+ to 13+ worked out at home.  I will post
them tonite.  In the meantime...

Comments?  Criticisms?  Ranting Flames?


