    'body' => 'Hi All.  Below are the probabilities of success, failure, extreme success
and extreme failure using the "doubles=extreme result" task system from my
previous post.  I think you\'ll find it interesting.

Major good points of this system:

a) Allows determination of degree of success/failure (extreme vs.
normal) in a consistent way.  This is not true of CT, for example.

b) There\'s always some chance of both extreme success
and extreme failure, no matter what target is (so long as it\'s in the
range of 3+ to 12+, obviously). This is not true of TNE.

c) Chance of extreme failure is minute (but still possible)  when target is
small, large when target is large.

d) Chance of extreme success is minute (but still possible) when target
is large, large when target is small.

e) Chances of extreme results never get too large (as they do in MT).


Here are the probabilities, a table of rounded values (for more
intuitive appraisal) follows:

TargetSuccessFailureExtreme S. Extreme F.

2+ 100.00%  0.00%16.66% 0.00%

3+ 97.22% 2.77%13.50% 0.08%
4+ 91.66% 8.33%12.73% 0.23%
5+ 83.33%16.66% 9.26% 0.92%
6+ 72.22%27.77% 8.02% 1.54%
7+ 58.33%41.66% 4.86% 3.47%
8+ 41.66%58.33% 3.47% 4.86%
9+ 27.77%72.22% 1.54% 8.02%
10+ 16.66%83.33% 0.92% 9.26%
11+  8.33%91.66% 0.23%12.73%
12+  2.77%97.22% 0.08%13.50%

13+  0.00%100.0% 0.00%16.66%



TargetSuccessFailureExtreme S. Extreme F.

2+100=% 0=%15+% 0=%

3+ 95+% 5-%15-% 0+%
4+ 90+%10-%10+% 0+%
5+ 80+%20-%10-% 1-%
6+ 70+%30-%10-% 2-%
7+ 60-%40+% 5-% 3+%
8+ 40+%60-% 3+% 5-%
9+ 30-%70+% 2-%10-%
10+ 20-%80+% 1-%10-%
