>
>Read the Rebellion Source books. The factions with jump-6 couriers got
>info to their people generally through the Imperium, not at a few
> selected locations.

I\'ve read them and I didn\'t find anything to that effect. That\'s why I ask
you to provide some quotes so that I can find them.

>I guess to each their own.  I prefer a background where I\'m not always
>running into things there are clearly there just to make something
>work the way it wouldn\'t have in the first place.  Real things don\'t
>work that way.

But you\'re perfectly ready to impose an arbitrary restriction in the way
jump drives work that makes drop tanks possible but eliminates jump
projectors. Why are your arbitrary restrictions better than my arbitrary
restrictions?

>>Not quite. There\'s a jump-6 courier in _Fighting Ships_ that costs MCr 255.
>>I won\'t mind betting that I could make a cheaper one, but I like using
>>canonical background material. So MCr 255 it is.
>
>You are right, your jump-6 torps are a lot cheaper than a ship.  So that
>leave the point.  They save a lot of money.  That makes a different.

These sweeping statements are pretty useless, not to mention wrong. They
make _a_ difference. I never claimed otherwise. I just claim that they
don\'t necessarily make a lot of difference. If, for example, there is a
small extra chance of the jump torpedo misjumping, then torpedoes are
_not_ cheaper than X-boats.

>As just one, Anyone who needs to send multiple messages back from an
>expedition can now just send one ship rather than having to send muliple
>ships  so that some can be sent back with news.

That\'s SO vague. An expedition from where and to where? Multiple messages
to where? How often does such a situation occur?

>>But a Traveller fleet will have them. They\'re useful and they don\'t cost
>>much.
>
>Again, a fundamental point. Useful technologies (esp. cheap ones) get
>widely used and have big impacts.  That\'s how technology works.  Look
>at history.

Let\'s see. Disposable nappies are useful and they are cheap. They are widely
used, no argument there. But I fail to see the big impact. Could you mention
a few battles that has been won or lost because of disposable nappies?

>So now, instead of having to weight each message to see if it\'s worth
>the loss of a ship you can just pop off anther torp.

1) You don\'t loose the ship, it\'ll be back again in two weeks, and 2) Now you
have to weigh each message to see if it\'s worth the loss of a torp.

Yes, you\'ll be sending more messages with torps than without. It will make
a difference, sure. But what you\'ve failed to demonstrate is why it should
make a BIG difference.

>>I\'m saying that any admiral has to assume (worst case scenario) that he
>>won\'t be able to retrieve any torpedoes he sends off. That\'s why I said
>>that _for this purpose_ one had to assume they were one-shot. The default
>>assumption for manne couriers is that they\'ll propably turn up again.
>
>A default assumption that is questionable.  You are in a middle of a war
>with an enemy that is keen on detroying your ships and you assume that if
>something has happened to the base you are sending a message back to, your
>couriers are going to be safe?

Yep. Unless the courier captain is a hopeless imbecile he won\'t jump in
anywhere near the base.

>And that, if nothing is wrong with the base, they will be unable to retrieve
>the torps?

No, they\'ll propably be able to retrieve them eventually, but in the meantime
the admiral may have jumped somewhere else. I didn\'t say he wouldn\'t get them
back some of the time. I said he couldn\'t assume that when he set out.

>>No, I\'m treating tham as having vast ressources. After all, if that sort of
>>information is so amazingly valuable, then it can hardly be called waste to
>>provide the means to disseminate it. The question then becomes: Can we
>>afford it?
>
>One of the points that people keep missing is that, the inablity to easily
>communicate IS ONE OF THE FUNDAMENTAL UNDERPINNINGS OF THE TRAVELLER
>UNIVERSE (it\'s in caps because I feel like I need to stand on the nearest
>builing and shout it).

No need to shout. I\'m perfectly aware of that. Communication is limited to
the speed of jump, so to speak. Jump torpedoes make no difference there.
They don\'t go any faster than a ship.

>The fact is that no organization has all the comunications it wants. Not even
>the Imperium (this is why it is forced to use a feudal type of goverment
>rather than more direct control).

None of them can send messages faster than 6 parsecs/week, if that\'s what
you mean (With or without jump torpedoes). _That\'s_ why the Imperium is
forced to use a feudal structure.

>By making communications easier you are allow more people to get more info
>(both civilian and military)

Marginally, perhaps, but it won\'t affect the time it take messages to get
between the core to the fringes.

>and going to allow more resources to be freed up for other things.

Yes, but not a significant amount of ressources. Read my analysis.

>>A fleet courier costs MCr 255.55 has a crew of 5 men. The Imperium thinks
>>in terms of fighting ships that cost from 70 times more and has nearly
>>50 times larger crew (and that\'s for a light cruiser;

>Right, and jump torps are even cheaper.  Thus, for each 50-70 messages a
