    'body' => 'as to the recent posting about the differences between the two lists, it
becomes clear from a few of the recent posts as to why the CT/MT list is
XBoat, and TNE is on the Traveller List:

They work totally differently. This causes major differences in many of the
traditional assumptions: In-system travel, combat, strategy, CGen, success
chances for assorted tasks.

Even the flexibility of FF&S causes problems, cannonizing something that
many might have never realized nor cared about: J-Torps.




As for the on-going discussion Re J-Torps:

If you have message drones, then you can have Nuke Drones. So unless they
are much more expensive by weight or displacement than ships, will come to
be the major "Hot War" weapons system. If you can build a Torp, you can
build a bigger one with a 0.5 Gigaton warhead. And still cost less than a
bomb and a 100 ton bomber. It will have to survive getting in system, but
hey, a major fleet could launch wave after wave of them, and if EVEN ONE
gets through, WOW!

A Batron could easily launch a dozen from the big ships, plus more from the
associated "Tag-Alongs". So you\'ld have heavily stealthed, 50-60 MCr torps,
which can EMP quite a bit. Jump them in to a different point than the
fleet, and let the target choose priority.

Also, remember one other limiting factor with fleet units, derived from
cannon: Jump time is not a constant, nor is it stated AFIK to be a fleet
constant. A Fleet jumping with a given vector (say 20 Mm/h aka 20,000 kph,
or roughly 1 g-turn), arrive iover a 48-72 hour time spread (potential)
putting a potentially strong invader at a disad: he may not have time to
regroup. Sure, the fleet can stop and wait for the others, making them
sitting ducks. They can have a scheduled out-sys (or deep in-sys) regroup
point. They can go to target, and by the time they regroup, they will no
longer have surprise.

On average, a given fleet of 24 ships: 4 will arrive on day 6, 16 on day 7,
and 4 more on day 8 post engage.

So armed J-torps will be much like Buzzbombs in WW II. When you encouter
the first, expect more. Terror Weapons. Unpredictable, morale breaking,
devastating occasionally to real targets, and only able to be stopped with
many more than their own numbers due to random time, and exit, points. And
far cheaper than replacing a ship and crew. And by the time you know they
location of the launcher, it can be GONE!

With Ranke torps, they are primarily a deadly diversion. With self-powering
ones, they are a major MENACE to the defender.

And, in both cases, the fleet could launch a set of sensor drones to a
given set of coordinates, jump in a few days later, and get great
intelligence, with no crew risks until the first ships of the group arrive,
and the torps go active.

They do change more than just commo. Intel, warfare, and such would all
have major use for them. Think of softening regina\'s defenses for three
days prior to jump-in with J-Buzz: sure, only a few ships would be lost.
But that\'s three ships lost WITH CREW, plus possibly a strike of a single
torp. (Pardon my ignorance about the total fleet strengths, but I don\'t own
FFW. Anyone selling?) Also, the fact that they would be EMM, tiny targets
(+4 or more Diffmods to hit or detect), possibly with evasions once they
are under fire. And they\'d prolly come in passive, to maximize their
defenses. Sure their expensive, but so is training warship crews.

enough of my ranting.

-Wil

William F. Hostman

