    'body' => '
William F. Hostman writes in digest 538:

   > Also, remember one other limiting factor with fleet units,
   > derived from cannon: Jump time is not a constant, nor is it
   > stated AFIK to be a fleet constant. A Fleet jumping with a given
   > vector (say 20 Mm/h aka 20,000 kph, or roughly 1 g-turn), arrive
   > iover a 48-72 hour time spread (potential) putting a potentially
   > strong invader at a disad: he may not have time to regroup. Sure,
   > the fleet can stop and wait for the others, making them sitting
   > ducks. They can have a scheduled out-sys (or deep in-sys) regroup
   > point. They can go to target, and by the time they regroup, they
   > will no longer have surprise.

I believe that this was canon only in CT; I recall reading an article
by one of the DGP staff (perhaps in the Starship Ops Manual, or in the
Travellers\' Digest) which stated that by increasing the time spent
making the jump calculations, a fleet could reduce the spread of its
ships when they came out of J-space.

This pre-jump coordination between the computers in the fleet
effectively does away with the need to spend several days regrouping
in the target system.

--
