    'subj' => 'Imperial Nobility--a possibility',
    'from' => 'Lance Blyth lrblyth@lamar.ColoState.EDU',
    'body' => 'The idea of an Imperial Nobility has cropped up from time to time.  I
suggest a possibility of how these individuals operate in the Third
Imperium (3I).

Nobles serve the empire.  In return, they get a living off of the excess
production.  There are two types of Imperial Nobility:  Landed (who have
Estate and can pass on the title) and Titular (who have no Estate, but
often a stipend, and cannot pass either on).  Many Landed are also
Titular, a higher title rewarded for service, ie the Baron of Snee (the
Estate), and Count of Eridani (a higher title rewared).  Only the Baron
of Snee can be passed on to whomever the noble wanted to.

Estates.  The Landed nobility possess these.  They have a title of Baron
(most), Viscount (awarded by Sector Duke), Count, or Marquis (awarded by
the Emperor).  Thus a Baron, if she performs an outstanding service for
the empire, may be made a Count and be able to pass that on to her heir.
An Estate is on a decent planet, decent is open to debate.  The noble
draws revenues from the planet, often via the starport.  Nobles are not
supposed to interfer with the local government, just advise on Imperial
matters, but the possibilities for problems exist.  The noble gets a
living, without imperial monies being spent, and the planet gets a
representative at the subsector council.

Ranks.  Rank is important in that the higher the rank, the more revenue
the noble can draw.  It also effects priorities for communication,
appointments, seats in restaurants, etc.  So, nobles want it, and to get
it they have to serve the empire.

Imperial Councils.  This is where nobles serve.  The Subsector Duke (Duke
of his planet) is also the President of the Imperial Council for (fill in
subsector here).  (Sector Dukes are the pres for the Sector council, made
up of the Dukes, or, more likely, their appointees.)  The Council meets
on the capital planet, about 100 days a year.  Here the nobles discuss
and implement Imperial policy.  Nobles from the council are assigned, at
the Dukes leisure, as Subsector Directors for the various Imperial
Ministries, War, Justice, etc.  Needless to say, the professional
bueracracies do the real work--the noble is an appointee.  Important
point--the decisions of the council are decided by vote, one noble, one
vote, thus there is no reason for one noble to hold more than one estate,
though some do.

Noble Families.  First off, these tend to be more like mafia families
than the nice nuclear family.  Each subsector likely has 10-14 Families,
each of 2-6 Landed Nobles and a number of Titular Nobles, plus spouses,
siblings, friends, children, etc.  Families are more factions linked by
some common background, often, but not always, genetics.

The Noble Life.  Basically, a third of the time is on the Estate,
ensuring the money is coming in, if nothing else.  A third will be spent
in council, playing politics, parties, meetings, etc.  The last third
will often be on assignments for the empire, usually in the subsector,
but not always.  In short, being a Landed, or Titled, Noble is a good
life, but it is a continuos round of events.

Thats it for now.  Again, this is a possibility based upon reserach and
reading about historic nobles and aristocracies.  Does this fit into the
CT/MT universe?  Also, sorry this got so long!

Lance

