    'month' => '02',
    'topic' => 'Scale',
    'body' => 'Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers) writes:

>Sat, 17 Feb 1996, Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
>>Not so. If you select
>>a nice quiet spot off the beaten routes, the odds against accidentally being
>>within reach of an enemy are literally astronomical.
>
>You can\'t select a spot if you don\'t know what\'s in the system.
>As to being off the beaten routes.  If you are going to be
>close enough to detect the enemy, you have to be close
>enough to be detected by them.
>
>>Easy. You just select a likely spot somewhere.
>
>
>You can\'t select a spot when you don\'t know where the enemy is
>(which is the problem in the first place).

Excuse me? I pick a *random* point that is 1 AU or more outside the
plane of the ecliptic in the system, and not near the zenith or nadir.
And make it from 1 to 20 AU out from the star. That\'s a volume of over
30,000 cubic AUs. Which means that if there were a spare 30,000 ships
(over and above the ones patrolling *in* the plane of the ecliptic,
which is where the planets are) then the odds are only *even* that
there\'d an enemy ship within an AU of me! That\'s 150 million km.


>>Again you display a complete lack of any grasp of scale.
>
>No, the problem is you apply that scale to only to combat
>and not to detection.  If you are close enough to be
>confident of detecting the enemy, you are close enough
>to be in danger from energy weapons.

Wrong. In the *real world* you can detect ships with *current*
technology at ranges that *far* exceed the ranges of any weapons in
Traveller. A telescope bigger than the Hubble scope, and equipped with
similar instrument can get adequate info. A wide field survey scope can
locate potential targets for the narrow feild scope in a matter of
hours.

Don\'t forget Heplar is going to be visible a *long* ways off. And *any*
ship much past the equivalent of Venus orbit will be *considerably*
brighter in the IR than any natural body.

Even if you accept "jump flash" as canon, then somebody *still* has to
get within attack range in time to attack. The spy ship has lots of
time to leave.

If I was doing this, I\'d send a half dozen or so ships, widely spaced.
That way you can compare the images from the wide field cameras and get
accurate positions for *everything* that\'s on the plates. Add in the
detailed info from the narrow view scope, and whatever info the ELINT
folks (radio monitoring and the like) can get, and you\'ll have *lots*
of info on the system.

Sure, stuff can still hide. But you\'ll have a pretty good idea of where
things are.

Also, never underestimate the possibility of impersonating a merchant
who didn\'t realize he was jumping into an area that was being contested
(or who hoped to get in, sell something "vital" and get out before the
fighting starts). You can get a lot of intel that way. Whether from
real merchants or ones who secretly report to you.

It\'s basicly not worth the trouble to make heroic efforts to stop spy
ships. You keep an eye out for chances to nail one without going too
far out of your way, and meanwhile try to disguise what you can (not as
much as many would like) and otherwise keep in mind that the enemy will
your moves within a week.

Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
