    'month' => '02',
    'index' => 'ac683',
    'body' => 'Hi Charles,

Regarding your question on neutrino background: No neutrino
background has ever been observed, but that may have more to do with our
inefficiency at detecting these things than with astrophysical reality.
Almost all neutrinos we\'ve seen to date have come from 1) Fission
reactors, 2) Particle accellerators, and 3) The sun.

I\'m not aware of any other large neutrino sources in the
universe, but that doesn\'t mean much. Very little is known about these
particles.

Re: Your High Guard quote. Everything you said is true. The
issue of clobbering worlds with high velocity ships has been discussed
to death earlier on this mailing list. (On two seperate occasions, many
years apart ---- are we ready for another one?)

There are some considerations that may make this tactic more difficult
than it might seem at first. How difficult, you may ask? Ah, that is the
controversial question. I have my own opinions, of course, but I
hesitate to state them, lest I incite a third war on this yet unresolved
topic. 8^)

-Rob (the jump torp guy) Flammang
