    'date' => 'Fri, 23 Feb 1996 10:13:33 GMT',
    'body' => 'In answer to Charles

The Black Globes descriptions suffer from retcons following further
thought.  Initially, someone thought "it doesn\'t emit anything, you
can\'t see it".  Then someone pointed out that it would appear on a
black patch on the sky, so you could detect a black globed ship as it
occults the stars, etc. behind it.  This applies to neutrino and
electromagnetic radiation.  Thus, it should be possible to spot a BG
cloaked ship, but probably more difficult (trying to see a small,
uniform black patch versus trying to see a luminous, varying, ship) -
think how much easier it is to see the sun than the asteroids (not a
good analogy).  I think there must be some sort of background neutrino
flux - I suppose all stars and galaxies must produce some, but then it
wouldn\'t be much different from electromagnetic radiation sources.

Another point that really isn\'t considered is a BG reaction to
gravity.  Somewhere I remember reading "...black globes cut across
all field lines...", which would presumably include gravity.  This
means that not only are BGs undetectable using densitometers, they are
also unaffected by gravity.  However, I\'m fairly sure that there are
references to BG cloaked fleets using gravity-assisted trajectories to
reach there targets (Knightfall?).  Certainly, if such a fleet wanted
to go into orbit, or at least have more than a passing encounter with
a target world, they would have to drop the BG.  Perhaps all this
suggests another consequence of the early descriptions of BGs which
wasn\'t thought of.  I think if a BG cloaked ship shot through a system
without being effected by the system\'s gravity, it would absorb a lot
of energy from the gravity field - result: big bang, or drop the BG.
In my game, I\'ll rule that BGs don\'t block gravity (when one comes
into my campaign), so they can be detected by densitometers - which
are relatively ineffective sensors in my game.  I\'ve just realised
that this means graitic drives will work through BGs - not thrusters,
though.  Perhaps I\'ll think some more about this!

