  {
    'body' => 'Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers) writes:

>Wed, 21 Feb 96,  shadow@ (Leonard Erickson)
>[Regarding jumping into a "safe" spot.]
>>Excuse me? I pick a *random* point that is 1 AU or more outside the
>>plane of the ecliptic in the system, and not near the zenith or nadir.
>>And make it from 1 to 20 AU out from the star. That\'s a volume of over
>>30,000 cubic AUs.
>
>A volume filled with locations that are all so far outside of your
>sensor range as to be useless for scouting out a system.

Out of the ranges given in the books for *active* sensors. Not out of
real world active and passive sensor ranges. Note that for example, it
is possible for *amateur* radio operators to not only bounce signals
off the moon, but to do so well enough to use it for communications!

With larger gear (well within the size a medium sized ship could carry)
it is possible to *image* Venus! Believe me, detecting a 100 ton or
better ship at interplanetary ranges *is* possible via radar if you
don\'t have an atmosphere in the way.

And passive sensors have ranges just as good. Radio transmissions, IR
signature, both light reflected off the hull, and light emitted by
rockets are all detectable at interplanetary ranges with gear a ship
can carry.

>>Wrong. In the *real world* you can detect ships with *current*
>>technology at ranges that *far* exceed the ranges of any weapons in
>>Traveller. A telescope bigger than the Hubble scope, and equipped with
>>similar instrument can get adequate info. A wide field survey scope can
>>locate potential targets for the narrow feild scope in a matter of
>>hours.
>
>OK, first of all, you _aren\'t_ going to detect ships at the range
>you describe with the Hubble telescope.

Depends on what you are detecting. The IR signature of a manned ship
*will* be detectable at several AU or else the crew will be dead.
Detecting a 300K object against the 3K background is *easy*. And if the
ship has any kind of powerplant or equipment running, it *must* have
some way of dumping the waste heat. Either you use evaporative cooling,
which leaves you in a pinch when you run out of fluid to evaporate (and
which makes you stick out like a neon sign, as you\'ll look like a baby
comet) or you must use *radiative* cooling. That requires radiator
surfaces that are *much* hotter, and thus stick out even more on an IR
scan.

>Furthermore, you are
>assuming great advances in sensor technology without similar
>advances in concealment.

Nope, I\'m not assuming *any* advances in sensor technologies. Just that
you have clear space to use them in and cheap transport to carry them
in.

While the Palomar scope isn\'t suited for mounting in a "scout" vessel,
something along the lines of the Multiple Mirror Telescope *is*.
(half a dozen 1 meter mirrors, computer synchronized). Get that outside
the atmosphere, and float it on a tether, to isolate it from vibrations
on the ship, and you\'ll be able to *image* ships.

Making several hundred meter "inflatable" dishs for radio/radar
observation is easy. And those will give you quite a bit of detection
without using them actively. They, unlike the optical scope, are cheap
enough to discard rather than recover.

As for advances in concealment, you are up against the hard limits set
by physics. Especially with regards to IR.

First, lets look at passive radio/radar. You can maintain
communications silence. But that gets impractical for any ships
manuevering near each other. And please note that radio transmissions
from handheld units like walkie-talkies and cell phones are *known* to
be capable of being picked up by current surveilance satellites.
Without an ionosphere in the way, and without much in the way of nearby
radio noise, ship-borne sensors will be better. And if you use radar
for navigational purposes, that\'s detectable at interplanetary
distances.

Active radar is definitely capable of detecting ships at a mere 20 AU.
And given that it takes several hours for the signals to make the round
trip, it might even be worth doing, even tough it screams "here I am"
to the whole system. After all, the odds of another ship being within
12 hours of you are damn slim, and if they *are*, you\'ll likely know
about it.

Radar "stealth" has definite limits. There are only *three* principles
used:

1. reflect the beam off in another direction.
2. absorb the beam
3. Be transparent to the beam.

#3 is *not* available to a ship in Traveller. If nothing else, the
fusion plant can\'t be transparent to radar!

#2 requires either a black globe, or knowing in advance what
frequencies you want to absorb (it\'s done with quarter wave coatings).

#1 is the main method used on the stealth fighter and bomber. Thus the
use of *flat* suraces, and the angling of them. The problem is, this
requires that you know what direction the radar is looking at you from.

They stick out like a sore thumb if the radar is *below* them, and
show up fairly well from more or less overhead. Y\'see, the flat surface
relects the beam off at an angle. Unless it\'s coming pretty much dead
on to the surface. So you have to avoid "concave" areas, and you want
to try not to have too *large* an area facing any given direction. You
don\'t want to have too *many* areas though, as the smaller areas will
act like a larger *curved* area, especially if longer wavelength radars
are used. So you can minimize radar return from the front. And even reduce it
from the sides. But you can\'t *eliminate* it.

Now, lets consider visible light. Sure, you can paint the ship black.
But the best black coating known only absorb about 90% of the light.
Nature manages to get that up to 99% (or so) on carbonaceus chondritic
bodies, and with soot. But let\'s ignore that.

So you have a 100% absorbtive coating. Great. That means that at 1 AU
from a G-type star you are absorbing *kilowatts* of light on every
square meter of the starward side of the ship. That becomes *heat*.
Which you have to get rid of somehow. That\'s why the Shuttle is painted
*white*, to reduce the load on the cooling systems. In case you didn\'t
know, once in orbit they open the cargo bay because the *entire* inner
surface of the doors is covered with heat radiators!

Now we get to IR. The outside temperature of the ship *must* be the
same as the inside temperature. If it isn\'t, then you are doing
something to "pump" the heat out of the hull and into something else.
Problem is, the higher the temperature difference, the harder it is to
increase it. And the pumping process generates heat also. So, you can\'t
just pump it into some sort of internal heat sink except for short
periods. You can dump it into a liquid and then allow some of the
liquid to evaporate into space. That will cool you, but the increased
gas density near you *will* make you more noticeable. Or you can pump
it into a "radiator" to radiate excess heat into space. That will
*really* make you stand out!

IR is the main problem. In IR your ship is going to be *much* brighter
than any natural object unless you are in *close* to the star, and have
the systems shut down so they don\'t generate excess heat. And then, you
are going to fry the crew....

So, a ship is any "bright" IR signal or any "normal" IR signal that is
moving "too fast" (which you *will* be doing unless you want to take
*years* to get around).

You can reduce your radar signature, but again, if you give the return
of a small rock, but are moving with a speed or orbit that says "ship",
you are still "busted".

>But this is all beside the point
>because Traveller detection ranges are given and they
>are in only the light-second range (at least in the
>original books).

And they are patently *wrong*. It\'s one thing for the rules to say that
it\'s possible to do things we don\'t think are possible (like go FTL).
It\'s quite another case when they say it\'s *impossible* to do things we
*know* are possible.

Detection good enough for a *target lock* or with "normal" sensors I
can buy. But not with the sort of stuff you stick into a vessel
intended to scout a system.

Figure it out. If we can image a planet at multiple parsecs, we can
image a ship at a few AU.

>>Even if you accept "jump flash" as canon, then somebody *still* has to
>>get within attack range in time to attack. The spy ship has lots of
>>time to leave.
>
>Only if they detect the other ship.  There first clue to it\'s
>existance my be the attack on their ship.

Maybe. But it\'s pretty darned unlikely. In fact, that\'s one of the
arguments for going ahead and using radar. That way you *know* you are
going to see anybody coming. To get surprised then, they\'d have to be
within laser range when you started up the radar.

>>Also, never underestimate the possibility of impersonating a merchant
>>who didn\'t realize he was jumping into an area that was being contested
>>(or who hoped to get in, sell something "vital" and get out before the
>>fighting starts).
>
>This is not a new tatic.  It\'s been used before in the "real world"
>and it has the same risks that other approaches do (standard NATO
>policy was to sink all those Russian "trawlers" if war broke
>out and the russians detain, and sometimes even shoot down,
>civilian aircraft in the wrong place).  The chances
>of being disabled and captured or the enemy deciding that it\'s
>just a ploy and blowing you away (esp. if you are making a habit
>of this sort of thing, which you will be if this is your major
>approach to intellegence gathering).

On the other hand, even the Russians let ships from other countries
into their ports.

For what it is worth, there\'s even a fair chance that a single ship
jumping in, not making any threatening moves and then jumping out will
be "left alone" much of the time. Consider that while the Germans and
Japanese did shoot at the planes sent in to check the weather over
tasrget areas, they didn\'t waste a lot of shells on them and almost
*never* sent up fighters. It wasn\'t worth the effort. It made more
sense to save fuel and ammunition to use against attacks.

I used to know a guy who\'d been navigator on a B-29 and his plane had
been making weather flights over Japan at the end of the war. One
interesting item is that it was pretty much a "milk run". Until August
6th, 1945. After that they got everthing but the kitchen sink thrown at
them.

So unless a single ship is a serious danger, I don\'t think it\'s going
to be in much danger. While I don\'t agree with you that it can\'t detect
much unless its on top of things, I do concede that it can\'t find
everything. And that being closer is better. But given that it\'ll be
at least a week before the enemy can use the info the ship gathers, I
rather expect that it\'ll get some lasers and masers aimed at it to try
to "blind" it (which *is* semi effective at long ranges) and maybe even
have some missiles or the like fired at it if it\'s close enough. But
nobody is going to really expect it to be hurt unless it gets unlucky.

