    'index' => 'ac708',
    'body' => 'Derek Wildstar <wildstar@qrc.com> wrote:

>answer sessions.  As a rough, ballpark estimate the velocity difference
>between two nearby star systems should be somewhere above 10 km/sec and
>below 100 km/sec for nearby destinations, and increasing as the size of the
>jump increases. (are there any astronomers out there who can give me
>better figures?).

Sounds reasonable from what I know.  (Amateur astronomer, only!)

Near the Sun, the "local standard of rest", or average orbital speed of
all stars around the Galaxy, is 200 km/s.  The Sun is moving somewhat
faster than average -- 20 km/s toward Lambda Herculis; this breaks down
roughly into 14 km/s to spinward, 10 km/s to coreward, and 7 km/s to
galactic north ("upward").  (_Guide to the Galaxy_, Henbest & Couper.)

Mean orbital speed of the Earth is 29.8 km/s, but this can either add or
subtract from the vector depending on the time of year, and relative
angle of the world orbits to each other.  Likewise, the departure world
will have a vector that will affect the calculation as well.

This shouldn\'t be a problem even for limited-fuel starships from TNE.
Acceleration at one gee for one hour achieves a velocity of just over
35 km/s from a standing start.  That\'s two G-turns, in TNE.

