-> Charles was wondering about neutrino backgrounds.

There is a 2.1 K cosmological background in neutrinos (the neutrino
version of the cosmic microwave background). It is hopeless to try to
detect it now, but since these 57th century guys have neutrino
detectors so good to see the shape of an object from neutrino scattering
they must be able to detect the cosmological background.
Of course the cosmological background is superimposed to the stellar
sources, supernovae etc that were already mentioned.

One thing I am missing is why should one want to find black globes
using the neutrino background rather than the visible background.

-> David believes HST cannot detect starships.

oh my, better not tell NASA about this... I believe it all depends on
your assumptions about emissivity. I have done a little excercise
using the wfpc2 simulator.
Suppose you know approximately where to look (ie you had a successful
scan). Consider a 500 MW starship with 99 per cent
efficiency. The one per cent lost to heat is radiated away with heat
exchangers operating at 1500 Kelvin (on the Starship\'s operator
manual it is stated that thruster plates are optically bright when
operating, so my heat exchanger could just be the thruster). About
one per cent of the flux would be emitted in the waveband of the broad
WFPC2 visible filter ie 50 KW. At one astronomical unit this is
about 5E-19 W/m^2. With one hour exposure with WFPC2 and the visible
filter one can see with a reasonable signal to noise sources down
to 4E-19 W/m^2. Therefore this 500 MW starship would be visible only
down to 1 AU.
Of course under the same assumptions a 5,000,000 MW battleship
could be detected at 100 AU.

With the Advanced Camera supposed to fly in 1999 the sensitivity
will increase by a factor 4. In addition improvements in Near IR
detectors should allow one to operate at more convenient wavelengths
for the detection of thermal emission.

Summarizing I believe that a very extensive masking will be necessary
to hide a battleship to this pinpoint kind of detection. Simply cooling
down the exhaust would not be enough. NICMOS flying in 1997 can observe
down to 2.3 microns and will be probably able to detect cooler emissions.
The best option (apart from a black globe) is to increase the efficiency
even further. An efficiency 1 starship emitting only black body
radiation at say 300 K would be very hard to detect.

To find something not knowing the approximate direction is another business.
The field of view of all the instruments I have mentioned are ludicrously
small compared to the full sky. For some applications one does not need
the full sky, though. For instance we could build now a battery of HSTs
dedicated full time to monitor solar system planets. Any Vilani
dreadnought approching one of the planets would immediately be detected.

Without any preferential direction one faces the big factor 10^-9 which
is roughly the ratio of the WFPC2 field of view over the whole sky.
Obviously one would have to design a special purpose instrument on
a special purpose telescope. With a 4000*4000 pixels 0.25 arcsec in size
one could cover 2 *10^-6 of the sky with a single shot. Increasing too
much the pixel size would not help you since the objects you are looking
for are fainter than many stars. One would end up having something in
every single pixel. Summarizing I believe that either a real world scan
would take days or a scan would be much less sensitive than a pinpoint.

Needless to say, TNE starships without thrusters would be detected MUCH
more easily.

                Cheers,
                     Massimo
