26/2-1996 William F. Hostman wrote:

>Could someone please send me a rule reference (full citation) for the =
rules
>that allow fleets to jump together and not face individual time rolls? =
I
>have looked through HG, MT, BL, TNE, and SSOM, and cannot find such a =
rule.

Excerpt from the MegaTraveller Journal #1, Q&A, p. 24:

"When a group of starships know they have to arrive in unison, they =
elect to spend significantly more time at the start computing and =
sharing jump vector computations. This leads to a much more accureta =
jump exit at the other end, with the error dropping significantly.
  The formula in the _Starship Operator\'s Manual_ for normal jumpspace =
exit is:

  124 hrs + (2D x 6 hrs)
  yielding a result of 136 - 196 hours
    (that is, 5.7 to 8.2 days)

  If double the jump preparation time is spent with all the affected =
ships in computer link via tight beam communication, use the following =
formula instead:

  167 hours + (2D x 0.1 hr)
  yielding a result of 167.2 - 168.2 hours.

  Most ships now arrive within _minutes_ of each other, with the worst =
spread being up to 60 minutes apart (and this only happens in about 1 =
out of 20 jumps): Considering the vast distances found in a star system, =
starships arriving minutes apart would not spoil a surprise arrival."

Due to the limitations of email, I have replaced italics with an =
underscore ("_").

Hope this is what you were looking for.

Mark Seemann
mark@dk-online.dk
