    'ts-index' => '1996-02-26.ac728',
    'body' => 'Sun, 25 Feb 1996, Massimo Stiavelli <mstiavel@stsci.edu>
>-> David believes HST cannot detect starships.

>oh my, better not tell NASA about this... I believe it all depends on
>your assumptions about emissivity.

Those assumptions are the key problem.  See below.

>I have done a little excercise
>using the wfpc2 simulator.
>Suppose you know approximately where to look (ie you had a successful
>scan). Consider a 500 MW starship with 99 per cent
>efficiency. The one per cent lost to heat is radiated away with heat
>exchangers operating at 1500 Kelvin (on the Starship\'s operator
>manual it is stated that thruster plates are optically bright when
>operating, so my heat exchanger could just be the thruster). About
>one per cent of the flux would be emitted in the waveband of the broad
>WFPC2 visible filter ie 50 KW. At one astronomical unit this is
>about 5E-19 W/m^2. With one hour exposure with WFPC2 and the visible
>filter one can see with a reasonable signal to noise sources down
>to 4E-19 W/m^2. Therefore this 500 MW starship would be visible only
>down to 1 AU.

First of all, and most imporantly, my point is that the kind of ships
we make now are not detectable by the HST.  If you want to talk about
how Traveller ships put out more energy, you also have to talk about
what measures technology allows that ship to use to make itself
harder to detect.

However, even if we ignore the above, you aren\'t correct.  (These
are mostly points I covered in my earlier message.)
-First you really have no basis for heat exchangers operating at 1500 K.
You can control the temp of heat exchangers by design.
-Your assumption that even 1% of the energy is in the visible is based
entirely on the 1500K figure.
-You also assume that the energy is radiated in all directions.  Even a
simple measure of putting heat exchangers in back of the ship would prevent
detection from the HST.
-You numbers also assume to a ship with the powerplant operating at full,
if it is sitting still waiting for a ship to come by (like a scout ship)
then the real number will be a fraction of the number you mention.
-Additionally, unless you already know where the ship is, the odds that you
will have the telescope fixed on the ship for an hour are miniscule.

>Summarizing I believe that a very extensive masking will be necessary
>to hide a battleship to this pinpoint kind of detection.

But the point is that Traveller ships have extensive masking.  You
can\'t detect current ships at 1 AU with the HST.  You can\'t detect
Traveller ships.  Maybe you could detect a Traveller ship with
all concealment technology removed and additionally forcing it
to use 1500K cooling and forcing it to distribute that cooling
isotropically, but that is a rather pointless exercise.

>Simply cooling
>down the exhaust would not be enough. NICMOS flying in 1997 can observe
>down to 2.3 microns and will be probably able to detect cooler emissions.

Aside from the fact the cooling is only one aspect to not being able
to detect the ships, and that the original message refered to visible
telescopes, the fact remains that this is only an assumption not
backed up with any figures.

>To find something not knowing the approximate direction is another business.
>The field of view of all the instruments I have mentioned are ludicrously
>small compared to the full sky. For some applications one does not need
>the full sky, though. For instance we could build now a battery of HSTs
>dedicated full time to monitor solar system planets.

With hour exposures, you are still going to have to fix the telescope on
the ship.


