16/2 1996 Harley Grantham wrote:

>A change of subject from the ever popular J-torps. :)

Ever popular... Hmm... At least one member of this list has been tired =
of that particular debate almost from it\'s outset. This is a welcome new =
topic!

>I have been giving some thought to what cities and other structures =
would look
>like in the Traveller Universe.  How would some of the high tech =
buildings=20
>look once contragravity became available, and then common.  How would =
the=20
>Zhodani architecture differ from the Imperial? =20
>
>I really don\'t like the way much of this has been portrayed in =
Traveller,
>although some of the Megatraveller supplements have some interesting =
struc-
>tures on their covers.  The Imperial palace is a massive floating =
sphere.
>Dull. Dull, Dull, Dull!   I would think once technology can free =
architects
>from the laws of physics, they would let there imaginations soar, not =
revert
>to simple shapes that are easy for non-artists to draw.  (Which seems =
to have
>been a major factor in Traveller descriptions.)

Well, the period in which the Imperial Palace was build was maybe a =
\'functionalist\' or \'geometric\' one. Think of some of the arcitecture of =
the twenties (Bauhaus but especially Funkis) or the sixties-seventies. =
The arcitecture of these decades was much more simple than technology =
allowed at the time. Design is as much linked to current estaethics as =
it is to technology. This is not disagreeing with Harley, only trying to =
find a reasonable explanation why the Imperial Palace looks like it =
does.

>The space docks in Star Trek films and on Babylon 5 are much more =
interesting
>than the boring sphere described in one of the DGP magazines, (I think =
it
>was the MT Journal).  And the floating city in Empire Strikes Back was
>the sort of thing I would expect on some of the more exotic atmosphere =
worlds.

The sphere I think Harley is thinking about is Limii Orbital in the =
Theton system. It was published in "the Flaming Eye", and I think it =
makes perfect sense as a Vilani structure. Dull, maybe, but very Vilani. =
And this brings us back to the Imperial Palace. It was build by =
Arbellatra (Imperial Encyclopedia, p. 10) who heralded an all time high =
for Solomani political influence in Core (Solomani & Aslan, p. 24). So =
why was the Palace build in an architectural style which seems more =
Vilani than anything else? The most reasonable explanation I can think =
of is that the Palace was build to appeace Vilani high nobles, still =
powerful although their influence was declining at that time. Any better =
explanations?

Vilani architecture is described in "Vilani & Vargr" as being mostly =
dull, with an eye more to functionality than appearance. I guess that =
Bespin from "the Empire strikes back" is more like a Solomani design. In =
my Traveller universe there\'s room for both, depending much on the mood =
I\'m in when I play.

>So the bottom line is I cannot turn to the tradtional Traveller sources =
and
>expect to find anything interesting.  I think this is a major deficency =
with
>Traveller, as this is the sort of thing that can really add color to a =
game.
>My single biggest problem with Traveller has been the lack of =
descriptions=20
>for alien worlds that give a feel for that alieness. =20
>
>So does anyone have any references, suggestions, wild ideas?

Well, I certainly agree on some of the above mentioned points are =
problems. How does alien design differ from Imperial design, especially =
since one must assume that all races go through different estaethic =
phases which are not necessarily very similar to each other? I think =
this is a difficult question, but then again, trying to imagine _aliens_ =
is a difficult task at best.

Vilani design/architecture is maybe the easiest to describe. It is very =
functional and often ugly. Different periods are more mirrored in choice =
of materials and color than form. Of course, tech level determines a =
lot, too, as the Vilani would tend to utilize the most cost-effective =
methods of construction and use of available space.

On the other hand, _good_ Vilani design, when found, will tend to have =
very simple lines, somewhat like Arne Jacobsen or Philippe Starck.

The Solomani will, of course take a more individual approach towards =
form. Official (read: Party) building would probably tend to be rather =
monumental and monolithic. Individual investors would prefer a wide =
range of different styles, from very conservative buildings, to =
buildings that look more like a work of art than a building. With grav =
technology, one could imagine almost anything. With grav plates, the =
floors don\'t even have to be down! I think some structures would be =
absolutely crazy. Most would probably be rather ordinary looking, =
though, as architects will have to be paid just like everyone else, and =
most investors will tend towards a certain degree of conservatism.

Great Solomani architecture will tend to be highly decorated, intricate =
and voloptuous   to enable the great architects to promote themselves.

I guess that Imperial architecture is a blend of the two.

Vargr design is, as with everything Vargr, a planless blend of =
everything. I think a typical type A Vargr starport will have started =
out as a little installation. As traffic increased, more structures were =
added to the first one, with little thought to if styles clashed or not. =
This will have happened over and over again, till you get something like =
\'the Navel\' from the french science fiction graphic novel/comics series =
"Valerian" (highly recommended as inspiration for sf architecture).

For Aslan architecture I think that one can find much inspiration with =
the spanish architect Gaudi.

The rest of the major races I\'ve haven\'t thought so much about.

Mark Seemann
