  {
    'topic' => 'Human Minor Races',
    'index' => 'ac757',
    'month' => '03',
    'body' => 'Traveller chronology is a bit odd.  The Ancients took humans off Earth
around 300,000 BCE.  That means that they did not collect a bunch of
modern humans, instead, they got a whole lot of Homo Erectus specimens.

For here were born the 40+ human minor races, as well as the Solomani,
the Vilani, and the Zhodani.  Given that Homo Erectus was pretty
different from modern humans, and we are talking about 300 K years of
evolution on an alien planet, I think that most human minor races will be
a good bit more divergent than the ones described so far.

It would be easy to avoid the whole problem and change the date from
300,000 years ago to 60,000 years ago. By this time, humans looked a whole
lot more human.  However, I see the possibilities presented by this data
as really interesting.  I tend to assume that the Vilani and other
"normal" human varieties are only part of a wide spectrum ranging from
folks who look just like Solomani to quite divergent types.  I would
assume that the Darrians are a rather moderate example of how divergent the
various varieties can get.  The most extreme types would undoubtably be
wholly different species.  Of course, in addition to this are the
varieties who the Ancients genetically modified.  All bets are off with
them.

While 300,000 years is not enough time for prehensile tails, IR vision, or
similar oddities to evolve, I can see an amazing variety of differences
between the various types of Humaniti found within the Imperium.  Fur,
short muzzles, minor aquatic adaptations, all seem quite possible.  I\'ve
occasionally borrowed some of the less unlikely hominds from Ringworld in
some of my games.

So, has anyone else thought about this, or come up with any interesting
varieties of humans?

I think human minor races present a great opportunity for role-playing,
since they are an opportunity to play someone who is human, but quite
different.  This is easier (for many people) than trying to play a truly
believable alien being.


-John jsnead@netcom.com

(Who would much rather ask odd Traveller questions than write the Nephilim
book I\'ve contracted for (Sigh))
