    'id' => '<Pine.A32.3.91.960310225256.15336A-100000@astro.sns.it>',
    'date' => 'Sun, 10 Mar 1996 23:20:52 +0100 (NFT)',
    'ts-index' => '1996-03-10.ac759',
    'topic' => 'CT, MT, and TNE (longish)',
    'index' => 'ac759',
    'month' => '03',
    'body' => 'I\'d like to share some thoughts on the expected Traveller developments.
First of all I\'d like to clarify that I simply hate TNE. I hate it because
of the background and also for what is represents. I remember reading on
the old TML about the efforts that the contributors to the list made
to avoid the introduction of the Virus. At the time GDW guys were in more
or less regular contact with the list. It is remarkable how arrogant their
attitude was. The background was killing new customers and the new customers
wanted not a grandious empire but a post-holocaust scenario. It was even said
that the market would have demonstrated who was right. Well, it has.
They obviously did not conquer the market while managing to loose a
fraction of the old customers (me included).

Let\'s face it, the crowds of kids will never (again) be captured by
Traveller. The collectible cards will not help. That idea has already been
exploited by many, and, as far as I know, nobody repeated the success of
Magic The Gathering (TM). The original CT was introduced few years after the
first landing on the moon. I remember the emotional impact of that landing.
Everybody was interested in space. Now some have a  moderate interest in
space. My feeling is that a new issue of TRaveller should target these
few, a fraction of whom, however, are probably already players. It is not
by alienating the old players that this new initiative will produce money.

What is my recipe? first concentrate on ideas. no set of rules will make
everybody happy (not to mention ADD, I recently gave a look to the
2nd edition rulebooks [I am not a regular player..], it is incredible how
crappy, dispersed, difficult to use they are, still how many ADD players
are there?). Once the ideas are there one can take care of the details,
e.g. rich lists of equipment, good design rules, possibly a task system,
scenarios and worlds pregenerated with some detail, etc.
As a referee I find it difficult to move away from the year 1000 timeline,
but as a player I would love to play in any period as long as the show
works and it is a far future science fiction game and not a survivors
new barbarians game.

Finally my personal feeling is that one should not get too worried about
the physics of jump drives , thruster plates etc. Of course they are
unphysical. Of course if misused they could create enormous inconsistencies,
but who cares? The game is refereed for a reason. Thruster plates,
antigravity etc add a lot to the game, I would not like to play without them.

                          Cheers,
                          Massimo

