>around 300,000 BCE.  That means that they did not collect a bunch of
>modern humans, instead, they got a whole lot of Homo Erectus specimens.
>
>For here were born the 40+ human minor races, as well as the Solomani,
>the Vilani, and the Zhodani.  Given that Homo Erectus was pretty
>different from modern humans, and we are talking about 300 K years of
>evolution on an alien planet, I think that most human minor races will be
>a good bit more divergent than the ones described so far.

By 300,000 years ago Homo sapiens were the predominant hominid species on
earth. Homo erectus is not known in Africa this late, and was even no longer
present in the Far East after 250,000 ya.

However, these are not known as *archaic* Homo sapiens for nothing...Homo
sapiens is composed of a variety of subspecies which include Cro Magnon man,
Heidleberg man, and the Neanderthals, so there is still room for plenty of
morphological variation (although these weren\'t around until long after
300,000 ya). If an ancient poped down to Eartyh then, his/her/it\'s sample of
humans would nearly all be \'primitive\' H. spaiens.

The differences between these archaic forms and modern man are primarily in
the cranium, and include lower, longer braincases, reduced cranial capacity
(not by much though - Neanderthals actually had *larger* braincases) and
facial prognathism (their noses stick out).

Sorry to be anal, this is not a flame. It\'s just that enough people get on
their high horse regarding physics on this group that I thought I\'d do the
same with biology :-)

Jules

