    'index' => 'ac763',
    'body' => 'Hi there

I think there are other sources for architecture in the Imperium than
the Imperial Palace.  How about: Moot Spire, or the acrcology-type
city in Imperial Encyclopedia or Referee\'s Companion (gravitic
structures there), or the grav cities of Vincennes (one of the MTJs)?
As for aliens, there are the floating gardens on Kusyu (Aslan &
Solomani), the great monolithic starscrapers of Vland (Vilani &
Vargr), the subterrainean Vargr city on some world in Gvurrdon (Alien
Realms.  Don\'t forget, just because you can think of things to do,
doesn\'t mean the architects of the day can.  I\'m sure there are things
we can do with modern technology that haven\'t been done.  Also, most
architects, in common with all other professions, are mostly
work-a-day types who simply do what they are payed to do, and take
inspiratoin from the fore most architects of the day; as architecture
is as much a matter of taste as what is possible, then technology
doesn\'t necessarily result in exciting buildings.  Yes, the Imperial
Palace is dull, but then maybe the Imperium needed dull after the
Civil War!  Perhaps Arbellatra didn\'t want to appear to be
aggrabdising herself.  Just because she was a successful Admiral and
Empress doesn\'t mean she had any taste.  Perhaps an impression of raw
power was intended.  Face it, dull architecture is more realistic than
exciting architecture!  However, I\'d say that you can find interesting
illustrations in the Traveller books (some above), although there are
also some terrible illustrations.

>The sphere I think Harley is thinking about is Limii Orbital in the =
>Theton system. It was published in "the Flaming Eye", and I think it =

There was also the Gateway Station in MTJ#4, but that was built around
a hollowed out asteroid, which are typically a roughly (dull) sphere.

>I had a race of humans that their homeworld was a very high G
>planet. (3G) These people rarely were over 4\' 6" but were *wide*. I
>don\'t remember the science fiction novel I got that idea from

Were these books E. E. Doc Smith\'s D\'Alembert series, eg. Clockwork
Traitor, where the empire had a group of intelligence operatives which
had a famous interstellar circus for a cover.  The people who ran this
circus were from such a world.

