    'from' => 'Robert Flammang FLAMMANG@vms.cis.pitt.ed',
    'body' => 'John Snead wrote about aging the other day:

<Date: Sat, 9 Mar 1996 13:36:05 -0800 (PST)
<From: "John R. Snead" <jsnead@netcom.com>

<Is anyone else bother by the fact that all the wonders of Imperial
<medicine have absolutely no effect on aging unless the character is
<taking anagathics.  W/o anagathics characters raised in TL 1 and TL 15
<environments have no differences in aging.

I guess I\'ve never really been bothered by Traveller\'s aging rules.
Here\'s why:

I\'m no expert on aging, but it seems to me that all of our medical
technology hasn\'t affected human aging much, if at all. Our increased
AVERAGE lifespan is admittedly much longer, but this isn\'t due to our aging
more slowly. Rather, it\'s due to the fact that we are so much less
likely to die of disease or trauma than our ancestors.

In other words, we\'re more likely to grow old now than in the bad old
days, but we don\'t BECOME old any later. Even thousands of years ago, a
man who died of "old age" died at seventy or eighty. Such men were rarer
then than now, of course. But that\'s because only about half of the
population ever had a chance to get old.

Someone told me once that our extended average lifespan this century was
attributible almost entirely to early detection of cancer and to the
invention of refrigeration (which eliminated most cases of food
poisoning.) This sounds a little too trite and tidy to be entirely true,
but it\'s sentiment jibes well with my observation that modern medicine
protects us more from dying young than from growing old.

So it seems to me that, barring some new medical breakthrough like
anagathics, the steady march of medical TL\'s will help Trav characters
more on their survival rolls than on their aging rolls.

Well, now you have my Cr 0.02 worth. 8^)

-Rob

PS, nice post about the observation tasks by the way. It\'s a much needed
addition to Traveller.

