    'from' => 'Phillip McGregor aspqrz@sydney.DIALix.oz',
    'body' => '> You are forgetting one factor.  In either Solomani & Aslan or Vilani &
> Vargr it was mentioned that the Vilani lacked resistance to many Terran
> diseases.  It sounded like the whole smallpox & the New World problem all
> over again.

Well, yes, this has been *alleged* over and over ... as the so-called "Plague
of Duskir" (which, despite searching through a friends copy of the Vilani
sourcebook, is *not* mentioned there as some have previously suggested ... does
it really exist in some reliable "canon" publication or is it simply a furphy?)
.. the problem that has to be faced is, that the Plague of Duskir (assuming
that it existed at all ... and I have suggested already that it is of dubious
veracity for good scientific and medical reasons) occurs *after* the final
defeat of the Vilani *not* before.

In any case, this still doesn\'t explain how the Terran Federation was then
KO\'ed by its own colonies. Consider this, the latest figures (in teh Sydney
Morning Herald today) are that the previous max figure of 13 billion projected
for the earth\'s population is likely now to only be 11 billion, as the rate
of increase has decreased. Now, given the continuing enhancement of female
equality, and this is supported by all CTrav, MTrav and TNE material, it seems
most unlikely that in 300 years that a vast colonial population could have been
built up ... and it seems even more unlikely that it would be place where all
the high tech industry would be in any case. So how did the colonials manage
it?

My solution in both cases -- the history that we have been told of by the
Imperium is an organised lie for their own political reasons. We know that
the Imperium has a long track record of organising this sort of "big lie", so
why not, if it suited their purposes. You may well not agree with my
explanation as to *why* they have manipulated the truth -- or exactly what
it is they are hiding ... but an *excellent* case for their being *something*
that they are hiding exists. Just consider this, there are evidently documents
in the British Public Records Office dating back to the middle ages that are
*still* classified as "Top Secret" ... what can their be that they could
possibly want to hide from back then? (I can think of a few things!) So, surely
the Imperium may have some skeletons that they would prefer no-one uncovered?!

> Sure, the Vilani could come up with cures or immunizations, but If your
> troops and industrial planets are sick *now* having a cure in a year
> doesn\'t help if the Terrans invade next month.

Yes, except there had been ongoing contact for most of the 300 years of the
Interstellar wars, and any disease ... no-one yet having presented credible
"canon" evidence that the Plague of Duskir was anything other than the usual
sort oif thing that accompanies societal collapse in the chaotic aftermath
of a lost war ... the Terrans had is well and truly likely to have run its
course on the Vilani *long* before the end.

Then, consider this. What did the other planets (outside of Vland) *eat*? We
are told that the plants and animals of Vland were largely inedible to the
Vilani ... surely the chances of any planet having *any* food that is edible
by humans or human descended/related lifeforms is so close to nil as to be
pointless considering?! Sure, there are two solutions to this --

1) The Panspermia Premise -- That is, that life was spread throughout the
Galaxy from a single source by comets (or whatever) and so all life on all
planets are related. This means that the story the Vilani put around about
Vland must be distorted ... or that Vland must have been a unique case.

2) There are what, someone recently mentioned 28 IIRC, a *lot* of minor and
major human races in the vicinity of the Imperium ... what do *they* eat?
There is no indication that the Zhodani, Vargr, Julians, Darrians, or any
of the other human races have any food problems on *their* planets. Moreover,
it is made quite plain in a variety of sources that most animals that can be
encountered are *edible*. Assuming that they are, then it seems to me that
there is a very high chance (approaching 100%) that each such planet will have
at least one ... and probably several (tens, hundreds?) diseases that will find
human beings quite palatable. So the Vilani *must* have had considerable
experience with disease prior to contact with the Terrans. Ergo, it seems
more and more *certain* that Vilani apologists for the Ziru Sirka are lying
through their teeth for their own socio-political ends!

(Well, that\'s one line ... and it makes more sense and is based on more logic
and better evidence that yours, so *I* think, FWIW)

> I would say that disease was likely a major factor in the Terran victory.

I would say that you still haven\'t explained the population disparity, and *I*
have offered an alternative -- and more believable -- explanation for the so-
called disease theory.

