    'ts-index' => '1996-03-18.ac792',
    'body' => '     Counterpoint to Philip McGregor problem with population for Terran
     Federation:

     My primary focus is your idea about the women having careers and its
     effect on the Terran Population 300 years from now.  I think that you
     are focusing only on the major industrialized nations in this
     analysis.  The women\'s movement here in the states and England began
     in the relational feminist way, with women realizing and promoting the
     fact that although they were equal to men in basic human rights, they
     also carried the ability to reproduce, which made them different.  It
     later evolved into Independent Feminism, which said that women should
     see themselves as equals and not be concerned about their reproductive
     capabilities when relating to men.  This is what we experience today
     in the US...the reality is that relational feminists are still the
     majority by a huge margin.  Yes, population growth has slowed in the
     US, but that is not only a factor of feminism but also of the aging
     boomer population which no longer can have children (at least for the
     most part).

     You must remember that in the women of continental Europe have also
     undergone a feminist revolution and seem very content with a
     relational feminist idea.  In many third world and developing
     countries, even many Asian countries (whose population makes up over
     50% of that on Earth), women haven\'t had ANY revolution yet.  In the
     Moslem nations, its not religiously correct for the female to have a
     career or even SPEAK!  Many Asian cultures have an extremely
     \'subservient female\' mindset and with all of the openness of the world
     economies in the last 50 years and exposure to the American movement,
     this hasn\'t changed their culture (or that of Korea or China) by any
     measurable means.

     Let\'s not turn this into a discussion on feminism, but my point is
     that I think you\'re thinking in an America-centric fashion when you
     say that the women of the world have careers now, so our population
     growth will slow down in the future.

     Steven

