> Actually, full body cloning is a TL 9 procedure, and by TL 10 growth
> quickening allows the clones to be grown a 10x speed.  Creating a 20 year
> old clone would only take 2 years.  Cloning only a single arm or eye is
> substantially more difficult than cloning a fully body.  Take a look at
> the Traveller\'s Digest 12-14 for more info.

Well, this *directly* contradicts MTrav Referees Companion, pages #28 and #32.
I would take formally GDW published material as being canon over DGP publsihed
stuff as a matter of course *when there is such a direct contradiction*. There
seems to be no justification for taking what basically was dumped by GDW as
canon. If GDW didn\'t publish it, they probably didn\'t fully (if at all) approve
of it.

Phil McGregor


> > > You are forgetting one factor.  In either Solomani & Aslan or Vilani &
> > > Vargr it was mentioned that the Vilani lacked resistance to many Terran
> > > diseases.  It sounded like the whole smallpox & the New World problem all
> > > over again.
>
>   Actually, it\'s in Rats & Cats, p. 22.
>
>   In Rats & Cats, the plague is described as happening during the mass
> migration of the Solomani that occured after the defeat of the Vilani.
> The article on disease in one of the later copies of MegaTraveller Digest
> (unfortunatly I don\'t have access to my copies at the moment) implies that
> the plague played a role in the war.

Aha! Confirmation at last! The Plague of Duskir is *NOT* GDW canon - it\'s in
one of the later DGP Digests! If we are going to treat the "sparklers" with
contempt, I guess the fact that Rats and Cats and the Plague *both* are DGP
products from *late* in their existence, just before GDW dumped them (or
whatever actually happened), *and* that they go against -- *directly* against
in the case of the relevant technology -- accepted GDW material, then both must
be regarded with a *great* deal of suspicion, and probably discarded as
*non-canon*!

OK! When the Milieu Book of Trav4 comes out on the Interstellar war period,
*and* supports Duskir/Rats and Cats (*IF* it does provide such support -- and
*IF* it explains how the Terrans had TL13/18 tech at Tech 12 and earlier!),
*then* I\'ll go for your arguments! In the meantime, nope. Ref\'s Companion
contradicts it, and I\'ll take Ref\'s companion over later DGP stuff any time!

>   The standard explanation for Terran victory, taken from the
> MegaTraveller Encyclopedia entry "Nth Interstellar War" (p. 33), is that
> the initial wars between the Solomani and the Vilani were fought on the
> Vilani side with only the resources of the local Imperial Governor (this
> is a direct steal from the GDW boardgame Imperium), allowing the
> Solomani to win against limited opposition.  By the time the central
> government had noticed what was going on and dispatched major fleet
> units (after the Terran victory in the 8th Interstellar War), the Terrans
> had invented J-3 (which the Vilani did not have) and generally kicked
> Imperial behind.

Yes, I\'ve read the Imperial Encyclopaedia and have Imperium as well. To which I
say, "so what"? The question here is, how big could the Terran Federation *be*
at the time of first contact, and then during the wars? My position is that
there is a *major* discrepancy here. And so what if the local Vilani Governor
had limited resources ... if he had a umpteen times larger population and
inudustrial base than the Terrans then he had a major advantage. In any case,
even the introduction of Jump3 ships would not have been enough in and of
itself *unless* the Terrans had a force that was already close to parity with
the Vilani (and the Vilani were using the whole of the Imperium\'s forces by
this time). How did they do it with less people?

My suggestion -- for a given TL, Terran *Industry* was *vastly* more efficient
and productive than Vilani *industry*. This meant that the Terrans could have
many more ships and much larger armies than the Vilani for the same population.
This seems to be one of the few (I\'d say *only* -- but it\'s my pet idea, so I\'m
biased!) explanations that make any sense, or so I think, FWIW.

>   Note that developments on Terra are limited by the lack of avalible
> land and economic opportunity.  When Europeans came to the Americas,
> these transplanted populations experienced huge growth rates, much higher
> than were seen in the Europeans left at home.  There is no reason to
> assume that Terrans encountering the opportunities of interstellar
> colonies would not respond with more children to fill them up.  This does
> not imply a different role for women - Rats & Cats p. 20 shows that these
> birth were largely through "artificial wombs", freeing women to be as
> equal as they liked.

But Rats and Cats is suspect at best, as it directly contradicts MTrav Referees
Companion. So the women would *still* have had small families. Even if R&C was
true ... who in the hell is going to look after all those kids? Memory Dupes
(even at a crude level) are stated as being a TL/16 technology (from MTrav
Referees Companion again).

>   Actually, we\'ve hashed this out before, so I won\'t go into this
> arguement again, but I am still unconvinced that one needs anything other
> than the canon explanations for Vilani defeat (internal decadence, Terran
> use of J-3 drive, Vargr invasions, internal rebellion) - taken together
> they do very nicely.

But, as I\'ve now been able to point out, the *DGP* explanation is *EXTREMELY*
suspect as to whether it can or should be regarded as "canon"!

>   On the other hand, your theories do make for a nice X-Files kind of
> deep background, with opportunities for adventure.  Not my idea of
> Traveller, but then, each to his or her own.

Yep, what can I say, I *really* like the X-Files ... so goofily believable, and
so *american*.

>   The answer to where these food sources came from is very simple - the
> Ancients put them there, just as they put all those major and minor human
> races there.  If I were them, I\'d have made sure I didn\'t take any
> diseases along to infect my human breeding stock.

Sure, but one species\' disease is anothers benign bacteria. Also, allow for
thousands of years of development in isolation. Diseases do mutate into
harmlessness over a period of time ... and, therefore, we can assume that
previously harmless bacteria do the opposite. The disease doesn\'t even have to
be fatal to trigger Vilani medical science - a nice debilitating long term
disease, or one that weakens permanently but doesn\'t necessarily kill, or one
that simply takes a *long* time to kill ... think Influenza, Polio, Syphilis
style nasties. If they were reasonably infectious, then it seems that the
Vilani are *going* to have to deal with medical science at a sophisticated
level *regardless* of the evolution of life on Vland ... unless they forgo an
interstellar empire and *remain* on Vland. They can\'t simply quarantine every
system that has such a disease ... they have to try to find *some* sort of
cure.

>   Nobody said that the Terrans didn\'t get diseases from the Vilani (the
> Native peoples of the Americas passed syphylis on to Europeans, after
> all), just that Terrans had lots more diseases to give, and had better
> medicine to cope with Vilani imports.

Doubtful. The Vilani had a much larger empire ... ergo, a *much* larger pool of
diseases for which the Terrans would have just as much resistance as the Vilani
would for Terran diseases.

>   The "population disparity" is easily accounted for by the "artificial
> wombs" described in Rats & Cats that are described as creating a new
> fully functioning colony world in twenty years.  This is indirectly
> supported by the rules of the boardgame Imperium, where an undisturbed
> Terran outpost on a habitable world takes only ten years of peace (or
> something like that; don\'t have the rules here) to turn into a colony
> with two-thirds the industrial capacity of Terra itself.  Sorry, but
> there is no population disparity - the Terrans can have as many people as
> you like.

Sorry again, the tech required for Rats & Cats just wasn\'t available at the
time of the Interstellar wars. It contradicts Referees Companion, and this,
being a GDW pub, should be regarded as definitive compared to a dubious late
DGP publication.

> > Yep, but is cloning available prior to TL/12? Actuall7y, according to the MT
> > Referees Companion, you can\'t even clone *body parts* until TL/13! Genetic
> > Engineering is not available until TL/14 ... and I guess that full cloning
> > isn\'t available until TL17-18, as "Partial Memory Transfer (Dupe)" isn\'t
> > available until TL18, and this sort of implies full cloning.
>
>   The Solomani didn\'t use cloning, they used "Artificial Wombs," which
> implies that they just extracted a whole bunch of eggs from doner women
> (we can do this now - in fact we do), added sperm, and then put them in
> the oven to bake.  You could increase yield even further by encouraging
> the development of identical twins or even greater multiples.  Aside from
> the artificial womb thing, this is all contemporary tech.  By getting
> arround the physical limit of human wombs, you can use all of a woman\'s
> eggs (hundreds, I think - maybe more) and have population growth rates
> that are just absurd - the only limit is how many of these artificial
> wombs you can build.

OK. You have artificial wombs. So what? How does it solve the problem? Sure,
you get a *lot* more babies ... but you\'re begging the question of *who looks
after them*? Memory Dupe technology is TL/16+ so *someone* has to ... for at
least five or six years, and that\'s not allowing for education and the like.
Who feeds those who look after them? Who provides all these nonproductive
mouths with food, clothing, shelter, consumer goods? Sure, "real" people are
*an* answer -- but a *realistic* one? No way! How many people are going to
lower their living standards so drastically as this would seem to require just
to win a war ... wars may not be fought to increase ones living standards, but
I reckon a damn good case for them being fought to *defend* ones living
standards could be made.

Either you have to assume that terran *industrial* production tech was vastly
more efficient than that of the vilani ... my preferred solution, in which case
there probably isn\'t any need for the R&C "solution", dubious as it is ... or,
well, how else do you explain it? Short answer? you can\'t!

> > The problem stands.
>
>   I don\'t think so.

The problem *still* stands, though may perhaps be on a slightly different
emphasis.

>   Very true.  Note also that there are subgroups even within American and
> European societies who have large families - Mormons, Catholics, etc.

Yes, and note that they are having no effect! They may be slowing the rate of
slowing of population increase. Also note that, AFAIR, *Italy* - *the* catholic
country - has a declining level of population, even though the use of the Pill
and of Condoms is evidently not terribly popular there. So, so what?

>   I\'d just add that artificial womb technology would allow women to have
> children without the career interference we see in contemporary society.
> Moreover, government policies that favored more children, esp.
> arrangements for collective child care, would also increase birth rates
> if needed.  Families currently limit the number of children due to
> calculations about the amount of resources they can devote to each and
> their chances for success - and expanding colonial society provides more
> opportunity and would change the calculus parents make.

But you then run into the problem that raising children takes time. Or, at
least, assuming that you have (or wish to have) children *you* would want to
spend some time with them? The more children you have, the more the woman is
going to be tied down (or, let\'s not be sexist, the *man* just as likely)
caring for them even if she doesn\'t have to carry them to term ... babies take
a lot of looking after! So *this* interferes with her career *far* more than
the actual 9 months of pregnancy ... and how much of this will they be prepared
to put up with? I would suggest that the likely average family size is going to
be around 2-3, and this is below replacement rate for a stable high level of
population. And your claim that a colonial society would allow for more
resources per child makes no sense on the above basis.

>   Sorry for such a long post - it\'s just that this topic is a nice break
> from the recent hardware wars and flames about the death of TNE and stuff.

Don\'t be sorry, it\'s good to see the different ideas! I think the intellectual
exercise of the argument is more fun than the topic itself, in general!

Phil McGregor

