> >that it existed at all ... and I have suggested already that it is of dubious
> >veracity for good scientific and medical reasons) occurs *after* the final
> >defeat of the Vilani *not* before.
>
>     The plague of Duskir is mentioned in "Solomani and Aslan" in the
> chapter labelled "History of the Solomani Peoples." It occured AFTER the
> Rule of Man (ie, 2nd Imperium) was established; it was one of the
> contributions to its downfall.

What page? I had a *close* look at a friends copy of the above, in fact, we
*both* pored over it for an hour or so, and we couldn\'t find any mention of
it. Doesn\'t mean it isn\'t there ... it may well have been a forest for the
trees effort! However, it also may have been a one line mention - or, as a
number of other people have been now claiming, it was in some of the late
DGP Digests or Adventures such as Rats & Cats which I have strong reason to
doubt about their canonicity (?!).

> The population of the US is several times the population of the UK, its
> parent nation. This pop was achieved in under 300 years. The population
> of the earth doubled in the last 40 years. The rate of growth is slower
> now for many reasons, several of which you point out, but it need not
> stay slow. Even assuming the continued enhancement of the equality of
> women, it is still likely that women will want to have children (and men
> will too.) Maybe even alot of children, if the economy encourages it.

OK, so the population of the colonies in 300 years will be 250,000,000 - I can
live with that sort of estimate!

> >My solution in both cases -- the history that we have been told of by the
> >Imperium is an organised lie for their own political reasons. We know that
>
> This is certainly a good explanation, but I think others are possible
> too.

Sure! Undoubtedly! But you have to be careful that they don\'t have worse holes
in them than the one I\'ve picked up on ... and all the ones to date certainly
seem to! The beauty (or flaw, take your pick) of a "mother of all conspiracy
theories" is that by its very nature it can pick on flaws in *your* arguments
and ignore flaws in its own!

>     ----    ----    ----    ----    ----    ----
>
> The real mystery to me is how did they conquer the Vilani? Two
> possibilities present themselves:
>
>     1) The Vilani Population was unusually low. But why? I don\'t
> find the plague argument very convincing either.

And the Plague seems certainly to have dubious status as far as being "canon"

>     2) Many of the Vilani almost wanted to be conquered. The TC
> government just looked that much better to the Vilani "voters" who were
> fighting in the trenches.

This is perhaps a good theory. Still, such "defeatism" would have had to have
developed over a long period of time. I doubt that the Terrans could have
beaten the Vilani at all for any extended period if the severe problems with
population differences exist, as it seems they must.

> Of course, this begs the question, did they really beat the Vilani?

If they didn\'t, then who did? (Aha! I sense an even bigger conspiracy theory
coming on! Maybe the Vilani fooled those unsophisticated Terrans into merely
*thinking* they\'d won, and then set about absorbing them into their culture
without them realising it? How devious!)

