> 1) An artificial womb is simpler than cloning, TL 10-11 seems quite
> reasonable

Well, perhaps. However, note my practical objections to the idea of Tuber
colonies presented in answer to other posts ... obviously another of those
completely (not!) thought through DGP ideas.

> 2) From The Traveller\'s Digest # 12 page 37 (hardly a dying gasp product).
> " Crude full-body cloning of lower life-forms first occurs at tech level
> 8. The ability to reliably create higher life forms (such as humans)
> doesn\'t occur until TL 10.  The donors cell is placed in an artificial
> womb -and the clone grows at the same rate as any normal offspring.  At
> the end of the normal gestation period the clone is removed from the womb.
> The result: a normal, healthy newborn baby, but with one parent...

This is *directly* contradicted by MTrav Referee\'s Compendium. It states that
Partial Cloning (Body Parts) is unavailable until TL/13. I take official GDW
products as taking precedence over any non-GDW product.

> Using growth quickening techniques (also a typical tech level 10
> development) an "adult" full-body clone (roughly equivalent to 20 years of
> age) can be grown in an artificial womb in about 2 years...

Yes, unfortunately, you end up with a 20 year old *body* with the mind of a
newborn ... or, perhaps, depending on how the forced growth is done, two year
old. And, as far as I am aware, this is *not* contradicted by DGP, according
to the Referee\'s Companion, TL/16 (pg. 32) Successful brain transplants become
possible. Memory transfer is developed, although it is not yet reliable." In
other words, the clone cannot be provided with a "personality", or "memories"
or "skills" or "knowledge" until TL/16 *at the earliest*. Now. As you may or
may not know, the human brain had definite developmental stages that it goes
through as it ages (I did this as part of my teaching credentials 20 years ago,
so I may be a bit rusty on the details) ... and some of these, such as the
development of speech (or alternatives thereto, such as signing for the deaf)
takes place very early on in the piece and *cannot* be "jumped" ... if you
don\'t gain language skills by the time that particular part of the brain has
been developed *you never do*! (Think of the French boy found to have been
raised by wolves, and more recent cases of child abuse resulting in complete
isolation from human society for a couple of cases in the US ... none of the
children ever learned to do more than speak a couple of disjointed words. And
the wolf boy evidently never even progressed that far) Sorry. Even if we take
the dubiously "canon" material of DGP as opposed to "official" GDW
publications, then it falls flat on its face as far as this area goes anyway.
Even if the forced growth is combined with some sort of socialisation as it
proceeds, then you have a 20 year old body with a 2 year old mind and
personality ... and who in the hell takes care of it 24 hours a day, educates
it etc. Sorry, it becomes impractical to the point of ridiculousness.

> It is important to not that such a clone, although possessing an adult
> body, will have the mind of a newborn baby, since it has had no exposure
> to the outside."

Which makes the processes of Tuber colonies wuite impractical. Ask anyone who
has to deal with adult morons and cretins (in the technical definition) ...
I have worked (and still do) with people who work with such people on a part
time basis, and, believe me, from what they tell me, only a true saint would
have the patience, and a muscular wrestler (well, almost!) the brawn, to deal
with them when they get stroppy. You are expecting us to believe that you can
create a viable society using such techniques ... sorry, not believable.

> If by clone you mean physical and mental duplicate of a person, no, that\'s
> TL 17 or 18.  If you simply mean artificially grown physical duplicate, TL
> 10 does it.

So says DGP. GDW says different. I believe that GDW "official" products are
generally accepted as overruling DGP products as far as "canonicity" goes.

> Remember, basic cloning produces a fertilize egg which will naturally grow
> into a human (or other) infant.  Learning to modify this cell so that it
> instead only produces and arm or an eye is rather more complicated.  Today
> we can clone lower animals, and we have no idea how to clone only and eye.

GDW still says TL/13. DGP doesn\'t count.

> Any further questions?

Yep, explain exactly who works in the factories, on the farms, in the offices
etc. if everyone has a 20 year old (at least one) with a 2 year old brain and
personality to look after it. Sorry, I can\'t see any society doing this
voluntarily, not even to win an interstellar war. And you can\'t force them
to do it, not unless you commit huge resources to, so to speak, "watch the
watchers". In other words, it\'s totally impractical (even leaving out the fact
that it seems to be anti-canon).

> Date: Wed, 20 Mar 1996 12:53:05 -0800
