What Robots? According to Book #8: Robots, it is only at TL/12 that the first
self-mobile computer brain with developed manipulative appendages (i.e. a
robot) finally becomes an economic and commercial reality. AI software can be
developed, but cost and size are limiting factors ... remember Aybee (?) from
the DGP Digests? He was, what, TL/16? And *he* was not AI in any real sense -
and this was made plain on a considerable number of occasions ... like every
issue! So, at TL/12-13 there *are* no Robots. Sorry to puncture your balloon!

Also, note that it is plainly stated that Memory transfer is not available
until TL/16 ... subliminal teaching is a crock that doesn\'t work here and now
and is not mentioned anywhere in Traveller ... certainly not in any of the
"official" GDW publications.

>   By the way, Rats & Cats provides some support for this position:
> "GenAssist first sought to genetically alter Terran and alien lifeforms
> so that food supply was not a problem."  p. 20.

Unfortunately this means, technically speaking, that they are unlikely to be of
the same species any more ... they will be Homo Sapiens *XXX* (name of specific
planet) rather than Homo Sapiens Sapiens (i.e. *us*) ... and it is likely that
they will be as capable of interbreeding as Horses and Donkeys, or Lions and
Tigers ... all they wil produce (if they\'re lucky) are *mules*. I do not see
that a society that eventually develops the Solomani Party on one side and the
Society for the Soveriegnty of Man over Machine (and then classes cyborgs as
machines) on the other could spawn such a movement ... we\'re talking Nazi level
nasties here, kiddo!

>   In Rats & Cats this is cited as a major reason behind the swift Terran
