    'body' => 'Why is life as we know it based on left-handed proteins and right-handed
sugars?

Until recently I assumed it was a 50:50 chance sort of thing, but new
research is providing some evidence that it may not be. As it turns out,
left and right handed molecules are *not* exactly equal in energy; a
left-handed protein made of protons, neutrons and electrons is the mirror
image of a right-handed protein made of positrons, anti-neutrons and
anti-protons i.e. an antimatter right-handed protein. The energy
differences are small but calculable, if one is fond of quantum
electrodynamics. (I\'m not, before anyone asks.)

What\'s interesting is that there\'s some evidence that these tiny energy
differences are somehow "cumulative" -- that all things being equal, you
will get noticeably more of a given handedness of a molecule over time
e.g. left-handed proteins will proliferate. It\'s analagous to the way
that evolution is often thought to work: tiny advantage per generation,
over successive generations, leads to a population which is predominantly
"advantaged". [I don\'t know if it\'s thought to work *exactly* that way,
or just in a similar way.] If this is true, then you\'d have left-handed
primordial soup, as it were, from which left-handed life would evolve.
Evidence for this includes a preponderance of one handedness of quartz
over another ( + optical rotation more common than -, or maybe vice versa)
in some deposits.

As you can see, I\'m not 100% up on the theory, but it seems there\'s a
basis for assuming life will almost all be the right way round,
chemically speaking. Thus, you don\'t *need* panspermia as a hypothesis
for this to be true (although you might want panspermia to be correct
anyway).

The woman doing the research is Dr. Alexandra MacDermott, here in
Cambridge, which is how I know about it.


Nick

