> designed to imitate humans, sure, these things couldn\'t do that, they
> could change diapers and (maybe) teach children spelling. Also, by TL 12
> low autonomous robots are perfectly possible.  When the Terrans reached TL
> 12 the colonies could have used robots almost exclusively.

OK. Let\'s say for the moment that what you aregue is true/likely. Note that the
Terrans only reached TL/12 *at the end* of the wars ... *not* at the beginning
where the population growth would have had to have been. They were TL/10 at the
beginning and TL/11 for most of it. The cost of such facilities compared to
their utility would seem to be tremendously negative (unless, of course, you
make the assumption that all Traveller prices are hopelessly too high -- and
that Terrans were able to produce these things at much lower unit costs than
anyone before or since ... with robot factories that the Vilani never seem to
have used. Ergo, the Terrans can outproduce the Vilani and need no excessive
social cost as would result from the sort of "solution" that Tuber colonies
propose) and counterproductive. It also would require a totalitarian society
of a degree that the Terran Confederation is never described as being - I
cannot see normal humans accepting this sort of program as "normal" and, in any
case, as a Teacher, I do not believe that I would want to have anything to do
with any society where children are substantially raised and educated by
robots. Think of the long term socialisation problems alone!

So, your "solution" assumes Tech that isn\'t available until too late ... and
the implications of the "solution" make said "solution" unnecessary anyway.

Phil McGregor


