  {
    'body' => 'Summary:

Phil and I disagree about Terran population growth.  I argue that
reproductive technology is not inconsistent with existing Traveller canon,
indeed can even be considered as being implied.  I also argue that the
primary factors in a rapidly expanding population would be cultural not
technological.

----

>But such (artificial wombs) are not mentioned anywhere in Traveller
material.
>Sure, you *can* assume that they are available ... however, *if* they were
of significance,
>surely they would have been mentioned *somewhere* previously.

Well, major mills aren\'t mentioned in Roman literature and inscriptions, but
they existed and ground a large proportion of the grain.  And for a long time
very few civilian vehicles were published in Traveller, most equipment was
military, etc.  The absence of something just indicates that no one wrote
about it.  Hey, look at cargo containers.  Not mentioned at all until MTJ 3,
when they became \'canon\'.  (I wrote that one, along with grashfalt and quite
a few others.)

Personally, I assumed that artificial wombs were common well before I read
any Bujold.  (I just like her terminology better.)  I have several friends
who would cheerfully mortgage their houses for one (major morning sickness,
several miscarriages...).  Given Traveller\'s equality between the sexes, yet
nature\'s work-split, this always seemed an implied development, especially
when women work in high-risk occupations.  (For example, nurses and
schoolteachers have higher miscarriage rates than other occupations.)  In
fact, back when we were playing Classic Traveller one of the female players
insisted on them (rather than bench her character for nine months)!

It is true that nothing is mentioned in the tech tables.  But note that we
already have whole-animal cloning (sheep), and we can do genetic engineering
(tech 14).  Personally, I figure that we are looking at a bio-engineering
problem - pump in enough money and effort and we can crack it.  After all, by
tech 10 Traveller has cyrogenic suspension, cancer cures, growth
quickening... all related to genetics and cell development.

>ideas such as the Sparklers which, I presume, got them dumped by GDW at the
end
>(at least partly?).

Actually, no.  At least, not according to either DGP or GDW.


>But, as a Teacher, I would suggest that this is the *least* part of raising
>kids (well, not seriously ... I\'m sure any parents out there wouldn\'t agree
>with mee). The problem is, regardless of how you look at it, how safe can
>non-AI robots be around small children? I suggest that few (if any) parents
>would allow them to do anything much re *raising* the kid ... and there are
>already labour saving devices aplenty that reduce housework etc. *right
now*.
>No, robotic nannies are an expensive, and probably unnecessary, addition.

Why use a robotic nanny?  Playing with your kids is the fun part.  Use the
robot to do the boring jobs.  Housework takes a tremendous amount of time,
when you add it up, even with labour-saving devices.  Cooking, cleaning, etc
take me many hours a week, anyway, and I don\'t have any kids living with me
right now.  As to safety around small children, that argument has,
historically, been used for power tools, spin driers, and many other
labour-saving appliances.  Design in good safeguards (eg. robot doesn\'t clean
while living creature is in room).




>> Personally, I visualize a Terran colony as being a place where _everyone_
>> (married or not) is socially expected to raise children.  Families are
large,
>> with the older children helping out.  Because there is a lot of
automation,
>> most workplaces are safe enough for children, and there is no social
stigma
>> attached to bringing a child to work; more importantly, there is no social
>> stigma attached to devoting yourself full-time to childrearing.
Childrearing
>> (in a couple) is a responsibility of both parents, not primarily the
woman.
>> Children are supported by the state; in fact, there are probably economic
>> incentives that make childrearing \'profitable\' and penalize childless
people.

>But there is no justification for this.

Nor reason against it.  There is simply nothing written on daily life in the
Terran Confederation.  This is my view.  (OK, one of my views - I figure the
Terran Confederation had a _lot_ of different cultures.)

>In fact, everything we have for
>Traveller from the word go assumes male/female equality in all fields.

Exactly.  That\'s what I was saying.  Reread my post.

>since robotic child-care is needlessly dangerous and (I suspect) excessively
>expensive, that\'s not an option.

See above re robotic nannies.

>It still boils down to how many children people will want to have ...

True.  I\'m trying to come up with a culture/society that will make them want
to have lots of kids, and make it easy for them to have lots.

>Assuming that present day social trends continue, no-one is going to stand
for that sort of time
>consuming effort ... and even with day care and the like, kids still take a
>hell of a lot of effort. That\'s the way the trend is now, and there is no
>reasonable expectation that it will change

Depends on the reason for the trend.  One reason families are getting smaller
is that people have less time (2-3 jobs, longer hours, etc.).  Change that
trend and there will be a corresponding change in birth rate.  Hey, it
happened that way here in the Great Depression - people put off having kids
until they could support them.  Also note that we spend more money on
ourselves than previous generations - but this trend is also beginning to
alter.  Leaving aside issues like sterility (presumed solved by the medical
tech we\'re talking about) we should be considering cultural values.

I think that removing the economic constraints will do a lot to increase
family size.  This happened in the U.S. with the G.I. Bill; it is happening
right now in developing countries with some aid projects.  If you subsidize
kids, more people will have more kids.  (In fact, some of my students are
trying for a second child, because with two kids they get enough welfare to
afford their own apartment.)

>the fact that women can now
>control their own fertility and have their own careers mean that being a
>homemaker is increasingly *not* No 1 in their priorities ... at least, not
in Oz.

Nor here (Canada).  But notice that with my assumptions women are not
(necessarily) homemakers.  Also note that with a donated egg a man could go
out and have a baby made and raise the child.



