    'body' => '> From: jlockett@hanszen.rice.edu (Joseph L Lockett)
> Subject: Teaching Machines & Terran Pop
>
> Phillip McGregor <aspqrz@sydney.DIALix.oz.au> argues:

> Another bald-faced assertion presented as incontrovertible fact.  Actually,
> Phillip, the asteroid-ship "Rock" is described as TL9 (Ad6, p25).  One could
> just as easily argue that the memory-implant device is of the same tech level.
> It\'s not mentioned, and therefore we can\'t be sure about it.  Gee, uncertainty
> is a horrid thing, isn\'t it?  Makes you listen to possibly different
> opinions....

Yes, believe it or not, I do (listen). And, as it also says that the Professor
did his original research on Regina (TL/10) and later on Paya (TL/9) there may
well be something in it. I still remain unconvinced that there is a difference
between what the Prof\'s machine does and partial memory dupe. And, since Miller
et al aren\'t saying, we\'ll just have to say that either version is possible.
However, the Imperium is still TL/15, and the Prof may have been doing "cutting
edge" research ... after all, it is implied in a number of places that the all
encompassing world TL is only a general reference ... even disallowing the
way its handled in "World Builder\'s Handbook". And, for the sake of argument,
I\'ll even agree that the whole GDW TL system is, and has always been, a crock -
and a useless one, at that ... so it\'s quite possible that what the Imperium
*claims* is high tech may well not be (sorry, more conspiracy stuff here! ;-} )

> You aren\'t a Christian fundamentalist/Biblican literalist, are you Phillip?

No! And, you\'ll note, I am not necessarily assuming that anything said by GDW
is gospel. In fact, the whole point of this argument is that GDW "canon" has
inconsistencies and flaws in it!

As for what it says in Solomani and Aslan (deleted for brevity), well, I don\'t
dispute that it makes internal sense (without having seen the whole book). But
so (allegedly ... many would dispute it) does "Survival Margin" and TNE. And,
even if it does seem like fundamentalist ranting, surely something so
unprecedented (and, OK, I spose I *am* making an assumption here that it *is*
unprecedented) would have been mentioned in some of the other material that we
have that has been done by Miller/Chadwick/Nilsen *and* Fugate/DGP *if* it was
something that they approved of? Which is, I spose, neither here nor there
anyhow. I *personally*, FWIW, do not believe that it is supportable based on
what we know of Traveller tech from other sources or based on what we are told
about the Solomani from other sources ... and there seems to be the evidence
of GDW dumping DGP (note *seems*) to indicate that they weren\'t happy with
some of the things they were doing (and, sure, GDW didn\'t do any better, so its
a moot point ... happy?).

> On the same note, Phillip, I note that your much-vaunted MegaTraveller
> Referee\'s Companion notes, on p. 28, that Medical Technology allows "limb
> regeneration" at TL9, and "growth quickening" at TL10.  (Hell, along with
> "nerve refusion" at TL11).  What more is needed for "artifical wombs" which
> produce new infants rather than copies/clones of existing full-grown
> individuals?

Which still leaves us with what I believe is the problem of teaching and
raising them. On that we have a disagreement that isn\'t as simply solved - even
if we grant the above which, for the sake of argument, let us assume. There is
some justification for this, but I do not agree that you have a case for memory
dupe.

> p. 35 of the same book mentions how "in -2389 the Terran Confederation Navy
> commissioned a line of mass-produced tech level 12 robots as support staff
> for military personnel.  These were not warbots as we know them today.  A
> few of the robots were expert medical robots or served as administrative
> support, but most were heavy-duty, hard-working construction robots, used
> to build temporary installations for advanced bases."  Sounds like they
> were a bit more capable than you give them credit for.

No. I have no problem with the above. I just question whether you would want a
construction robot to look after a newborn baby? I know that *I* wouldn\'t.

> You are welcome, Phillip, to build your own Interstellar Wars campaign any
> way you like.  Just don\'t be so cock-sure of yourself that you try to make
> everyone else play the same way.

Have I ever said I required anyone to? I may be cocksure (and I would simply
say "well prepared" FWIW), but I\'ve never made that particular claim!

Phil McGregor

