    'body' => '> From: "Edgar W. Francis, IV" <gar@ucla.edu>
> Subject: Re: Vilani medical tech
>
> At 05:29 AM 24/03/96 -0500, you wrote:

> First of all, every indication is that Vilani medical science is *still*
> lagging behind, and it\'s not that hard to explain:  the Vilani just don\'t
> value doctors.  As the culture evolved on Vland, food preparers held the
> real keys to power, and any sort of doctor was just a technician to take
> care of bleeding, broken bones, etc.  As they encountered other worlds, the
> anmount of technical knowledge they had to acquire was greater, but that
> doensn\'t necessarily mean that their status increased any.  Imagine how many
> people would go to medical school in the U.S. if, after you got out, you got
> about the same pay and societal status as a high school teacher.  Not too
> many, I\'d wager.

Actually, though I\'m not sure that you\'re right about the "present" (i.e. c
1100, Imperial, say), you *are* right, come to think of it (or more likely than
not) ... there is a statement *somewhere* to the effect that the Vilani always
considered the potential effects of tech (esp., IIRC, *medical* tech) before
they release it ... sometimes, it is implied, for generations, perhaps even
hundreds of years. This is actually a good explanation ... though it needs a
little more work. You could, for example, also assume that the Vilani *had* the
tech to deal with Terran diseases ... back in hi-security labs back on Vland or
some of the interior sectors, and didn\'t (or were slow to) release it when it
was needed. This may well explain the evident fact that some of the Vilani
dominated worlds more or less went over to the Solomani ... perhaps the failure
of the Vilani to "give a damn" meant that they welcomed the terrans because
*they* seemed to?

Phil McGregor

> From: Rob_Prior@nynet.nybe.north-york.on.ca (Rob Prior)
> Subject: Re: Babies (again)
>
> >as a Teacher, I do not believe that I would want to have anything to do
> >with any society where children are substantially raised and educated by
> >robots. Think of the long term socialisation problems alone!
>
> But as a teacher, imagine a school where robots handle all the routine
> gruntwork, leaving you free to concentrate on your students.  I know I spend
> nearly half of my time dealing with non-kid issues (in spite of what the
> Ontario Minister of Education thinks).

Yep, I can sympathise with that. Of course, tho you have a *definite* point,
just consider this ... some damn bureacrat somewhere is going to figure, "Well,
those lazy so-and-so\'s have all this extra time on their hands that they\'re
probably wasting, so lets demand that they fill in these extra forms ..." ...
and, bang goes all the "extra" time you had, for all of five seconds, no doubt!

Phil

> From: Rob_Prior@nynet.nybe.north-york.on.ca (Rob Prior)
> Subject: Re: Babies
>
> Summary:
>
> Phil and I disagree about Terran population growth.  I argue that
> reproductive technology is not inconsistent with existing Traveller canon,
> indeed can even be considered as being implied.  I also argue that the
> primary factors in a rapidly expanding population would be cultural not
> technological.
>
> ----
>
> Well, major mills aren\'t mentioned in Roman literature and inscriptions, but
> they existed and ground a large proportion of the grain.  And for a long time
> very few civilian vehicles were published in Traveller, most equipment was
> military, etc.  The absence of something just indicates that no one wrote
> about it.  Hey, look at cargo containers.  Not mentioned at all until MTJ 3,
> when they became \'canon\'.  (I wrote that one, along with grashfalt and quite
> a few others.)

True, and fair enough. I\'ll go along with that.

I even agree about cloning. I *still* think that the limitation is the lack of
a memory transfer facility (and we disagree with this, too) ... *and* the
economic limitations, which hasn\'t been considered fully (cost of robots and
all that).

> Why use a robotic nanny?  Playing with your kids is the fun part.  Use the
> robot to do the boring jobs.  Housework takes a tremendous amount of time,
> when you add it up, even with labour-saving devices.  Cooking, cleaning, etc
> take me many hours a week, anyway, and I don\'t have any kids living with me
> right now.  As to safety around small children, that argument has,
> historically, been used for power tools, spin driers, and many other
> labour-saving appliances.  Design in good safeguards (eg. robot doesn\'t clean
> while living creature is in room).

Cost is still a problem.

> Nor reason against it.  There is simply nothing written on daily life in the
> Terran Confederation.  This is my view.  (OK, one of my views - I figure the
> Terran Confederation had a _lot_ of different cultures.)

Aha! But a little bird informs me that there *will* be, for Trav4! We\'ll see
how it turns out, shall we?

> >It still boils down to how many children people will want to have ...
>
> True.  I\'m trying to come up with a culture/society that will make them want
> to have lots of kids, and make it easy for them to have lots.

And that\'s where the problem is. Not impossible ... and, perhaps, it *will* be
the case in the above project (and *official* Trav4 one, but don\'t ask me
details of who and what!) ... but, FWIW, I suspect that it would take some
*real* mental contortions to do so.

As for the rest <snipped> re reasons for small families at present. I accept
and understand what you\'re getting at, I just am not convinced that you\'re on
the right track. We\'ll have to wait 50 years or so and see, I spose (if the Mad
Cow disease doesn\'t get us first!).

Phil

